1. e4 g6 {The Modern Defense. The opening is also coined as Robatsch Defense after the legendary Austrian player Karl Robatsch. Black fianchettoes the [f8]-bishop to [g7] to keep in contact with the central [d4]-square. Every opening has its own advantages and drawbacks. Here, the drawback is that we concede the center, and White gets comfortable space. On the other hand, the plus point is that we can undermine it with ...[c5] or ...[e5] breaks in the later stage, like in the King's Indian. The spirit is the same in both these openings. In addition to the above points, many strong players use this opening as their favorite weapon in rapid and blitz games to muddy the waters, steering the game toward unbalanced positions. To name a few, starting from the former World Champion Magnus Carlsen and Grandmaster Hikaru Nakamura to everyone in the top 100 has at least used it a couple of times in their life. Practically, I would rate this opening as very interesting, with many setups and plans for both sides. (Some people get confused with Modern and Pirc as both of them resemble the same in many instances. To clear the air, Pirc is with an early ...Nf6 1.e4 d6 3.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 followed by the ...[c6] and ...[b5] advance and the Modern is ...[Bg7], ...[d6], ...[a6], ...[b5] and only later developing the knight to [f6] – though against some systems inside the course we prefer to develop the knight to [f6] early. Having said that, the ideas are more or less similar in both these openings: to create a flank attack with either ...[a6] and ...[b5] or ...[c6] and ...[b5]. In case this plan is too slow, we have alternative ideas like challenging the center with ...[d6] and ...[e5] after ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] like in the King's Indian. Likewise, ...[d6], ...[Nd7], and ...[c5] ideas also exist in some cases. People who have King's Indian, Grünfeld, and Dragon in their arsenal will find it likable as here, too, we develop our bishop to [g7].)} *

