1. e4 g6 2. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Yes, this idea exists in many positions. This is what AlphaZero has brought to the table. White aims to target [g6] with an early [h5] advance, sometimes as early as move 2. Harry is in a hurry, trying to exploit our first move without even developing pieces properly – and that is simply not good! This option is very popular in Titled Tuesday events, bullet, and blitz games, where quick attacks can catch opponents off guard. However, in a classical setting, this plan is not effective enough to create a serious disruption in our camp. With precise play, Black can neutralize the attack and take over the initiative.} d5 $1 ({Adhering to the theory of flank attack must be met by counterplay in the center. Apart from} 2... d5 {, Black has other moves as well, like 2...Nf6 , not allowing White to push the h-pawn further. Play will continue with 3.e5 Nh5 4.Be2 , and so on.}) 3. exd5 Bg7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d5]} ({The immediate} 3... Qxd5 {is also possible.} 4. Nc3 Qd6 5. d4 {and we get into a weird version of the Scandinavian. The text move is clever; by the next move, when we grab on [d5] and counter [Nc3] with ...[Qd6], White does not have the [d4] advance. ( For Gambit lovers 3...c6 is also very interesting. )}) 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5] Retaining the [d5]-pawn.} Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} 5. Bc4 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd7b6] Coordinating all the forces towards the [d5]-pawn.} 6. d4 Nb6 7. Bb3 (7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Be2 Bf5 {resumes the threat of ...[Nxd5] and Black regains the pawn back.}) 7... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 8. a4 Nbxd5 ({We can include} 8... h5 {as well before capturing the pawn on [d5] so as not to allow White to advance Harry.}) 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. h5 Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ge8c8] The queen is nicely placed on [d6] with ideas like ...[Be6] and ...[O-O-O]. We also have some mysterious maneuvers like ...[Qa6] controlling the [a6]-[f1] diagonal, not allowing White to castle short.} 11. c3 Be6 $10 (11... Be6 12. h6 {will be met by} Bf6 {and Black's position is rock solid.}) *

