1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8] Finachettoing the bishop to [g2] is another option for White. Grandmaster Quesada Perez played this against me in the chess24 Banter Blitz. Those were the good old days of Banter Blitz. Petition to chess.com to start those fun series. : Coming back to the position, White's setup is simple – bishop to [g2], knight to [e2], castle, pawn to [d3], bishop to [e3], pawn to [f4], queen to [d2], and so on. The drawback is that it is slow, and White has no proper central control over the strategically important square [d4].} c5 {[%csl Rd4] Stopping d4 and it is more or less going to transpose to Closed Sicilian kind of positions: 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 d6 3.g3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 .} (3... e5 {is another viable option, aiming for a solid central grip and restricting White's pawn breaks. Both plans are equally playable, and the choice depends on the type of middlegame Black prefers.}) 4. Bg2 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] This position can also arise from 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.g3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 . Since White struggles to achieve [d4], Black's position is comfortable. The plans are straightforward – develop naturally, control the center, and prepare thematic breaks, depending on White's setup. Playing the Closed Sicilian as Black isn't a hard task here, as White's usual central expansion is restricted.} 5. Nge2 d6 6. d3 {The starting position of the Closed Sicilian with [g3]. Here, Black has many plans.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (6... e6 {followed by ...[Nge7] is one plan. 6...e5 and ...[Nge7] is another one. The text move prepares to expand on the queenside with ...[b5].}) 7. O-O b5 8. f4 Bd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gd7]} ({The immediate} 8... Nf6 {is a mistake due to} 9. e5 {, and Black loses a piece. So it is important to first protect the [c6]-knight before bringing the [g8]-knight to [f6].}) ({Another option for Black is to kick the c3-knight immediately by} 8... b4 {, but White can reroute it to a better square after} 9. Nd5 e5 10. Ne3 {followed by the [f5] thrust.}) 9. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Ge2g3] This is one of White's plans to expand on the kingside with [g4], [Ng3], and so on.} Nf6 (9... b4 {is also possible, but} 10. Nd5 e6 11. Ne3 Nge7 12. f5 {leads to a different story.}) 10. g4 O-O ({Now} 10... b4 {is once again possible, as White cannot reroute with [Nd5]-[e3] like in the earlier cases. So it's an equally effective alternative. White will reply with} 11. Nb1 {followed by [Nd2]-[f3] and so on.}) 11. Ng3 b4 12. Nce2 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7b5,Gb5d4,Gg7a1] This key maneuver has to be noted, which improves Black's position of pieces. The plan is ...[Nc7]-[b5]-[d4] or ...[a5]-[a4]-[a3] and so on.} 13. f5 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3]} ({There's nothing wrong with the direct} 13... Nc7 {and then ...[a5]-[a4].}) 14. Rb1 a4 15. Kh2 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7b5] Black has brought all the pieces on the queenside. Meanwhile, it is not clear what are White's ideas on the kingside} 16. Bf4 a3 {Since White has removed the bishop from [c1], we penetrate.} 17. b3 Nb5 $15 {[%cal Gb5c3] And the knight is invading.} *

