1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Pinning the [f3]-knight creates additional pressure on the [d4]-pawn – the advantages of not committing to ...[Nf6]. Now we can counter the center with ...[c5] or ...[Nc6] next.} 5. Be2 {White has to unpin it; otherwise, Black's ...[c5] will become too powerful. This is by far the top choice, according to the lichess database.} Bxf3 ({Clarifying matters.} 5... Nc6 {is also possible, but it gives White some extra options like} 6. Nbd2 {.}) 6. Bxf3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. Be3 e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. d5 Nd4 9. Bxd4 {White concedes the bishop pair in order to corner the [d4]-pawn, but it is not easy to do so.} exd4 10. Nd2 {With the idea of [Nb3] next, attacking the [d4]-pawn, but Black is in time to regroup their pieces to meet this idea.} Nf6 11. Nb3 Nd7 12. Nxd4 O-O $10 {[%cal Gd8f6]} ({Next on the cards is ...Qf6, and there is huge pressure along the h8-a1 diagonal. The immediate} 12... Qf6 {is also possible.} 13. Nb5 O-O 14. Nc3 a6 {followed by ...[b5] and so on.}) *

