1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Pinning the [f3]-knight creates additional pressure on the [d4]-pawn – the advantages of not committing to ...[Nf6]. Now we can counter the center with ...[c5] or ...[Nc6] next.} 5. Be2 {White has to unpin it; otherwise, Black's ...[c5] will become too powerful. This is by far the top choice, according to the lichess database.} Bxf3 ({Clarifying matters.} 5... Nc6 {is also possible, but it gives White some extra options like} 6. Nbd2 {.}) 6. Bxf3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. Be3 e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. d5 Nd4 9. O-O c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Ge5] Now White is forced to trade the [d5]-pawn.} 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Nc3 Rb8 $1 {[%csl Rb2] Our usual reply once the b-file is open.} 12. Rb1 a5 {[%csl Rb4] Not allowing easy expansion for White on the queenside.} 13. a3 Ne7 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 O-O 16. b5 Nc8 $10 {[%cal Gc8b6] Next on the cards is ...[Nb6], stabilizing the game. The computer often overestimates these positions, but once you let it run for a longer time, it understands that White has not made much progress.} *

