1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 {With the plan of forming a Sämisch setup like [Be3], [f3], [Qd2], and so on.} Nf6 $1 (5... Nc6 6. d5 Nce7 7. Ng3 {and it is not easy for Black to strike with ...[f5] in the desired way – an inferior King's Indian position for Black.}) 6. f3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2]} exd4 $1 (6... O-O 7. d5 {here is a different story compared to the 6.d5 a5 variation, as now Black has castled and White has targets with [h4]-[h5].}) 7. Nxd4 O-O {[%cal Gd6d5] Black's next idea is to strike with ...[d5] to break the bind created by the [c4] and [e4]-pawns as soon as possible before White stabilizes.} 8. Be2 d5 {Bam! A strong novelty that leads to concrete play.} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 c6 {[%csl Rd4,Rd5]} 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 {Yes, Black is a pawn down but has tremendous activity and also pressure along the [h8]-[a1] diagonal. The weaknesses created by the pawn move to [f3] also bring us compensation along with the above-said factors.} 12. Be3 Be6 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} ({The immediate} 12... Bxb2 {is not good due to} 13. Rb1 Bg7 14. O-O {. Although Black has regained the pawn back, we are unable to get rid of the dominant knight on [d5] by} Be6 {due to} 15. Rxb7 {.}) 13. Qd2 Bxd5 14. exd5 Ne7 {[%csl Rd5]} 15. Rd1 {[%csl Gd5]} (15. O-O-O Nf5 16. Bf2 Bh6 17. f4 Qc7+ {followed by ...[Bxf4] regains the pawn.}) 15... Qd6 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf8d8] Surrounding the [d5]-pawn.} 16. O-O (16. Bf4 Be5 {is fine.}) 16... Rfd8 17. Bc4 Nf5 {[%csl Re3]} 18. Bf2 Rac8 {[%csl Rc4]} 19. Bb3 Be5 {[%cal Gd6h2]} 20. g3 Qf6 $10 {[%cal Ge5b2] Radiating so much activity. Finally, Black will regain the pawn since [b2] is under immense pressure.} (20... Qf6 21. Rb1 {protects the pawn, but after} Nd4 22. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 23. Kg2 Re8 {, White has no advantage given the opposite-colored bishops. The pawn on [d5] is neutralized, and Black has a good grip on the dark squares.}) *

