1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 {With the plan of forming a Sämisch setup like [Be3], [f3], [Qd2], and so on.} Nf6 $1 (5... Nc6 6. d5 Nce7 7. Ng3 {and it is not easy for Black to strike with ...[f5] in the desired way – an inferior King's Indian position for Black.}) 6. f3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2]} exd4 $1 (6... O-O 7. d5 {here is a different story compared to the 6.d5 a5 variation, as now Black has castled and White has targets with [h4]-[h5].}) 7. Nxd4 O-O {[%cal Gd6d5] Black's next idea is to strike with ...[d5] to break the bind created by the [c4] and [e4]-pawns as soon as possible before White stabilizes.} 8. Be3 c6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 9. Be2 Re8 {[%cal Ge8e1]} ({The immediate} 9... d5 {is inferior, as after} 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. e5 Ne8 12. f4 {, White dominates. After the text move, the breakthrough with ...[d5] will be more effective.}) 10. Bf2 d5 {What else? :} 11. exd5 cxd5 12. O-O Nc6 {This position actually arises from the King's Indian: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Be2 e5 7.Be3 exd4 8.Nxd4 Re8 9.f3 c6 10.Bf2 d5 11.cxd5 cxd5 12.O-O Nc6 and here we are.} 13. c5 {[%cal Ge2b5] With the idea of [Bb5].} Bd7 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gg7f8,Gf8c5] Next, ...[Bf8] is on the agenda.} 14. Ndb5 {[%csl Rb7,Re8][%cal Gb5d6,Gd6b7,Gd6e8]} Re7 $1 {Prohylaxsis against the [Nd6] jump.} 15. Re1 a6 16. Nd6 Be6 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6][%cal Ge7b7,Gd5d4] Next on the cards is ...[d4] since White's knight does not control the [d4]-square anymore. To illustrate that, 17...d4 is not a pawn sacrifice since after 18.Bxd4 Nxd4 19.Qxd4 Nd5 20.Qd2 Nxc3 21.bxc3 Qa5 , White is in trouble.} 17. Na4 {[%cal Ga4b6]} Qf8 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8] Making way for the rook on [a8].} 18. Nb6 Rd8 {[%cal Gf6e8]} 19. Qa4 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6][%cal Gd6b7]} Ne8 $1 {[%csl Rd6] Precise, to get rid of the piece on [d6].} 20. Nxb7 Rxb7 21. Qxc6 Rc7 22. Qa4 Rxc5 $1 {Thanks to this tactical trick, everything ends up smoothly.} 23. Rad1 (23. Bxc5 Qxc5+ {loses the knight on [b6].}) 23... Qd6 {[%cal Gd6b6]} 24. Nc4 Qc6 25. Qb4 Bf8 $1 {[%csl Rb4,Rg1][%cal Gf8c5,Gf8b4] Tactics all over. :} 26. Qb6 Rc8 27. Qxc6 R5xc6 28. Ne5 Rc2 $10 {And once again, Black's activity is tremendous.} *

