1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3]} ({Maintaining the tension. This option is the second-rated move in terms of number of games played. The first one, which is played in high numbers, is} 5. d5 {.}) 5... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Adding more attack towards the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Bg5 {Played in a couple of games, but it is nothing special for White.} Nge7 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Nd5 h6 {[%csl Rg5] Again, we have to get rid of the pin as soon as possible.} 9. Bf6 (9. Be3 {does not make much sense, and we can react with} Bg4 {, with ...[Nd4] invasions floating in the air.}) 9... Bxf6 10. Nxf6+ Kf8 11. Qxd8+ Nxd8 12. Nxe5 {White has won a pawn, but the knight on [f6] is stuck and can be chased.} Kg7 {[%csl Rf6]} 13. Ned7 Ne6 {[%csl Rd7,Rf6][%cal Gh8d8]} 14. O-O-O Rd8 15. g3 {[%cal Gf1h3]} Nc6 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gc6d4]} (15... Nc6 {Threatening ...Ncd4 to trap the knight. If White lacks ambition and goes for a repetition with} 16. Bh3 Ng5 17. Bg2 Ne6 {, a draw with Black can't be a poor outcome.}) (15... Nf8 {is another option, but Black has to be ready to defend a passive position after, for example,} 16. Bh3 Ng8 17. e5 Nxf6 18. exf6+ Kg8 19. Rd5 Bxd7 20. Rhd1 a5 21. Bxd7 Nh7 22. Bh3 Rxd5 23. Rxd5 Nxf6 24. Rb5 b6 25. c5 Rb8 {.}) 16. Bh3 Ng5 {[%csl Rh3]} 17. Bg2 Ne6 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gc6d4]} 18. Rd5 Nb4 $132 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gb4a2] White drops the [a2]-pawn, which balances the material.} *

