1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White's next move is castle, and then [e5] will already be a big threat with the rook coming to [d1].} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2] There is nothing wrong with castling and then playing ...[Nc6], but I prefer this move, as it aligns with the spirit of the position, constantly putting pressure on White's center. Next, ...[Bg4] is coming, and the [d4]-pawn will be under pressure.} 6. e5 {Direct but ineffective.} dxe5 7. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Re5] Cornering the [e5]-pawn.} 8. e6 Bxe6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ng5 {[%csl Re6,Rg4][%cal Gg5e6,Ge2g4,Ge2e6]} (10. Qxe6 Nge5 {is nothing special for White, and 10.O-O is faced by 10...Qd6 with long castle. In both these options, Black is slightly better.}) 10... Nd4 {Only move, otherwise everything is falling apart.} 11. Qxg4 Nxc2+ 12. Ke2 (12. Kf1 {loses to} Qd3+ 13. Qe2 O-O-O {and bye-bye to the [a1]-rook.}) 12... Qd7 $132 {[%csl Ra1,Re2][%cal Gd7b5] The [a1]-rook is ours and can be taken anytime. Now ...[Qb5]+ is a big threat. White has to be careful here.} *

