1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White's next move is castle, and then [e5] will already be a big threat with the rook coming to [d1].} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2] There is nothing wrong with castling and then playing ...[Nc6], but I prefer this move, as it aligns with the spirit of the position, constantly putting pressure on White's center. Next, ...[Bg4] is coming, and the [d4]-pawn will be under pressure.} 6. O-O Bg4 {[%cal Gg4e2,Gc6d4] White's center is under huge pressure now. First the [e4]-pawn and now the [d4]-pawn.} 7. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4] One of the reasons in this direction not to commit [Nc3] is that White can strengthen the [d4]-pawn by the [c3] push.} e5 {[%csl Rd4] Bestowing more pressure on [d4].} 8. Rd1 O-O {[%csl Rb1,Rc1] White has stabilized the center, but now the question is how to get their pieces out, which are sleeping on [b1] and [c1], without harming the center control.} 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7d4] Again the [d4]-pawn is the target.} 11. Be3 Kh8 $132 {[%csl Rb1,Rd4][%cal Gf7f5] Preparing the key move ...[f5]. Black has good counterplay here. The knight is still stuck on [b1].} *

