1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. d5 {White releases the tension but does disturb our knight.} Nb8 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ge7e6,Gg7a1] Black has wasted one move with this knight back and forth, but now the [g7]-bishop is open, and we can undermine the [d5]-pawn with ...[c6] or ...[e6].} 8. c4 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} 9. h3 (9. Nc3 Nbd7 {or 9...Nfd7 , and anyway, at some point, White needs to play [h3] to get rid of the pin.}) 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nfd7 {[%cal Gg7a1]} (10... Nfd7 {I like this more than ...Nbd7, as it paves the way for the g7-bishop. For example, if} 11. Nc3 {, we have extra options like} Bxc3 {, shattering White's pawn structure. Black's main idea is ...[Ne5] now.}) 11. Bc2 Nb6 {[%csl Rc4]} 12. Qe2 N8d7 13. Nc3 c6 $10 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6d5,Gc8c1]} ({Here,} 13... Bxc3 {is not good, as the knights are really far away, and White has a free attack with [f4] later. The text move is stronger, and next on the agenda is ...[Rc8] and create play on the c-file.}) *

