1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Although ...[Bg4] is not such a big deal now and can be met by [Nbd2], in the future, it might be available for Black; hence, White plans to prevent it for a lifetime.} e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. Nbd2 a5 $1 ({The direct} 8... Nd7 {is also possible to target the [d4]-pawn, as White's pieces piled up on the d-file lose the queen support. White will have to play} 9. Nb3 {. So the text move is even more clever since next the idea is ...[Nd7] and White can no longer play [Nb3] due to ...[a4].}) 9. Re1 (9. Bc2 Nh5 {or 9...Nd7 and again, White has to answer questions from the [d4]-pawn.}) 9... Nd7 {[%csl Rd4]} 10. d5 Ne7 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black has a better version of the King's Indian. The ...[f5] breakthrough is coming next.} *

