1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Against invasions on [g4].} d5 $1 {[%csl Re4] A nice shortcut, which is efficient at the same time. Black uses White's slow play by striking in the center.} 7. e5 Ne4 8. Nxe4 {White captures the annoying knight immediately and tries to corner the [e4]-pawn.} dxe4 9. Ng5 {[%csl Re4]} c5 $1 {Striking in time.} 10. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4]} Nc6 11. dxc5 Qc7 {[%csl Re5]} 12. Nxe4 Nxe5 13. Be2 Bf5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8d8] And if the knight moves, our rook will come to [d8] followed by an invasion on [d3].} 14. Qc2 b6 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf5c2]} 15. cxb6 axb6 {[%cal Ge5c4,Gc7c6,Gf5c2] Black's activity is tremendous with ideas like ...[Nc4] and ...[Qc6] coming next. We have full compensation.} *

