1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. O-O a6 ({Another idea is} 6... Nc6 {followed by ...[e5], but there is a drawback. After} 7. d5 {, Black is forced to play} Ne5 {, which leads to doubled e-pawns following} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 {, and then White has this strong bishop move} 9. Bc4 {, not even allowing us to undermine the [d5]-pawn easily. It is unpleasant.}) ({Hence, I would like to include} 6... a6 {before placing the knight to [c6] so that Black can go back to [a7] as well when attacked. I must say it is a strange square but works concretely, as we can immediately challenge the [d5]-pawn with the ...[c6] thrust.}) 7. a4 {White prevents ...[b5] while also gaining space, aiming to restrict Black's counterplay on the queenside.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] This position has been tested in numerous games, each showcasing different plans and nuances for both sides.} 8. Be3 {One of the logical moves in this position.} e5 {[%csl Rd4] Time to challenge the center.} 9. d5 Ne7 {We get to some kind of King's Indian without the white pawn on [c4].} 10. Nd2 {[%cal Ga4a5] White is able to set up their pieces nicely, thanks to the bishop on [e3]. By this maneuver, White prevents ...[Ng4] and ...[f5] expansions.} b6 $1 {[%cal Gb6b5,Ra4a5] Black's idea of meeting [a5] with ...[b5] makes the ...[b6] setup particularly important, ensuring stability on the queenside. White has several possible continuations, but rather than attempting to analyze every single move, let's focus on the most logical and critical options.} 11. b4 {Expanding on the queenside is a key strategic theme for White in this position.} Bd7 12. Ncb1 {[%cal Gc2c4] Though retreating the knight to the first rank may look odd at first glance, it serves a clear purpose – facilitating the [c4] push. If White successfully executes [c4] followed by [Nc3], their queenside play gains significant momentum, making it difficult for Black to counter effectively. This maneuver is a key part of White's strategy, ensuring smooth expansion while keeping flexibility in piece placement. Black must react swiftly, either by challenging the queenside plan directly or by creating counterplay elsewhere on the board.} Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5] The best move. The knight is quite active there, compared to being on [e8], to facilitate ...[f5].} 13. a5 bxa5 14. Rxa5 f5 15. f3 c6 $132 {And now, it's complete chaos on the board! This is exactly the kind of dynamic, double-edged position we seek when playing the Modern or King's Indian.} *

