[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Tricky Systems: 4.Be2 – 6.O-O | Alternative 6...a6 7.a4 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B08"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2159115886768837"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. O-O a6 ({Another idea is} 6... Nc6 {followed by ...[e5], but there is a drawback. After} 7. d5 {, Black is forced to play} Ne5 {, which leads to doubled e-pawns following} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 {, and then White has this strong bishop move} 9. Bc4 {, not even allowing us to undermine the [d5]-pawn easily. It is unpleasant.}) ({Hence, I would like to include} 6... a6 {before placing the knight to [c6] so that Black can go back to [a7] as well when attacked. I must say it is a strange square but works concretely, as we can immediately challenge the [d5]-pawn with the ...[c6] thrust.}) 7. a4 {White prevents ...[b5] while also gaining space, aiming to restrict Black's counterplay on the queenside.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] This position has been tested in numerous games, each showcasing different plans and nuances for both sides.} 8. d5 Nb4 $1 {The drawback of White's [a4] is that they can no longer kick the knight on [b4] with [a3]. So we use this opportunity.} 9. a5 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga1a4]} e6 $1 {[%csl Rd5] Time to undermine the [d5]-pawn.} 10. Ra4 c5 11. dxc6 Nxc6 {[%csl Ra5]} 12. Be3 {[%cal Ge3b6]} Nxa5 13. e5 Nd7 14. Bg5 (14. exd6 b5 {followed by ...[Bb7] helps Black to coordinate the pieces. And 14.Qxd6 Nc6 points at the [e5]-pawn.}) 14... f6 15. exf6 Nxf6 $10 {[%cal Gc8d7] We have ...[Bd7] next, and Black is fine here.} *

