[Black "Fianchetto Setups: 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nge2 Nf6 5.g3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2159115886789318"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nge2 ({This is a better move order to reach the fianchetto setup, as} 4. g3 {gives a lot of options for Black.}) 4... Nf6 {Black aims for castle and a quick ...[e5].} 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 e5 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... exd4 {followed by ...[Nc6] is equally possible but might give an extra option for White after} 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {. The pawn structure is changed here.}) 8. Be3 {Thanks to the pawn on [h3], White doesn't need to worry about ...[Ng4].} exd4 {Now it's time to take on [d4].} 9. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gd7] Holding on to the knight on [c6].} 10. O-O Re8 {[%csl Re4] And now the [e4]-pawn is pressurized. Here, there are a couple of options for White.} 11. Re1 {The natural response.} Nxd4 $1 {This is the key idea to take note of.} 12. Bxd4 c5 13. Be3 Bc6 {[%csl Re4]} 14. Qd3 (14. Bf4 Re6 {is similar.}) 14... Re6 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Re4][%cal Gd8e8,Ge6d6] All these moves starting from 11...Nxd4 should be considered as a unit. Only thanks to this plan of ...[Re6] and ...[Qe8] Black is able to create counterplay.} 15. Rad1 Qe8 {[%csl Re4]} 16. f3 b5 $132 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga7a5] Black achieves good counterplay with ...[b4], ...[a5], and so on.} *

