1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Planning to castle long and whenever our knight moves away from [g8], they can insert [Bh6].} b5 {Continuing the flow of creating play on the queenside.} 6. a4 b4 7. Nd5 Nd7 $1 ({Only one amateur game in my database.} 7... a5 {has been played in most games but in fact, we don't need to protect the pawn, and taking it only helps us to get play along the b-file.}) 8. f3 (8. Nxb4 c5 {is strong, and White is collapsing along the [h8]-[a1] diagonal. For example,} 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. Bc4 a5 11. Na2 Bxb2 {or 11...Nxa4 brings us the pawn back.}) (8. Qxb4 {is met by} c6 9. Nc3 Rb8 {, when one of the two pawns, [d4] or [b2], will fall.}) 8... c5 (8... h6 {and then ...[c5] is also possible.}) 9. dxc5 Nxc5 $10 {[%cal Gg7b2] The [g7]-bishop becomes a monster now.} *

