[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2159115886822088"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be2 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White delays the [g1]-knight development for ideas like [h4]-[h5] or [Be3] and [Qd2] without having to worry about ...[Ng4] jumps.} Nf6 (4... a6 {is also possible, but I would like to not stick with one plan of ...[b5]; hence, I prefer development first so that we can adapt according to what the position needs, like ...[e5] or ...[c5] breaks, and so on.}) 5. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Gf2f4,Gh2h4] Keeping all the plans open, like [f4], [h4], [Qd2] followed by long castle, and so on.} O-O 6. Qd2 c5 $1 {Thanks to this pawn sacrifice, we create ample play.} 7. dxc5 (7. Nf3 {, holding on to the central pawn, is met by} Ng4 {. And 7.O-O-O is worse due to 7...cxd4 8.Bxd4 Nc6 .}) 7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc5 {Yes, White has captured a pawn, but on the other hand, Black gets huge counterplay due to our active pieces.} Nc6 {[%cal Gf6d7] One of the next ideas is ...[Nd7], attacking the bishop on [c5] and opening up the diagonal for the Dragon bishop on [g7] at the same time.} 10. Nf3 (10. Bb5 Nd7 11. Ba3 Nde5 {gives us counterplay as well.}) 10... Bg4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gg4e2,Gf6d7,Gg7a1]} 11. O-O Nd7 12. Be3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 (13. gxf3 Nd4 {neutralizes.}) 13... Nb6 {[%csl Rb2,Re3][%cal Gb6c4]} 14. Be2 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Na4 $10 {Black finally regains the pawn. Generally, the bishop pair is a strong asset in open positions, but in this case, White's weakened pawn structure on the queenside offers Black plenty of counterplay.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Defense"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.g4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B06"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2159115886842569"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh2h4] An interesting option to bring the bishop to [g2] in a dynamic manner.} Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. h4 {, and it is not easy for Black to coordinate the pieces. For instance, if} Nf6 {, then} 8. h5 gxh5 9. g5 {is really powerful, crushing Black. So, anyway, at some point, we need to develop our [b8]-knight to [d7] to push ...[c5].}) 6. h4 {The juicers are coming to haunt our kingside.} h6 (6... h6 {Just sticking to the groove to face} 7. h5 {with} g5 {.}) (6... h5 {is not effective here due to} 7. gxh5 Rxh5 {, and the difference is that White's bishop is on [f1] and not [g2]. White can continue with} 8. Nf3 {, [Ng5], [Be2], and, after the rook retreats, [h5].}) 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White's plan is very obvious: to castle long and continue the rampage on the kingside.} b5 8. O-O-O Ngf6 {[%csl Rg4]} 9. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3,Gg4]} Nb6 {Keeping an eye on the [c4]-square. One of the ideas is ...[b4] followed by ...[Nc4] when White's knight retreats to [e2], cutting off the connection of the [f1]-bishop with the [c4]-square.} 10. Nh3 {The knight cannot head to [e2] due to ...[Nc4].} (10. Bd3 {is another natural move, but now we have the nice plan of regrouping the other knight with} Nfd7 {, preparing ...[c5].}) 10... h5 $1 {Now that we have the [d7]-square for the [f6]-knight, we can challenge the pawn on [g4].} 11. gxh5 (11. g5 {only helps Black:} Nfd7 {and ...[c5] will happen in the near future.}) 11... Nxh5 12. Qf2 {[%csl Rg3] This move makes sense, as Black was planning to invade with ...[Ng3].} b4 {Black has to be quick in creating counterplay; otherwise, with our exposed king, we will certainly have some problems in the near future.} 13. Ne2 (13. Nb1 a5 14. Nd2 a4 {and the tables have turned in Black's favour as now our attack is faster on the queenside.}) 13... c5 {[%cal Gg7b2] This is the follow-up. Otherwise, the pawn push to [b4] would not make much sense.} 14. b3 {[%csl Rc4,Rc5] It is critical to stop ...[Nc4]. Now Black has to give an answer to the pressure around the [c5]-pawn.} Bxh3 $1 ({The direct} 14... c4 15. d5 Nd7 {(locks in the [c8]-bishop, and White also has [Nf4] ideas. With both their knights on [h3] and [e2], White can get rid of the blockade on [h5] the knight on [h5] and penetrate into the kingside. For all these reasons, we eliminate the [h3]-knight first.)}) 15. Rxh3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} (15... c4 {is not good here. With the white bishop on [f1], White can respond with} 16. d5 Nd7 {and} 17. Nd4 {and the [f1]-bishop will make a difference in contrast to the 15.Bxh3 line.}) 16. f4 (16. dxc5 Qa5 {is the point.}) 16... a5 $132 {[%cal Ga5a4] Next on the agenda is ...[a4] and Black obtains good counterplay.} *

