[GameId "2159115886871242"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Nf3 {This is a really unpleasant move order to trick us, as against 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be3 , we prefer 5...O-O 6.Qd2 c5 is a very interesting approach that I have advocated.} (5. Nf3 {With this move order, we cannot approach it in a similar way since we have committed to ...a6. The usual follow-up with} b5 {is the pretty common approach, but here it is slow, and White's attack is so powerful with [h4] and so on. Of course, we will analyze it a bit to understand why this is very strong for White to face ...[a6] and ...[b5] and why is White faster on the kingside.}) (5. Nf3 {So the question remains: how to face this annoying move order from White? After digging deep, I found that the} Nf6 {, ...[O-O], and ...[Nc6] plan to be the best.}) 5... Nf6 $1 ({➢ The best move in this position, avoiding} 5... b5 {altogether. The problem with 5...b5 is that after 6.h4 , Black is already in a tough spot. 6...Nf6 is the general response, but White has a strong resource here. (6...h5 7.Ng5 Nf6 8.Bd3! and Black suffers here. We have no proper counterplay. 8...O-O 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Ng4 11.e6 ± and Black's position is collapsing on the kingside. ) 7.h5! Nxh5 8.Ng5 , threatening [Rxh5]. 8...Nf6 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 and Black is in trouble, as once the knight drifts away from [f6], White can invade with [Nd5]. 11...Nh5 12.Nd5 Bxe5 13.g4 Nf6 14.Bg2 ± and Black has to take care of several threats from White on every move. Not a fun thing to do.}) ({➢} 5... Nd7 6. h4 Ngf6 7. Qe2 b5 (7... e5 8. O-O-O {±}) 8. e5 {+- .}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] The main critical plan. White is going to plant their bishop to [h6] next.} b5 {Since [h4] is no longer effective with our knight on [f6] already, we have to start the expansion on the queenside.} 7. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7]} O-O (7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 {followed by [e5] is annoying.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. Bd3 Nc6 {leads to the same story.}) 8... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5] The critical and the best direction Black has to go for.} 9. e5 (9. Nd5 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Ng4 {followed by ...[e6] kicks the knight back.}) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Rh6]} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Arriving at a critical juncture. This position was discussed in a book of GM Parimarjan Negi in the Grandmaster Repertoire series.} 12. O-O-O b4 {[%csl Rc3]} 13. h3 bxc3 (13... Ngxe5 {is a mistake due to} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Qe3 {and the threats along the open d-file trouble Black.}) 14. Qxc3 Nxf2 {[%csl Rd1,Rh1][%cal Gf2h1,Gf2d1]} 15. Be4 Bb7 $1 (15... Nxe4 {is possible, and play will continue after} 16. Qxc6 Qe8 17. Qxe4 {and so on, but the text move is the cleanest played in one correspondence game.}) 16. Bxc6 Nxd1 17. Rxd1 Qb8 {[%csl Gb7,Gb8] Protecting the [b7]-bishop.} 18. e6+ f6 19. Rd7 {[%cal Gd7e7]} Re8 {[%csl Re7]} 20. Nd4 Bxc6 21. Nxc6 Qb5 {[%cal Gb5f1] The active queen generates huge counterplay.} 22. b4 Qe2 {[%csl Re6]} 23. Nxe7 Qxe6 24. Nf5+ Kg8 (24... Kf8 25. Qc5+ Kg8 26. Qxc7 {leads to the same story.}) 25. Qxc7 Kf8 $1 ({Black is now threatening ...gxf5. The immediate} 25... gxf5 $2 {fails to} 26. Qg3+ {, while 25...Qe1+? 26.Rd1 is another problem.}) 26. Qc5+ Kg8 27. Qc7 Kf8 $10 {White is forced to give a perpetual.} *

