1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. f4 {The Austrian Attack with the inclusion of [Be3] is not that effective, as it wastes time and creates a target on [e3] ...[Nf5], ...[Ng4]. If you compare this to the main Austrian Attack, you will notice that White develops the [f1]-bishop to [d3] first and then castles immediately with the [c1]-bishop tucked in so that they can roll their pawn with [e5] and have a strong attack.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] In the footsteps of the ...[a6] move.} 6. Nf3 ({This resembles the Austrian Attack 4.f4 with one major difference: White has committed their bishop to e3. White can also start with} 6. Bd3 {, but it transposes to the text move after} Bb7 7. Nf3 {.}) 6... Bb7 7. Bd3 (7. e5 Nd7 8. Bd3 {simply transposes and has no independent value.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is the Black's setup. We are not able to play ...[Nf6] easily when White is aiming for [e5]. So first, we need to challenge the [d4]-pawn by ...[c5]. In order to do that, we need the knight on [d7] facilitating the ...[c5] breakthrough.} 8. e5 {[%csl Rg7] Before Black opens up with ...[c5], White plans to attack on the kingside and barricade the [g7]-bishop at the same time.} Nh6 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ge8g8,Gh6f5,Gc7c5]} (8... c5 {is recommended by Vjeko in his Uncompromising Modern Defense course. I like the text move of developing the knight first and then carrying the important break ...[c5], keeping the options flexible. Doing necessary things first, like developing the knight.}) 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1] The main move, planning to castle long.} c5 $1 {Time to strike before White castles long.} 10. dxc5 (10. O-O-O b4 {and the white knight has no proper square since} 11. Ne4 c4 {exists, and 11.Na4 Bc6 also keeps the knight under threat.}) 10... dxe5 (10... Nxc5 11. Bxc5 dxc5 12. O-O-O {is the problem.}) 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. fxe5 O-O 13. O-O-O Qc7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc7e5]} (13... Bxe5 {is not possible due to} 14. Bxh6 {.}) 14. Kb1 Rad8 $1 {[%cal Gc7e5]} ({Crucial, as if we capture the e5-pawn now, there are some consequences. For example} 14... Qxe5 15. Bxh6 Qxe2 16. Bxe2 Bxh6 {and White can chip in with} 17. Nd5 {, and we have to face an unpleasant endgame. The text move improves the position of our pieces and, at the same time, keeps an eye on the [e5]-pawn. Next, of course, we will regain the pawn back on [e5].}) 15. a3 (15. e6 $2 {is well met by} f5 $1 {with a clear advantage for Black given the ...[Ng4] and ...[f4] ideas. White's structure is weak, and that yields more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 15... Qxe5 16. Bxh6 Qxe2 17. Bxe2 Bxh6 18. Bf3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Bd2 {[%csl Rc3]} 20. Ne4 Bf4 $10 {[%cal Gf7f5] Followed by ...[f5] and White's knight has no proper square to jump forward.} *

