1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] We will have to check this move every time, as it creates an ambitious threat of [h5].} h5 $1 {This is important. Otherwise, White will push the h-pawn all the way, creating deadly threats.} ({Unfortunately, the natural} 5... Nf6 $2 {is a big mistake, as it allows the deadly} 6. h5 $1 {, a well-known exchange sacrifice that happened in many games, including Prag-Carlsen 2022, and White was superior in the arising complications.} Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 e6 9. e5 d5 10. O-O-O {± followed by [f4] and [Nf3] with a crushing advantage.}) 6. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3][%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] With the plan of [Qd2], [O-O-O] and [Nh3].} b5 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} Nf6 8. O-O-O {The logical follow-up.} b4 $1 9. Nce2 a5 10. Nh3 {[%cal Gh3g5]} ({Already an unexplored fresh position in human games as I can only find a majority of correspondence games.} 10. Kb1 Ba6 11. Nh3 Nc6 {leads to the same story.}) 10... Nc6 $1 ({The best square for the knight, as} 10... Nbd7 {is met by the powerful} 11. e5 {.}) 11. Ng5 (11. Kb1 Ba6 {and White has nothing better than} 12. Ng5 {, which in turn transposes.}) 11... Ba6 {[%cal Ga6f1]} 12. Kb1 (12. d5 Ne5 13. Nd4 Bxf1 {followed by ...[Qc8] and ...[c5].}) 12... a4 13. Nf4 Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6]} (13... Bxf1 {would be a grave mistake, as it only activates White's rook. Moreover, the queen on [d8] will be under pressure when we want to free our position with ...[e5] or ...[c5], so drifting the queen away from the wrath of the [d1]-rook is useful.}) 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qa6 $10 {Black dilutes White's forces by exchanging them.} *

