1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] We will have to check this move every time, as it creates an ambitious threat of [h5].} h5 $1 {This is important. Otherwise, White will push the h-pawn all the way, creating deadly threats.} ({Unfortunately, the natural} 5... Nf6 $2 {is a big mistake, as it allows the deadly} 6. h5 $1 {, a well-known exchange sacrifice that happened in many games, including Prag-Carlsen 2022, and White was superior in the arising complications.} Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 e6 9. e5 d5 10. O-O-O {± followed by [f4] and [Nf3] with a crushing advantage.}) 6. Nh3 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh3g5] White wants to puncture the knight to [g5], creating threats around Black's king. White will enjoy a nice outpost on [g5] since Black cannot kick it with ...[h6], while ...[f6] would be a positional concession.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 7. f3 {[%csl Rg4]} ({Stopping ...Ng4 makes sense, as the immediate} 7. Ng5 {will be met by} Ng4 8. Bf4 Nc6 {.}) 7... b5 {Time to create counterplay. We can also capture the knight on [h3] and follow it with ...[Nbd7].} ({But in this particular position, White gets a nice attack after} 7... Bxh3 8. Rxh3 Nbd7 9. Qe2 {, an important place for the queen not blocking the rook on [d1] after White castles long. Play will continue} b5 10. O-O-O {with a powerful thrust of [e5] coming next thanks to the queen on [e2]. So when White places the queen on [d2], then we can capture on [h3]. So, for now, we keep the idea in mind.}) 8. Ng5 O-O 9. Qd2 c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7a1] The typical pawn sacrifice to open up the Dragon bishop on [g7].} 10. dxc5 (10. d5 Nbd7 {doesn't help White.}) 10... dxc5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxc5 {[%cal Gc5e7] Black has lost a pawn, but in turn, Black has a tremendous activity, which provides decent compensation.} Nc6 {Here, White has a couple of plans of how to place their pieces.} 13. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1c1] Blocking the d-file to castle long.} Nd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 14. Be3 Nde5 {[%csl Rd3]} 15. O-O-O Nxd3+ 16. Rxd3 (16. cxd3 b4 {, and in fact, White is in trouble here.}) 16... Rxd3 17. cxd3 f6 {Go back!} 18. Nh3 Bxh3 19. Rxh3 Rd8 {[%csl Rd3]} 20. Kd2 (20. Kc2 Nb4+ {is winning.}) 20... f5 {[%cal Gg7b2,Gg8f7] The computers claim it as equal even though White has an extra pawn. The reasons are the backward pawn on [d3] and the dangerous bishop on [g7]. These factors have a huge say.} *

