1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Both bishops are fianchettoed now towards the d4 and e4-pawn respectively. This will be my suggestion if you would like to play the 4.f4 a6 system.} 7. O-O Nd7 8. e5 c5 {[%csl Rd4] The main counterplay idea, without which we would be crushed.} 9. Be4 Bxe4 10. Nxe4 cxd4 11. exd6 Ngf6 {We have coordinated our pieces.} 12. dxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Re1 Ne4 15. Qd3 f5 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5] Sealing the knight on [e4], which restricts White's activity on the e-file.} 16. Ng5 O-O $10 {Finally, our king has founds its place. : All cool now.} *

