[Black "Austrian Attack 4.f4 a6 – Alternative: 6.Bd3 Bb7 7.O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B06"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2159115887313623"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Both bishops are fianchettoed now towards the d4 and e4-pawn respectively. This will be my suggestion if you would like to play the 4.f4 a6 system.} 7. O-O Nd7 8. a4 {This is one of the major problems. In the end, we kind of neutralize by holding on to a thread with many concrete moves. This direction is also one of the reasons I am not so happy about the 4...a6 system, as every time, we need to play some accurate moves. Having said that, White also needs some precision to create problems. You can check the lines and decide for yourself if you are happy with it or if you prefer the solid 4...Nf6 system.} c5 $1 {We often see that Black reacts in this manner to White's breakthrough with [a4] rather than pushing our pawn to [b4].} (8... b4 {only helps White since after} 9. Ne2 c5 10. c3 {, White builds up a great center. There are only three games in my database here, so it is a relatively fresh concept. A young Hans Neimann from 2019 also approves us, as he is one of the Black players who played ...[c5] here.}) 9. axb5 cxd4 10. Na4 {The top choice of the engine.} axb5 11. Bxb5 Bxe4 {Again, the position is totally messy and only clings on to concrete resources.} 12. Bxd7+ (12. Nxd4 Ngf6 {and Black consolidates with castle coming next.}) 12... Kxd7 {Forced, as if we capture with the queen, then White has the knight fork on [b6].} 13. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5f7,Gg5e4]} (13. Nxd4 Nf6 14. Be3 Qb8 {followed by ...[Rc8], ...[Ke8], and Black consolidates slowly.}) 13... Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc7c6] With the plan of ...[Qc7]-[c6].} ({For a long time, the computer was suggesting} 13... Bc6 {over 13...Bb7 , but after probing it in greater depth, the computers increased the evaluation to White's favor.}) ({So} 13... Bc6 14. Nxf7 Qa5 {, targeting the [a4]-knight.} 15. Bd2 Qa7 16. Qg4+ Kc7 17. Qe6 d3+ 18. Be3 {, and so on.}) 14. Nxf7 {[%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8]} Qc7 {[%csl Ra4,Rg2][%cal Gc7c6]} 15. Nxh8 {It is not necessary to capture the rook as it is stuck there.} Bxh8 {[%cal Gc7c6] Next, Black is coming up with ...[Qc6].} 16. c3 {[%cal Gd1a4] Renewing the support to the knight on [a4].} (16. f5 {will be met by} Qc6 {, double attacking the [g2]-pawn and the [a4]-knight. The game will continue with} 17. Qf3 {, and we are not able to capture the knight on [a4] due to the hanging bishop on [b7], so we react with} Kc7 {, supporting the [b7]-bishop.} 18. Qxc6+ Bxc6 {and the knight on the a-file is pinned and pressurized, which gives Black good enough compensation.}) 16... Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f5]} (16... Qc6 {is also possible. White will react with} 17. Rf2 {.}) 17. Qb3 {[%cal Ga4b6]} Kd8 {[%cal Ga8b8] Followed by ...[Rb8] and Black has good compensation for the exchange. Though our king is exposed, White is not able to exploit it thanks to our active pieces. The computer gives zeros here.} (17... Kd8 {One sample line is} 18. Bd2 Rb8 19. Qb6 Qxb6 20. Nxb6 Bc6 21. Nc4 Bd5 22. Ra4 Nf5 {, and so on.}) *

