[PlyCount "60"]
[GameId "2159115887448792"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Both bishops are fianchettoed now towards the d4 and e4-pawn respectively. This will be my suggestion if you would like to play the 4.f4 a6 system.} 7. Qe2 {[%cal Ge4e5]} (7. a4 {is also possible, but this option of 7.Qe2 is even more threatening, as White is now in a mood to roll out with [e5] next.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] What else? We only have one plan of carrying out the most important ...[c5] break before White starts rolling on the kingside.} 8. e5 (8. a4 {now is met by the typical} c5 {.}) 8... c5 {The only counterplay idea. If it works, it's all well and good; if not, then we are crushed.} 9. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Rf7][%cal Ge5e6]} ({All in, threatening e6.} 9. Be3 b4 {turns the table in the Black's favor.}) 9... cxd4 10. e6 {Play gets very interesting and complex.} f5 {Only move, as [exf7]+ followed by [Ne6]+ was a big threat.} 11. exd7+ Qxd7 {The start of a crazy and imbalanced position.} 12. Nd1 {White has got an extra piece after the complications, but thanks to our central pawn mass, we do have some counterplay. Stockfish overestimates this position for White, as once you start digging deep, the evaluations drop. That is why it is always nicer to have a human perspective.} ({After} 12. Nxb5 axb5 13. Ne6 {, we have} Kf7 {, and if 13.Bxb5 Bc6 safeguards. 14.Bc4 Bf6 followed by the ...[Nh6] setup is important to make note of. Black has safeguarded the [f7]-square thanks to the knight on [h6] and as well Black can exchange the annoying knight on [g5] anytime. If you play the Modern, you have to get used to these weird setups as most of the time, play is concrete and not based on the general setup of pieces.}) 12... e5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5] Let's go!! The juicers on [e5] and [f5] rule the game.} 13. fxe5 dxe5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf5]} 14. a4 {[%csl Rb5]} (14. O-O {allows us to stabilize with 15...Ne7 , and then ...[h6] followed by ...[e4] is a big threat since our king is safeguarded.}) 14... h6 15. Nf3 e4 {Although we don't have an immediate threat, the pawns create a mess all over the board, not allowing White to relax.} 16. axb5 Ne7 {Unpinning on the e-file and now White has to surrender one piece.} 17. bxa6 O-O (17... exd3 {would be a blunder due to} 18. axb7 Rxa1 19. b8=Q+ {.}) 18. Bc4+ Kh7 {I can understand that we have already reached a bit far, and it might not happen over the board. The reason for analyzing further is that we are still a piece down, and we ought to know the natural responses from White and how to react to them as the game is concrete.} 19. Nd2 {[%csl Rc1,Rd1,Rd2] White escapes from the piece loss, but their pieces are cramped and not in full flow.} Bd5 20. O-O Rfc8 {[%cal Gc8c2,Ge4e3] Threatening ...[e3].} 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 {I would like to stop the analysis here, claiming it as good compensation, but the position is so concrete still, so we will have to continue a bit further.} 22. Nxe4 {It looks natural to give up the piece in the form of two pawns.} fxe4 23. Qxe4 {[%csl Rc2] White is two pawns up here, and one might wonder where is Black's compensation. But Black does have some in the form of [d4]-pawn and active pieces, and the pressure on the [c2]-pawn tops the list.} Ra7 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Rc2][%cal Gd7c6] The [a6]-pawn has to be blockaded and targeted.} 24. Bd2 Qc6 {[%csl Ra6,Rc2] Having an eye on both pawns, [c2] and [a6].} 25. Qe2 (25. Rf2 Rca8 {and then we grab the [a6]-pawn.}) 25... Re8 26. Qd3 Ne3 {Activity is what keeps Black going.} 27. Nxe3 dxe3 28. Bc3 (28. Bxe3 Rd7 {is the problem.}) 28... Rd7 29. Qe2 Bxc3 30. bxc3 Qxc3 $10 {Black is fine now. The passed [a6]-pawn is compensated by our [e3]-pawn.} *

