1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 5. a4 {[%csl Rb5] White stops ...[b5].} (5. Be2 Nf6 6. O-O O-O {transposes to the Tricky Systems, and 5.Be3 Nf6 transposes to the 4.Be3 line.}) 5... Nf6 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] This is a useful move, aiming to prevent ...[Ng4] when White plays [Be3], while also sometimes stopping ...[Bg4] and the resulting pin.} (6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {would transpose.}) 6... O-O 7. Be2 b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Thanks to the inclusion of ...[a6] and [a4], this setup becomes possible. Black plans to develop the bishop to [b7] and target the [e4]-pawn, creating a double fianchetto.} 8. e5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Nfd7 {[%csl Re5] Challenging the influential knight on [e5].} 10. Bf3 Ra7 {[%cal Gc8b7] Up next is ...[Bb7].} 11. Nc4 Bb7 12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. O-O c6 $10 {[%cal Gb6b5] A precise move, preparing ...[b5] next.} ({Playing} 13... b5 {immediately is met by} 14. Na5 {. Once Black successfully breaks with ...[b5], our position becomes more active.}) *

