1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 5. a4 {[%csl Rb5] White stops ...[b5].} (5. Be2 Nf6 6. O-O O-O {transposes to the Tricky Systems, and 5.Be3 Nf6 transposes to the 4.Be3 line.}) 5... Nf6 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] This is a useful move, aiming to prevent ...[Ng4] when White plays [Be3], while also sometimes stopping ...[Bg4] and the resulting pin.} (6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {would transpose.}) 6... O-O 7. Be3 {[%csl Ge3,Rg4] The bishop feels safe now without having to worry about ...[Ng4] jumps.} b6 $5 {[%csl Ga4,Ga6,Re4][%cal Gc8b7] This plan is only possible when the moves ...[a6] and [a4] are included.} 8. Bc4 {[%cal Rc4g8] This occurred in my game against the strong Iranian GM Idani Pouya at the 2015 Asian Championship, which is also analyzed in the Model Games chapter. Placing the bishop on [c4] makes sense as it increases the pressure along the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} e6 $1 {[%csl Ga6,Gb6,Rc4,Gd6,Ge6] A Hippopotamus-like structure, characterized by a deep, defensive setup where Black remains flexible, often developing pieces behind a sturdy pawn wall before striking back in the center or on the flanks. This represents one of the typical schematic structures in the Modern Defense, allowing Black to remain flexible and react based on White's setup. Additionally, it also restricts the bishop on [c4], limiting its activity.} 9. d5 Re8 $1 ({The best move. Black is not well-prepared for} 9... exd5 {here, as after} 10. Bxd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 {, White can castle queenside and launch an h-pawn attack on the kingside, making Black's position look dangerous.}) 10. O-O exd5 {With White castling kingside, capturing on [d5] is now feasible.} 11. Bxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Ra7 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1]} 13. a5 Bb7 14. Qd3 Nd7 15. axb6 Nxb6 $10 {Black has now consolidated the game.} *

