1. e4 g6 2. g3 {White also wants to fianchetto the bishop like us, but the drawback is that the [e4]-pawn will restrict it.} Bg7 3. Bg2 c5 {[%csl Gd4] Controlling the center in the spirit of the Sicilian Defense.} 4. Ne2 {[%cal Gd2d4]} Nc6 {No [d4] for you. :} 5. O-O d6 ({There are some funny ideas in this position, such as} 5... h5 {followed by ...[h4], taking advantage of White's knight placement on [e2] instead of [f3]. This subtle difference gives Black the opportunity to disrupt White's setup. By pushing ...[h5], Black not only gains space on the kingside but also keeps open the possibility of launching an early pawn storm. The follow-up ...[h4] can be quite annoying for White, potentially weakening White's structure. Additionally, Black benefits from not having castled yet, meaning we have the flexibility to decide where to place our king based on how the game develops. This can catch White off guard, especially if they are unprepared for these early flank operations.}) 6. d3 h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} ({Apart from the roll of the h-pawn, there are other normal alternatives as well like} 6... e5 {followed by ...[Nge7] and so on. But I like this way of creating some attack towards White's king.}) 7. h3 (7. h4 Nf6 {and the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5] is in Black's favour as White cannot push [f4] anymore due to the hole around the [g4]-square.}) 7... h4 8. g4 f5 {Piercing through White's camp by playing energetically.} 9. f3 e5 $132 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gg8e7] Followed by ...[Be6] and ...[Nge7] – Black has a great game. I like Black here, as our pieces are well placed with nice tension around White's pawns on the kingside.} *

