1. e4 g6 2. g3 {White also wants to fianchetto the bishop like us, but the drawback is that the [e4]-pawn will restrict it.} Bg7 3. Bg2 c5 {[%csl Gd4] Controlling the center in the spirit of the Sicilian Defense.} 4. Ne2 {[%cal Gd2d4]} Nc6 {No [d4] for you. :} 5. O-O d6 ({There are some funny ideas in this position, such as} 5... h5 {followed by ...[h4], taking advantage of White's knight placement on [e2] instead of [f3]. This subtle difference gives Black the opportunity to disrupt White's setup. By pushing ...[h5], Black not only gains space on the kingside but also keeps open the possibility of launching an early pawn storm. The follow-up ...[h4] can be quite annoying for White, potentially weakening White's structure. Additionally, Black benefits from not having castled yet, meaning we have the flexibility to decide where to place our king based on how the game develops. This can catch White off guard, especially if they are unprepared for these early flank operations.}) 6. d3 h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} ({Apart from the roll of the h-pawn, there are other normal alternatives as well like} 6... e5 {followed by ...[Nge7] and so on. But I like this way of creating some attack towards White's king.}) 7. h3 (7. h4 Nf6 {and the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5] is in Black's favour as White cannot push [f4] anymore due to the hole around the [g4]-square.}) 7... h4 8. g4 f5 9. gxf5 gxf5 10. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4g6] A super crazy line.} Bh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f4] Black is planning to exchange the active knight on [f4].} 11. Qh5+ Kd7 {The Majesty is not scared.} 12. Ne6 $1 (12. Qxf5+ Kc7 {is winning for Black, as the queen has no proper squares to hide.}) 12... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6h5] The only move, taking the piece, will lead to mate in one. So, we have to counterattack White's queen.} 13. Qf7 (13. Qxf5 Qg8 {is bad for White, as they have to release the knight without any proper discovered threats.}) 13... Qe8 14. Qxe8+ Nxe8 15. Bxh6 Rxh6 16. exf5 Nc7 $10 {[%csl Gc7,Ge6][%cal Gc8f5] Black removes the annoying knight on [e6]. We will regain the pawn on [f5] with a good game.} *

