1. e4 g6 2. g3 {White also wants to fianchetto the bishop like us, but the drawback is that the [e4]-pawn will restrict it.} Bg7 3. Bg2 c5 {[%csl Gd4] Controlling the center in the spirit of the Sicilian Defense.} 4. Ne2 {[%cal Gd2d4]} Nc6 {No [d4] for you. :} 5. O-O d6 ({There are some funny ideas in this position, such as} 5... h5 {followed by ...[h4], taking advantage of White's knight placement on [e2] instead of [f3]. This subtle difference gives Black the opportunity to disrupt White's setup. By pushing ...[h5], Black not only gains space on the kingside but also keeps open the possibility of launching an early pawn storm. The follow-up ...[h4] can be quite annoying for White, potentially weakening White's structure. Additionally, Black benefits from not having castled yet, meaning we have the flexibility to decide where to place our king based on how the game develops. This can catch White off guard, especially if they are unprepared for these early flank operations.}) 6. c3 {[%cal Gd2d4]} e5 {[%csl Gd4] The whole game revolves around the [d4]-square. If White successfully gets [d2]-[d4] in, we may just get steamrolled in the center.} 7. Na3 Nge7 ({The most precise.} 7... Nf6 {instead is possible but allows} 8. d4 {. If we can restrict White's play while also planning to win the battle for the center with ...[d5], we'll obviously go for that.}) 8. Nc2 {[%cal Gd2d4] Finally, White is now getting [d4] in, but it is too late, as we can already strike in the center.} d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Ncxd4 O-O $10 {With a comfortable game – the position will fizzle out soon.} *

