1. e4 g6 2. f4 {[%csl Rc1,Re1,Re5][%cal Gg1f3] Inducing the Bird Defense into the Modern. White aims to control the [e5]-square, with [Nf3] likely to follow.} ({However, compared to the direct} 2. d4 {push, this method of occupying the center comes with certain drawbacks – most notably, the [c1]-bishop is blocked, limiting its scope. Additionally, White's king is slightly exposed, which is something to keep in mind.}) 2... d5 $1 {When the opportunity arises to challenge the center, there is no other priority – this is the essence of dynamic chess. Central control dictates the flow of the game, and delaying action could allow White to consolidate. So, let's strike with full force! A well-timed break can shift the momentum in our favor, seizing initiative and creating immediate problems for our opponent.} 3. d3 {Magnus played it once in an online game against Spanish strong Grandmaster Anton Guijaro way back in 2022 Chessable Masters. But it's nothing special, and we can fizzle out with exchanges on [e4].} dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ {Trading the queens is the simplest solution.} 5. Kxd1 Bg7 6. Nf3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8g4] Next, maybe ...[Bg4] or ...[Nf6] followed by ...[e5] are Black's main ideas to continue development.} 7. c3 {[%csl Rc6]} Nf6 (7... Bg4 8. Kc2 Nf6 9. Nbd2 Bh6 {is equally possible.}) 8. Bd3 e5 $10 {Black has a comfortable game with nicely developed pieces. Next, we will bring the light-squared bishop into action or castle short.} *

