1. e4 g6 2. f4 {[%csl Rc1,Re1,Re5][%cal Gg1f3] Inducing the Bird Defense into the Modern. White aims to control the [e5]-square, with [Nf3] likely to follow.} ({However, compared to the direct} 2. d4 {push, this method of occupying the center comes with certain drawbacks – most notably, the [c1]-bishop is blocked, limiting its scope. Additionally, White's king is slightly exposed, which is something to keep in mind.}) 2... d5 $1 {When the opportunity arises to challenge the center, there is no other priority – this is the essence of dynamic chess. Central control dictates the flow of the game, and delaying action could allow White to consolidate. So, let's strike with full force! A well-timed break can shift the momentum in our favor, seizing initiative and creating immediate problems for our opponent.} 3. exd5 {Followed by Nc3 is the problem if we play 2...d5 in the line: 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.Nc3 and White gets a better version of the Center Counter/Scandinavian. Here, it's a different story, as White has weakened their king position with [f4] as early as move 2, so we are not concerned about it.} Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e1]} 5. d4 Bg7 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gg8f6,Gc8f5] The pawn on [f4] is a mismatch. Black gets easy play with ...[Nf6], ...[Bf5], and so on.} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Bd2 O-O 8. Be2 Qb6 $10 {[%csl Rd4,Rb2][%cal Gc8f5] Black slowly takes over the game. Next, we will develop the bishop to [f5], place the rook on [d8], and develop the [b8]-knight as well, and there is always pressure on the [d4] and [b2]-pawns. I will take Black's side any day here.} *

