1. e4 g6 2. f4 {[%csl Rc1,Re1,Re5][%cal Gg1f3] Inducing the Bird Defense into the Modern. White aims to control the [e5]-square, with [Nf3] likely to follow.} ({However, compared to the direct} 2. d4 {push, this method of occupying the center comes with certain drawbacks – most notably, the [c1]-bishop is blocked, limiting its scope. Additionally, White's king is slightly exposed, which is something to keep in mind.}) 2... d5 $1 {When the opportunity arises to challenge the center, there is no other priority – this is the essence of dynamic chess. Central control dictates the flow of the game, and delaying action could allow White to consolidate. So, let's strike with full force! A well-timed break can shift the momentum in our favor, seizing initiative and creating immediate problems for our opponent.} 3. e5 {[%cal Gd2d4] Closing the game so that the [f8]-bishop will remain passive.} c5 {[%csl Rd4] If White plays [d4] next, then they will have a formidable pawn chain, center, space, and whatnot, so we do not allow easy fortification of the central pawn on [e5] by [d4].} 4. Nf3 (4. c3 {is one more logical option for White, trying to fortify the center with the [d4]-pawn but is slow, and Black can react with} Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 {and here Black has a sound idea with} h5 {, preparing ...[Bg4], and in fact Black is slightly better here, as we can target the [d4]-pawn with ...[Nh6]-[f5] after ...[Bg4].}) 4... Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1] Pinning can be one of the most annoying tactical motifs in chess, restricting piece mobility and creating long-term positional discomfort. A well-executed pin can paralyze an opponent's position, making it difficult for them to execute their plans effectively. Here is the case as well.} 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 a6 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6] Followed by ...[Nc6], ...[e6], ...[Nge7], ...[h5], and ...[Bg7], Black maintains a solid and flexible position.} ({The key idea behind} 6... a6 {before ...[Nc6] is to prevent White from pinning the knight with [Bb5], which could otherwise become a positional nuisance. As mentioned earlier, pins can be quite frustrating in chess, limiting piece mobility and forcing unwanted concessions.}) ({Here, if Black plays} 6... Nc6 {immediately, White has the option of} 7. Bb5 {, leading to [Bxc6] at the right moment. This can result in structural damage similar to the Rossolimo Sicilian, where Black's pawn formation gets compromised after ...[bxc6]. By delaying ...[Nc6] and inserting ...[a6] first, Black avoids this structural issue and retains greater control over their development. The subsequent setup with ...[Nc6], ...[e6], ...[Bg7], and a well-timed ...[h5] ensures that Black has a resilient and dynamic position, ready to counter White's plans effectively.}) *

