1. e4 g6 2. Bc4 Bg7 3. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7] Threatening mate in one on [f7].} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] Of course, not falling into the childish trap of mate in one. One more point to add is that now the combination of the bishop on [c4] and the queen on [f3] falls flat.} 4. d4 {IM Levy Rozman, popularly known as GothamChess in the YouTube world, has played this option numerous times in Titled Tuesdays. So let's have a brief look at this pawn sacrifice to evaluate whether it is a bluff or not.} Bxd4 5. Ne2 Bg7 6. Nbc3 d6 7. h4 Nc6 {[%csl Rc4,Rf3][%cal Gc6e5]} 8. Qg3 h5 9. Bg5 Nge7 $17 {White is simply a pawn down with zero compensation. Hence, I conclude that Levy's 4.d4 option is a bluff, and it simply doesn't work. Black has a big advantage here.} *

