1. e4 g6 2. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Yes, this idea exists in many positions. This is what AlphaZero has brought to the table. White aims to target [g6] with an early [h5] advance, sometimes as early as move 2. Harry is in a hurry, trying to exploit our first move without even developing pieces properly – and that is simply not good! This option is very popular in Titled Tuesday events, bullet, and blitz games, where quick attacks can catch opponents off guard. However, in a classical setting, this plan is not effective enough to create a serious disruption in our camp. With precise play, Black can neutralize the attack and take over the initiative.} d5 $1 ({Adhering to the theory of flank attack must be met by counterplay in the center. Apart from} 2... d5 {, Black has other moves as well, like 2...Nf6 , not allowing White to push the h-pawn further. Play will continue with 3.e5 Nh5 4.Be2 , and so on.}) 3. exd5 Bg7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d5]} ({The immediate} 3... Qxd5 {is also possible.} 4. Nc3 Qd6 5. d4 {and we get into a weird version of the Scandinavian. The text move is clever; by the next move, when we grab on [d5] and counter [Nc3] with ...[Qd6], White does not have the [d4] advance. ( For Gambit lovers 3...c6 is also very interesting. )}) 4. Nf3 Qxd5 5. Nc3 (5. d4 {is met by} Bg4 {, pinning the [f3]-knight and exerting pressure on the central pawn on [d4].}) 5... Qa5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ga5e1]} ({Nothing wrong with} 5... Qd6 {as well, but in this case, I prefer to place the queen on [a5] so that when White pushes [d4], their [c3]-knight will be under the pin.}) 6. d4 Bg4 {[%csl Rc3,Rf3][%cal Ga5e1,Gg4d1] Double pin.} 7. Bd2 Nf6 $10 {[%csl Gg4,Rh4] This is a much better version of the Scandinavian. Black's bishop on [g4] is super strong and not easy to shake, all thanks to White's pawn on [h4].} *

