1. e4 g6 2. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Yes, this idea exists in many positions. This is what AlphaZero has brought to the table. White aims to target [g6] with an early [h5] advance, sometimes as early as move 2. Harry is in a hurry, trying to exploit our first move without even developing pieces properly – and that is simply not good! This option is very popular in Titled Tuesday events, bullet, and blitz games, where quick attacks can catch opponents off guard. However, in a classical setting, this plan is not effective enough to create a serious disruption in our camp. With precise play, Black can neutralize the attack and take over the initiative.} d5 $1 ({Adhering to the theory of flank attack must be met by counterplay in the center. Apart from} 2... d5 {, Black has other moves as well, like 2...Nf6 , not allowing White to push the h-pawn further. Play will continue with 3.e5 Nh5 4.Be2 , and so on.}) 3. exd5 Bg7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d5]} ({The immediate} 3... Qxd5 {is also possible.} 4. Nc3 Qd6 5. d4 {and we get into a weird version of the Scandinavian. The text move is clever; by the next move, when we grab on [d5] and counter [Nc3] with ...[Qd6], White does not have the [d4] advance. ( For Gambit lovers 3...c6 is also very interesting. )}) 4. d4 Qxd5 {[%csl Rd4] White is not in time to torment our queen on [d5] by [Nc3] as first, White needs to protect the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Be3 (5. c3 {defends the pawn but blocks the route of the [b1]-knight to [c3]. Black can therefore finish development unhindered following} Nf6 {, ...[c5], ...[O-O], etc.}) 5... Nf6 {Now we are no longer worried about [Nc3], as we have developed our pieces.} 6. Nc3 Qa5 {[%csl Rc3,Rh4][%cal Ga5e1] A much better version of the Scandinavian, as the [h4]-pawn is such a provocation with no effect.} 7. Nf3 Nc6 {More energy.} 8. Qd2 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8] White is in big trouble with long castle coming next.} *

