1. e4 g6 2. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Yes, this idea exists in many positions. This is what AlphaZero has brought to the table. White aims to target [g6] with an early [h5] advance, sometimes as early as move 2. Harry is in a hurry, trying to exploit our first move without even developing pieces properly – and that is simply not good! This option is very popular in Titled Tuesday events, bullet, and blitz games, where quick attacks can catch opponents off guard. However, in a classical setting, this plan is not effective enough to create a serious disruption in our camp. With precise play, Black can neutralize the attack and take over the initiative.} d5 $1 ({Adhering to the theory of flank attack must be met by counterplay in the center. Apart from} 2... d5 {, Black has other moves as well, like 2...Nf6 , not allowing White to push the h-pawn further. Play will continue with 3.e5 Nh5 4.Be2 , and so on.}) 3. exd5 Bg7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d5]} ({The immediate} 3... Qxd5 {is also possible.} 4. Nc3 Qd6 5. d4 {and we get into a weird version of the Scandinavian. The text move is clever; by the next move, when we grab on [d5] and counter [Nc3] with ...[Qd6], White does not have the [d4] advance. ( For Gambit lovers 3...c6 is also very interesting. )}) 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5] Retaining the [d5]-pawn.} Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} 5. Bb5+ Nbd7 (5... c6 {is also very interesting, sacrificing the pawn like in the 4.Bb5+ Bd7 5.Be2 lines.}) 6. d4 O-O {[%cal Gd7b6] Preparing ...[Nb6] next.} 7. Be2 {[%cal Gh4h5] White can no longer hold on to [d5]-pawn and has to focus on other areas.} Nb6 8. h5 Nbxd5 {Regaining the central pawn, which was sacrificed on move 3.} 9. h6 Nxc3 {Shattering White's pawn structure before moving the bishop.} 10. bxc3 Bh8 11. Nf3 c5 $10 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6e4,Gh8a1] White has doubled c-pawns, and the [c3]-pawn, in particular, is a long-term weakness due to the pressure along the [h8]-[a1] diagonal. This structural defect makes White's position slightly uncomfortable, as the pawn lacks natural support and can be a persistent target in the middlegame. Meanwhile, Black is threatening ...[Ne4], activating the knight to a strong central square. This move serves a dual purpose: Paving the way for the [h8]-bishop to exert influence along the long diagonal. Directly attacking the weak [c3]-pawn, forcing White onto the defensive.} (11... c5 {A possible continuation could be} 12. O-O Ne4 {, after which Black enjoys a comfortable position with dynamic piece play and a clear plan of action. By maintaining central control and exerting pressure on White's weaknesses, Black can look forward to a promising middlegame.}) *

