1. e4 g6 2. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Yes, this idea exists in many positions. This is what AlphaZero has brought to the table. White aims to target [g6] with an early [h5] advance, sometimes as early as move 2. Harry is in a hurry, trying to exploit our first move without even developing pieces properly – and that is simply not good! This option is very popular in Titled Tuesday events, bullet, and blitz games, where quick attacks can catch opponents off guard. However, in a classical setting, this plan is not effective enough to create a serious disruption in our camp. With precise play, Black can neutralize the attack and take over the initiative.} d5 $1 ({Adhering to the theory of flank attack must be met by counterplay in the center. Apart from} 2... d5 {, Black has other moves as well, like 2...Nf6 , not allowing White to push the h-pawn further. Play will continue with 3.e5 Nh5 4.Be2 , and so on.}) 3. exd5 Bg7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d5]} ({The immediate} 3... Qxd5 {is also possible.} 4. Nc3 Qd6 5. d4 {and we get into a weird version of the Scandinavian. The text move is clever; by the next move, when we grab on [d5] and counter [Nc3] with ...[Qd6], White does not have the [d4] advance. ( For Gambit lovers 3...c6 is also very interesting. )}) 4. Bb5+ {An intermezzo blocking the path of the queen on the d-file.} Bd7 {Hard to believe that there are no games in my database for this position! As early as move 4, we're already in uncharted territory – so much for the claim that chess is completely analyzed and explored. LOL!} 5. Bc4 (5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {only activates Black's pieces, and if} 6. c4 {, we have} c6 {and Black is on top.}) 5... Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} 6. d4 c6 $1 {Let's gambit to bring our army of pieces into full force.} 7. h5 O-O {Cool as a cucumber. Black does not care about the fact that the h-file is under fire, only thanks to the protective bishop on [g7], which simply safeguards the king 24/7.} ({After} 7... cxd5 {, the problem is the intermediate} 8. h6 {and we are forced to land on [f8], which looses the option of castling.}) 8. h6 Bh8 9. Nc3 cxd5 10. Bb3 (10. Nxd5 {is a blunder due to} Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Qa5+ {and Black wins a full piece.}) 10... Nc6 11. Nge2 e6 $10 {[%csl Rb3,Gd5,Ge6]} (11... e6 {Black's position is solid. If} 12. Bg5 {, then} Qa5 {followed by ...[Ne8]-[d6] is one of the ideas. The bishop on [b3] is shut by our pawn chain [e6]-[d5].}) *

