1. e4 g6 2. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Yes, this idea exists in many positions. This is what AlphaZero has brought to the table. White aims to target [g6] with an early [h5] advance, sometimes as early as move 2. Harry is in a hurry, trying to exploit our first move without even developing pieces properly – and that is simply not good! This option is very popular in Titled Tuesday events, bullet, and blitz games, where quick attacks can catch opponents off guard. However, in a classical setting, this plan is not effective enough to create a serious disruption in our camp. With precise play, Black can neutralize the attack and take over the initiative.} d5 $1 ({Adhering to the theory of flank attack must be met by counterplay in the center. Apart from} 2... d5 {, Black has other moves as well, like 2...Nf6 , not allowing White to push the h-pawn further. Play will continue with 3.e5 Nh5 4.Be2 , and so on.}) 3. exd5 Bg7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d5]} ({The immediate} 3... Qxd5 {is also possible.} 4. Nc3 Qd6 5. d4 {and we get into a weird version of the Scandinavian. The text move is clever; by the next move, when we grab on [d5] and counter [Nc3] with ...[Qd6], White does not have the [d4] advance. ( For Gambit lovers 3...c6 is also very interesting. )}) 4. Bb5+ {An intermezzo blocking the path of the queen on the d-file.} Bd7 {Hard to believe that there are no games in my database for this position! As early as move 4, we're already in uncharted territory – so much for the claim that chess is completely analyzed and explored. LOL!} 5. Be2 (5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {only activates Black's pieces, and if} 6. c4 {, we have} c6 {and Black is on top.}) 5... c6 $1 {The key move! Since White has wasted time with the Harry pawn advance and unnecessary bishop moves, it's the right moment for Black to seize the initiative with some energetic play.} ({A natural attempt like} 5... Bf5 {might seem logical, but it runs into} 6. c4 {, where White immediately clamps down on [d5], securing a strong central grip. This means Black needs to find an alternative to make use of the development advantage.}) 6. Nc3 Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} 7. h5 {Here is a key moment. We generally ignore the h-pawn, but this is the time to get rid of it.} gxh5 $1 (7... O-O 8. h6 Bh8 9. dxc6 {followed by [Nf3] is slightly better for White, as they are a pawn up with no apparent weakness on [h4] since it has reached all the way to [h6], only helping White to restrict Black's pieces.}) 8. dxc6 Nxc6 9. d3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Gb6,Rf2][%cal Gf6g4] With full compensation. Now ...[Ng4] is one of the main threats, and White is more or less forced to take on [h5], which loses the bishop pair.} (9... Qb6 {One sample line might be} 10. Bxh5 Nxh5 11. Rxh5 Ne5 {followed by ...[Rc8] and White is not able to castle long freely.}) *

