grip. This means Black needs to find an alternative to make use of the development advantage.}) 6. c4 cxd5 7. cxd5 Nf6 {[%csl Rd5] The [d5]-pawn is lonely and will be cornered.} 8. Nc3 O-O {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4,Ga6c7] Black's ideas are ...[Na6]-[b4]/[c7] to target the [d5]-pawn.} 9. h5 Bf5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf5h7] One more additional possibility apart from the ...[Na6]-[c7] maneuver.} 10. hxg6 Bxg6 {[%csl Gf7,Gf8,Gg6,Gg7,Gg8,Gh7,Rd5] Black's kingside is intact, and now the [d5]-pawn is hanging.} 11. Qb3 Na6 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd8b6] We can play ...[Qb6] next, exchange the main defender of the [d5]-pawn, and then grab the pawn as well by ...[Nb4].} (11... Na6 12. Qxb7 {should not worry us, as after} Nc7 {, the pawn on [d5] is falling while White's development continues to be difficult.}) *

