1. e4 g6 2. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Yes, this idea exists in many positions. This is what AlphaZero has brought to the table. White aims to target [g6] with an early [h5] advance, sometimes as early as move 2. Harry is in a hurry, trying to exploit our first move without even developing pieces properly – and that is simply not good! This option is very popular in Titled Tuesday events, bullet, and blitz games, where quick attacks can catch opponents off guard. However, in a classical setting, this plan is not effective enough to create a serious disruption in our camp. With precise play, Black can neutralize the attack and take over the initiative.} d5 $1 ({Adhering to the theory of flank attack must be met by counterplay in the center. Apart from} 2... d5 {, Black has other moves as well, like 2...Nf6 , not allowing White to push the h-pawn further. Play will continue with 3.e5 Nh5 4.Be2 , and so on.}) 3. exd5 Bg7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d5]} ({The immediate} 3... Qxd5 {is also possible.} 4. Nc3 Qd6 5. d4 {and we get into a weird version of the Scandinavian. The text move is clever; by the next move, when we grab on [d5] and counter [Nc3] with ...[Qd6], White does not have the [d4] advance. ( For Gambit lovers 3...c6 is also very interesting. )}) 4. Bb5+ {An intermezzo blocking the path of the queen on the d-file.} Bd7 {Hard to believe that there are no games in my database for this position! As early as move 4, we're already in uncharted territory – so much for the claim that chess is completely analyzed and explored. LOL!} 5. Be2 (5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {only activates Black's pieces, and if} 6. c4 {, we have} c6 {and Black is on top.}) 5... c6 $1 {The key move! Since White has wasted time with the Harry pawn advance and unnecessary bishop moves, it's the right moment for Black to seize the initiative with some energetic play.} ({A natural attempt like} 5... Bf5 {might seem logical, but it runs into} 6. c4 {, where White immediately clamps down on [d5], securing a strong central grip. This means Black needs to find an alternative to make use of the development advantage.}) 6. dxc6 {[%csl Rh4] The critical response, as we are currently a pawn down. However, there is nothing to worry about, as Black enjoys long-term compensation in the form of active piece play, strong central control, and potential counterplay. At this moment, we are not in a rush to regain the material immediately. Instead, we should focus on maintaining a dynamic balance and looking for the right moment to strike. There's no need to force matters – rather, we should let the position unfold naturally and wait for White to overextend or make inaccuracies.} Nxc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4]} e5 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3][%cal Ge5e4] A logical reaction to gain space in the center as White was preparing [d4].} 8. d3 {[%cal Gh4h5]} ({White is threatening h5 now. The immediate} 8. h5 {is met by} e4 {, and White's knight is in trouble.}) 8... h6 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg6g5]} (8... h6 {With the intention to meet} 9. h5 {with} g5 {, but 8...Nf6 is also equally possible.}) 9. Nbd2 (9. O-O Nf6 {leads to the same story.}) 9... Nf6 10. O-O Qc7 {[%cal Ge8c8,Ge8g8] Black sometimes can also castle long and attack with ...[g5] thanks to the exposed white pawn on [h4].} 11. c3 O-O {[%cal Ga8d8]} ({We would love to castle long, but in this particular case, it is not effective.} 11... O-O-O 12. d4 {is super strong and before we attack, White takes over.}) 12. Ne4 {[%csl Gc1] White has to bring the [c1]-bishop into the game. The knight on [d2] was obstructing it.} Nd5 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf7f5] Rad8 followed by ...[f5] is next on the agenda, aiming to generate counterplay. Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn, as the central control limits White's activity. The rook placement on [d8] increases the pressure along the open file, while ...[f5] challenges White's knight. With precise execution, Black can seize the initiative, creating practical difficulties for White.} *

