[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2159115891991282"]

1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8] Finachettoing the bishop to [g2] is another option for White. Grandmaster Quesada Perez played this against me in the chess24 Banter Blitz. Those were the good old days of Banter Blitz. Petition to chess.com to start those fun series. : Coming back to the position, White's setup is simple – bishop to [g2], knight to [e2], castle, pawn to [d3], bishop to [e3], pawn to [f4], queen to [d2], and so on. The drawback is that it is slow, and White has no proper central control over the strategically important square [d4].} c5 {[%csl Rd4] Stopping d4 and it is more or less going to transpose to Closed Sicilian kind of positions: 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 d6 3.g3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 .} (3... e5 {is another viable option, aiming for a solid central grip and restricting White's pawn breaks. Both plans are equally playable, and the choice depends on the type of middlegame Black prefers.}) 4. Bg2 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] This position can also arise from 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.g3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 . Since White struggles to achieve [d4], Black's position is comfortable. The plans are straightforward – develop naturally, control the center, and prepare thematic breaks, depending on White's setup. Playing the Closed Sicilian as Black isn't a hard task here, as White's usual central expansion is restricted.} 5. f4 {White aims to place the knight on [f3], reinforcing central control and preparing natural development. Compared to setups with [Ne2], this allows White to exert more direct influence over [d4] and [e5], but at the cost of some flexibility.} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7]} (5... Rb8 {is also possible, preparing ...[b5]. The text move makes sense as 5...Nf6 will be met by 6.e5 . So this is the best way to develop the knight while keeping the [g7]-bishop free of any obstruction.}) 6. Nf3 Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. O-O d6 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb7b5] This is our setup – next, we will plan to roll out on the queenside with ...[Rb8] and ...[b5].} 9. Be3 {We will more or less reach this position, as all the moves look natural.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Preparing ...[b5].} 10. a4 {Stopping ...[b5].} Nd4 $10 {[%cal Ge7c6] One knight will be exchanged and the other knight on [e7] will come to [c6]. The [c8]-bishop will come out on [b7] via ...[b6]. The game is balanced.} (10... a6 {preparing ...[b5] is another plan.}) *

