1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8] Finachettoing the bishop to [g2] is another option for White. Grandmaster Quesada Perez played this against me in the chess24 Banter Blitz. Those were the good old days of Banter Blitz. Petition to chess.com to start those fun series. : Coming back to the position, White's setup is simple – bishop to [g2], knight to [e2], castle, pawn to [d3], bishop to [e3], pawn to [f4], queen to [d2], and so on. The drawback is that it is slow, and White has no proper central control over the strategically important square [d4].} c5 {[%csl Rd4] Stopping d4 and it is more or less going to transpose to Closed Sicilian kind of positions: 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 d6 3.g3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 .} (3... e5 {is another viable option, aiming for a solid central grip and restricting White's pawn breaks. Both plans are equally playable, and the choice depends on the type of middlegame Black prefers.}) 4. Bg2 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] This position can also arise from 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.g3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 . Since White struggles to achieve [d4], Black's position is comfortable. The plans are straightforward – develop naturally, control the center, and prepare thematic breaks, depending on White's setup. Playing the Closed Sicilian as Black isn't a hard task here, as White's usual central expansion is restricted.} 5. Nge2 d6 6. d3 {The starting position of the Closed Sicilian with [g3]. Here, Black has many plans.} Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (6... e6 {followed by ...[Nge7] is one plan. 6...e5 and ...[Nge7] is another one. The text move prepares to expand on the queenside with ...[b5].}) 7. a4 {It is logical to stop ...[b5] and is preferred by many strong White players like Dubov, Wei Yi, Rapport, and so on. The other options simply give Black free play with ...[b5].} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] White cannot avoid it anymore, but at least after the exchanges on [b5], White will gain some control over the a-file.} 8. O-O b5 9. axb5 axb5 10. f4 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge4e5,Gg2c6]} Bd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gd7] A useful waiting move against [e5] threats from White.} (10... b4 11. Nd5 e6 12. Ne3 Nge7 {is also playable, but White has some ideas like} 13. f5 {. I did not want to venture out there.}) 11. h3 (11. Nd5 Nf6 12. Ne3 Ng4 {chases the knight, and 11.Be3 is met by 11...b4 , when White cannot reroute their knight via [d5]-[e3].}) 11... Nf6 {Apart from developing the knight to [e7], we can, of course, develop it to the most obvious square on [f6]. Without ...[Bd7], White will have [e5], and this tactic does not exist here thanks to the [d7]-bishop protecting the [c6]-knight.} 12. g4 O-O 13. Ng3 Nd4 $10 {[%cal Gb5b4] And ...[b4] is on the cards next. White has no proper attack on the kingside and Black has a fine game.} *

