he [g8]-knight to [f6].}) ({Another option for Black is to kick the c3-knight immediately by} 8... b4 {, but White can reroute it to a better square after} 9. Nd5 e5 10. Ne3 {followed by the [f5] thrust.}) 9. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Ge2g3] This is one of White's plans to expand on the kingside with [g4], [Ng3], and so on.} Nf6 (9... b4 {is also possible, but} 10. Nd5 e6 11. Ne3 Nge7 12. f5 {leads to a different story.}) 10. g4 O-O ({Now} 10... b4 {is once again possible, as White cannot reroute with [Nd5]-[e3] like in the earlier cases. So it's an equally effective alternative. White will reply with} 11. Nb1 {followed by [Nd2]-[f3] and so on.}) 11. Ng3 b4 12. Nce2 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7b5,Gb5d4,Gg7a1] This key maneuver has to be noted, which improves Black's position of pieces. The plan is ...[Nc7]-[b5]-[d4] or ...[a5]-[a4]-[a3] and so on.} 13. f5 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3]} ({There's nothing wrong with the direct} 13... Nc7 {and then ...[a5]-[a4].}) 14. Rb1 a4 15. Kh2 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7b5] Black has brought all the pieces on the queenside. Meanwhile, it is not clear what are White's ideas on the kingside} 16. Bf4 a3 {Since White has removed the bishop from [c1], we penetrate.} 17. b3 Nb5 $15 {[%cal Gb5c3] And the knight is invading.} *

