he [g8]-knight to [f6].}) ({Another option for Black is to kick the c3-knight immediately by} 8... b4 {, but White can reroute it to a better square after} 9. Nd5 e5 10. Ne3 {followed by the [f5] thrust.}) 9. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Ge2g3] This is one of White's plans to expand on the kingside with [g4], [Ng3], and so on.} Nf6 (9... b4 {is also possible, but} 10. Nd5 e6 11. Ne3 Nge7 12. f5 {leads to a different story.}) 10. a3 {Keeping an eye on the ...[b4] pushes from Black.} O-O {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4]} 11. g4 {Now that Black's ...[b4] is not that effective, White plans to have some play on the kingside, but Black immediately advances the a-pawn, facilitating the ...[b4] plan.} a5 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 12. Be3 b4 {Now we can already push ...[b4], as White does not have a proper square for the [c3]-knight to shuffle to.} 13. axb4 axb4 14. Nb1 {Now Black can target the vulnerable [b2]-pawn.} h5 15. g5 Nh7 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 16. c3 bxc3 17. bxc3 e5 $15 {White's pawns are loose.} *

