he [g8]-knight to [f6].}) ({Another option for Black is to kick the c3-knight immediately by} 8... b4 {, but White can reroute it to a better square after} 9. Nd5 e5 10. Ne3 {followed by the [f5] thrust.}) 9. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Ge2g3] This is one of White's plans to expand on the kingside with [g4], [Ng3], and so on.} Nf6 (9... b4 {is also possible, but} 10. Nd5 e6 11. Ne3 Nge7 12. f5 {leads to a different story.}) 10. a3 {Keeping an eye on the ...[b4] pushes from Black.} O-O {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4]} 11. Be3 a5 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 12. Qd2 {[%cal Gc3d1] Vacating the square for the [c3]-knight so that when attacked by ...[b4], it can go to [d1] and then [f2].} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1] An important rerouting of the [f6]-knight as it is not doing much there. Also, Black prepares for ideas like ...[Nd4]. The [g7]-bishop is out in the jungle now.} 13. g4 Nd4 ({This is one of the typical ideas for Black to punch the knight on d4, but} 13... f5 {is also interesting here to stop White's advance further.}) 14. f5 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 (15. Nxe2 {loses the [b2]-pawn.}) 15... e6 {[%csl Rf5] Keeping the tension around the [f5]-pawn.} 16. Qf2 (16. fxg6 hxg6 {, keeping the pawn structure intact.} 17. Qd2 b4 18. Nd1 Nc7 19. Bh6 a4 {⩱ , and we get some nice play on the queenside. Though White is going to exchange the key piece on [g7], they have no proper attack on the kingside as the [d1]-knight is not well placed.}) 16... b4 17. axb4 axb4 18. Nd1 exf5 19. gxf5 gxf5 20. exf5 Kh8 $10 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg7f6,Ge8g7,Gf8g8] Followed by ...[Bf6] and ...[Ng7] and Black surrounds the [f5]-pawn. Black can also include ...[Rg8] in between.} *

