1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd1f3] Not many games here, but this is a logical developing move, eyeing the [f7]-spot. One of the main ideas for White next is [Qf3] to induce some weakness around Black's camp.} c5 {[%csl Gd4] Given a chance, we control the center with the active bishop on [g7].} 4. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7] This resembles the Scholar's mate, and we are no beginner to fall into it. :} e6 {After ...[e6], both the queen and the bishop hit a dead end.} 5. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6]} d6 {Preventing [Nd6] invasions.} 6. Qg3 {[%csl Rd6] I can see a top-level game here between Anton Guijarro and Bu Xiangzhi from 2024 Qatar Masters 2024.} Ke7 {[%csl Gd6,Ge7][%cal Ga7a6]} ({Nothing to worry about our king position as so far White is behind in development. Another option to protect the d6-pawn by} 6... Bf8 {is also possible, when play will continue after} 7. b3 Nc6 8. Bb2 e5 9. f4 {and so on.}) 7. d3 {White gives us a lot of tempi to get our pieces into the game with great energy.} a6 8. Nc3 b5 9. Bb3 Nf6 10. Nge2 ({In case of} 10. Bf4 {, Black has many good moves to choose from since White doesn't threaten anything. To emphasize that further, the silly engine suggests even} Ke8 {, preparing ...[Nh5], which would no longer be met by [Qh4]+, as} 11. Bxd6 $2 Nh5 {is game over for White.}) 10... Bb7 {All our pieces on perfect squares. The king's position can always be shuffled with ...[Re8] followed by ...[Kf8], so it's all good.} 11. f4 Nbd7 12. O-O (12. f5 exf5 13. Bf4 Qb6 {and Black has protected the vulnerable [d6]-pawn.}) 12... c4 13. dxc4 bxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxe4 $15 {[%cal Gd8c7] Followed by ...[Qc7] and Black is slightly better here with well-placed pieces and intact pawn structure.} *

