[PlyCount "28"]
[GameId "2159115892683515"]

1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd1f3] Not many games here, but this is a logical developing move, eyeing the [f7]-spot. One of the main ideas for White next is [Qf3] to induce some weakness around Black's camp.} c5 {[%csl Gd4] Given a chance, we control the center with the active bishop on [g7].} 4. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7] This resembles the Scholar's mate, and we are no beginner to fall into it. :} e6 {After ...[e6], both the queen and the bishop hit a dead end.} 5. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6]} d6 {Preventing [Nd6] invasions.} 6. Qg3 {[%csl Rd6] I can see a top-level game here between Anton Guijarro and Bu Xiangzhi from 2024 Qatar Masters 2024.} Ke7 {[%csl Gd6,Ge7][%cal Ga7a6]} ({Nothing to worry about our king position as so far White is behind in development. Another option to protect the d6-pawn by} 6... Bf8 {is also possible, when play will continue after} 7. b3 Nc6 8. Bb2 e5 9. f4 {and so on.}) 7. Be2 {White wants to play [d3] and develop their pieces without shutting down the light-squared bishop.} a6 8. Nc3 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] Against the queen on [g3].} 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. d3 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2,Gd4f3,Gh5h4] Removing the defender on [f3] to get ...[h4] in.} 11. Bd1 {[%csl Rc2,Gd1]} (11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Nd1 h4 {and Black is slightly better.}) 11... Kf8 {[%cal Gh5h4] Rerouting the king to a safer square and at the same time planning for the ...[h4] push.} (11... Kf8 {is the most precise, not allowing White to reposition the queen to [f3] after 11...Nxf3+ 12.Qxf3 , when ...[h4] becomes an empty shot.}) 12. h4 {Now White is planning to take on [d4] followed by [Ne2] and [f4], so we will have to exchange on [f3] first before developing our [g8]-knight.} Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Ne7 14. O-O Kg8 $10 {[%cal Gg8h7] Followed by ...[Kh7] and Black's position is comfortable.} *

