1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd1f3] Not many games here, but this is a logical developing move, eyeing the [f7]-spot. One of the main ideas for White next is [Qf3] to induce some weakness around Black's camp.} c5 {[%csl Gd4] Given a chance, we control the center with the active bishop on [g7].} 4. h4 {We need to always take care of the battering h-pawn, as White has a target towards our [g6]-pawn.} h5 {One way to completely stop the further advancement of the h-pawn.} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3f7]} e6 {[%csl Rc4,Rf3,Gf7]} 6. d4 $5 {It is very interesting to sacrifice the pawn to bring in the [c1]-bishop without wasting time.} cxd4 7. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6]} d5 ({Only move, as} 7... d6 {fails to} 8. Bf4 {.}) 8. exd5 exd5 {White can capture the pawn both ways.} 9. Bxd5 {[%cal Gf3f7] The drawback of capturing the pawn with the bishop is that the knight on [b5] is left without support.} Nf6 10. Bxb7 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxb5 12. Bxa8 O-O {[%csl Ra8,Re1][%cal Gb5f1] We are an exchange down, but White's king is vulnerable, and in addition to that, the bishop on [a8] is stuck.} 13. Ne2 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6e2] Adding more pressure, not allowing White to stabilize.} 14. a4 Qb6 15. O-O Nbd7 $15 {[%csl Ra8,Re2][%cal Gd7e5] Followed by ...[Ne5] and White is in trouble with all of their hanging pieces.} *

