1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd1f3] Not many games here, but this is a logical developing move, eyeing the [f7]-spot. One of the main ideas for White next is [Qf3] to induce some weakness around Black's camp.} c5 {[%csl Gd4] Given a chance, we control the center with the active bishop on [g7].} 4. h4 {We need to always take care of the battering h-pawn, as White has a target towards our [g6]-pawn.} h5 {One way to completely stop the further advancement of the h-pawn.} 5. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3f7]} e6 {[%csl Rc4,Rf3,Gf7]} 6. Nb5 d6 7. Qg3 Bf8 {[%csl Gd6,Gf8]} ({Here,} 7... Ke7 {is not accurate with the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5], as White can continue with} 8. d3 a6 9. Nc3 b5 10. Bb3 Nf6 {and the hole around the [g5]-square will begin to create trouble for Black after} 11. Bg5 {, which did not exist in the 4.Qf3 e6 5.Nb5 d6 6.Qg3 Ke7 7.d3 a6 8.Nc3 b5 9.Bb3 Nf6 line.}) ({Also,} 7... e5 {would be a strategic concession, and after} 8. Qb3 Nh6 9. Qd3 {, Black has to play} Bf8 {anyway.}) 8. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] This is the critical option to exploit the [a1]-[h8] diagonal. Otherwise, Black will just push the [b5]-knight by ...[a6] and bring the pieces to their original squares.} Nh6 $1 {Not a usual square for the knight, but perhaps it is understandable that developing the knight to [f6] will come under pressure from White's dark-squared bishop after [Bb2].} 9. Bb2 Rg8 {A weird position I must say. We cannot castle short anymore, but we do have some targets to play against, for instance, the queen on [g3]. All this works only thanks to the fact that White cannot open up the center easily.} 10. Nf3 (10. d4 {does not work due to} a6 {.}) 10... a6 11. Nc3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb7b5] Preventing the [d4] breakthrough, and next on cards is ...[b5].} 12. O-O b5 13. Be2 f6 $15 {[%cal Ga8a7,Gg6g5] Black has a very nice plan of bringing the other rook via [a7]-[g7] followed by ...[g5] with a strong attack. The computer evaluates this position as clearly better for Black.} *

