1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] There are some games here as well, like in 2.h4 . White again tries the Harry trick to exploit our ...[g6] push. Let's see if it is effective here.} h5 {[%csl Rd4,Rh4][%cal Gc7c5] Here, we don't have the ...[d5] counterattack like in the case of 2.h4, and hence, we will have to change our plan. The text move makes sense as we stop White's pawn advance, which will, in turn, stir up the kingside.} 4. d4 {White will have to occupy the center. Otherwise, we will seal the center with ...[c5]. In the previous move, too, we could execute it, but the [h5] thrust from White was annoying.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (4... d6 {is definitely possible, but I like this direction more, getting ready to challenge the center with ...[d5].}) {One might ask why not 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 . There is a difference with the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5], as now 4.f4 simply punctures the [g4]-square.} 5. Nf3 d5 6. e5 {[%csl Rg7] It looks logical to barricade the [g7]-bishop, but on the other hand, White gives up a lot of squares for Black; for example, the [f5]-square can be conquered by the ...[Nh6]-[f5] maneuver.} Bg4 $1 {Now you can see that if White's pawn was on [h2], they could immediately push [h3], asking questions to the bishop. Now the black bishop on [g4] has a comfortable retired life there without any botheration.} 7. Be2 Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f5] Black is going to rule the light squares.} 8. Ng5 Bf5 $10 {[%cal Gf7f6] Next, we can plan ...[f6] and push the knight back.} *

