1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] There are some games here as well, like in 2.h4 . White again tries the Harry trick to exploit our ...[g6] push. Let's see if it is effective here.} h5 {[%csl Rh4,Rd4][%cal Gc7c5] Here, we don't have the ...[d5] counterattack like in the case of 2.h4, and hence, we will have to change our plan. The text move makes sense as we stop White's pawn advance, which will, in turn, stir up the kingside.} 4. d4 {White will have to occupy the center. Otherwise, we will seal the center with ...[c5]. In the previous move, too, we could execute it, but the [h5] thrust from White was annoying.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (4... d6 {is definitely possible, but I like this direction more, getting ready to challenge the center with ...[d5].}) {One might ask why not 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 . There is a difference with the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5], as now 4.f4 simply punctures the [g4]-square.} 5. Nf3 d5 6. exd5 {Another alternative for White rather than pushing [e5].} cxd5 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {We cannot take back with the knight because the [d5]-pawn is not well aided.} 9. Ne5 Bxe5 (9... Qf5 {9.Nxd5 Bxe5 is also fine for Black.}) 10. dxe5 Nc6 {This variation will fizzle out to an endgame.} 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7]} O-O-O {[%csl Rd5]} 13. c4 Nxe5 14. b3 Nd3+ $10 {And it's totally equal.} *

