1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] There are some games here as well, like in 2.h4 . White again tries the Harry trick to exploit our ...[g6] push. Let's see if it is effective here.} h5 {[%csl Rd4,Rh4][%cal Gc7c5] Here, we don't have the ...[d5] counterattack like in the case of 2.h4, and hence, we will have to change our plan. The text move makes sense as we stop White's pawn advance, which will, in turn, stir up the kingside.} 4. d4 {White will have to occupy the center. Otherwise, we will seal the center with ...[c5]. In the previous move, too, we could execute it, but the [h5] thrust from White was annoying.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (4... d6 {is definitely possible, but I like this direction more, getting ready to challenge the center with ...[d5].}) {One might ask why not 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 . There is a difference with the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5], as now 4.f4 simply punctures the [g4]-square.} 5. Nf3 d5 6. Be2 dxe4 {Now it's time to dissolve the center to bring our pieces out freely.} 7. Nxe4 Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 8. Neg5 (8. Nxf6+ {will be dealt with} exf6 9. O-O O-O {and Black's position is solid. With the text move, White has sealed their knight to [g5], but there is nothing to worry about as we also have the [g4]-square for our knight/bishop.}) 8... c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rd8d1,Rg7a1]} 9. dxc5 (9. O-O cxd4 10. Ne5 O-O 11. Bc4 e6 {and the [f7]-pawn is safeguarded.}) 9... Qxd1+ 10. Bxd1 Nbd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 11. O-O O-O ({Nothing wrong with} 11... Nxc5 {, but it gives some tempo for White after} 12. Be3 {. So we're delaying that one more move while consolidating our position.}) 12. Re1 (12. Be3 Ng4 {is the problem.}) 12... Nxc5 13. Rxe7 (13. Be3 b6 {and} 14. Ne5 {is no longer effective, as we have already castled and safeguarded the [f7]-pawn.}) 13... Nd5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5][%cal Gg7a1] The dominating knights – also, now the [g7]-[a1] diagonal is under fire.} 14. Re1 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3] With great compensation; ...[a4]-[a3] is on the cards next.} *

