1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] There are some games here as well, like in 2.h4 . White again tries the Harry trick to exploit our ...[g6] push. Let's see if it is effective here.} h5 {[%csl Rd4,Rh4][%cal Gc7c5] Here, we don't have the ...[d5] counterattack like in the case of 2.h4, and hence, we will have to change our plan. The text move makes sense as we stop White's pawn advance, which will, in turn, stir up the kingside.} 4. d4 {White will have to occupy the center. Otherwise, we will seal the center with ...[c5]. In the previous move, too, we could execute it, but the [h5] thrust from White was annoying.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (4... d6 {is definitely possible, but I like this direction more, getting ready to challenge the center with ...[d5].}) {One might ask why not 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 . There is a difference with the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5], as now 4.f4 simply punctures the [g4]-square.} 5. Nf3 d5 6. Bf4 {The critical line.} dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nf6 8. Neg5 (8. Nxf6+ {will be always captured back with} exf6 {. We will use the open e-file for our rooks, and the double pawns control a lot of squares; they also assure that our king on [g8] will be extra safe.}) 8... O-O 9. Bc4 Nbd7 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd7b6]} 10. O-O Nb6 11. Bd3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} 12. Qd2 {Drifting away from the pin along the [h5]-[d1] diagonal.} Nfd7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc6c5] White was threatening [Ne5], so let's stop it. On the other hand, we prepare ...[c5].} 13. c3 c5 14. Be4 {[%cal Ge4b7]} Qc8 {[%csl Gb7,Gc8] And it's a double-edged position. Both sides have their own advantages and disadvantages. Next on the agenda is ...[cxd4] followed by ...[Nf6].} *

