1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] There are some games here as well, like in 2.h4 . White again tries the Harry trick to exploit our ...[g6] push. Let's see if it is effective here.} h5 {[%csl Rd4,Rh4][%cal Gc7c5] Here, we don't have the ...[d5] counterattack like in the case of 2.h4, and hence, we will have to change our plan. The text move makes sense as we stop White's pawn advance, which will, in turn, stir up the kingside.} 4. d4 {White will have to occupy the center. Otherwise, we will seal the center with ...[c5]. In the previous move, too, we could execute it, but the [h5] thrust from White was annoying.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (4... d6 {is definitely possible, but I like this direction more, getting ready to challenge the center with ...[d5].}) {One might ask why not 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 . There is a difference with the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5], as now 4.f4 simply punctures the [g4]-square.} 5. Bc4 {[%csl Rd5] White thinks that they have accomplished a great deed by stopping ...[d5], but little did they know that it is an unstoppable force.} d5 {Bam!! We don't care about the pawn.} 6. exd5 Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} (6... b5 {is also interesting.} 7. Bb3 b4 {and taking back on [d5]. But I like the text move more, as we create a very interesting game with more energy and activity in regards to loosing a pawn.}) 7. dxc6 Nxc6 {[%csl Rd4] We are delving into a completely fresh position with no games. So, let's consider some of White's options in greater depth.} 8. Nf3 O-O {[%cal Gc8g4]} ({The direct} 8... Bg4 {is met by} 9. d5 Na5 10. Bb5+ {and we have to bring back our bishop to [d7]. Hence, I would like to castle and then pin with ...[Bg4].}) 9. Ne2 Bg4 {[%cal Rg4d1]} 10. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4] That was the whole point of [Ne2], to strengthen the [d4]-pawn, but now we just shatter White's pawn structure.} Bxf3 11. gxf3 e5 12. Bg5 exd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 {White is left with an isolated pawn now.} Qd6 $10 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6d5] With ...[Nd5] coming next, Black has nothing to worry about.} *

