g blunder due to} 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Bxb5+ {, winning the queen.}) 11. Be3 Ng4 {and White is under pressure from the knight on [g4], and the [d4]-pawn is hanging again.}) 10... O-O 11. f3 {[%cal Gc1e3]} ({To facilitate Be3, as the direct} 11. Be3 {is met by} Ng4 {. Here, Black has a couple of options like ...[Bf5], ...[Na5], ...[Ra7]-[d7] ideas or directly ...[Na5] and ...[Ra7]-[d7] or even ...[Bb7] and ...[Na5]. In all three cases, Black maintains good compensation.}) 11... Bf5 12. Bg5 Ra7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ga7d7] A very nice rook maneuver, aiming for the [d4]-pawn after ...[Rd7].} 13. Qd2 Rd7 {[%csl Rd4]} 14. Rad1 {[%csl Gd4]} Qc7 {[%cal Gf8d8]} 15. Qe1 Rfd8 16. Qf2 Na5 {[%csl Rb3,Rc2][%cal Gf5c2] Black has enough compensation for the pawn thanks to our active pieces.} *

