1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] There are some games here as well, like in 2.h4 . White again tries the Harry trick to exploit our ...[g6] push. Let's see if it is effective here.} h5 {[%csl Rd4,Rh4][%cal Gc7c5] Here, we don't have the ...[d5] counterattack like in the case of 2.h4, and hence, we will have to change our plan. The text move makes sense as we stop White's pawn advance, which will, in turn, stir up the kingside.} 4. d4 {White will have to occupy the center. Otherwise, we will seal the center with ...[c5]. In the previous move, too, we could execute it, but the [h5] thrust from White was annoying.} c6 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (4... d6 {is definitely possible, but I like this direction more, getting ready to challenge the center with ...[d5].}) {One might ask why not 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 . There is a difference with the inclusion of [h4] and ...[h5], as now 4.f4 simply punctures the [g4]-square.} 5. Be3 d5 {[%csl Re4]} 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Obviously showcasing that White is going to castle long.} dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nd7 {[%cal Gg8f6]} ({Since White is planning to castle long, we delay ...Nf6 and prepare for it with ...Nd7.} 7... Nf6 8. Nxf6+ exf6 9. O-O-O {followed by [f3] and [g4] is slightly scarier, though it's entirely possible for Black.}) 8. Nf3 Ngf6 9. Neg5 O-O 10. Bd3 Nb6 $132 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gb6d5] Black is fine in this complex position. We have many ideas like ...[Ng4], ...[Nd5] or ...[Bf5], and so on.} *

