1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} c5 {[%csl Rd4] X [d4]. One might think that we got tricked into a Closed Sicilian Grand Prix Attack, but that is not the case as Black is very comfortable in the ensuing lines, and the tabiya is actually quite simple to learn. So there is no reason to shy away.} ({If it is really bothering you, then you can have a look at the} 3... d6 {and 4...Bg4 alternative.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 {This looks like a strange move, but upon spotting many of Carlsen's games here, I delved it deeper and understood the point. White wants to play [Bc4] and secure the bishop on [a2] when chased.} (5. a3 {One of the ideas for White is to push b4 if Black plays} e6 {, waiting for White's bishop to come to [c4] to counter it with ...[Nge7] and ...[d5] in one go.}) 5... b6 $1 {We also wait for White to play [Bc4] so that we can insert ...[e6], ...[Nge7], and ...[d5].} ({Of course, there's nothing wrong with} 5... d6 {. Play will continue} 6. Bc4 e6 {and we waste one tempo on ...[Nge7] and ...[d5] compared to the immediate ...[e6], ...[Nge7], and ...[d5] plan.}) ({The direct} 5... e6 {is met by an interesting} 6. b4 {, leading to a complex game.}) 6. Bc4 e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5]} 7. e5 ({Now} 7. b4 {is not possible since the [c5]-pawn is well guarded.}) 7... Nge7 8. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6]} O-O 9. O-O (9. Nd6 Nf5 {and Black immediately challenges the annoying knight on [d6].}) 9... d5 $1 10. exd6 Nf5 $17 {A nice idea, freeing our position. To my surprise, the computer evaluates this position as clearly better for Black with -1.0.} *

