1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} c5 {[%csl Rd4] X [d4]. One might think that we got tricked into a Closed Sicilian Grand Prix Attack, but that is not the case as Black is very comfortable in the ensuing lines, and the tabiya is actually quite simple to learn. So there is no reason to shy away.} ({If it is really bothering you, then you can have a look at the} 3... d6 {and 4...Bg4 alternative.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a4 ({Like in the line with} 5. a3 {, White wants to secure their bishop to [a2] after [Bc4] when attacked by ...[d5]. With this advance of the a-pawn to two squares with 5.a4 , White also prevents ...[a6] and ...[b5] from Black for the time being.}) 5... a6 6. Bc4 e6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] Blunting the bishop on [c4].} 7. d3 Nge7 8. O-O d5 9. Ba2 O-O $132 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (9... O-O {Though the white pawn is on a4, Black anyway can strike with ...b5. For example, let's say} 10. Kh1 b5 11. axb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Nb4 {and the pin on the a-file is deadly.}) *

