1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} c5 {[%csl Rd4] X [d4]. One might think that we got tricked into a Closed Sicilian Grand Prix Attack, but that is not the case as Black is very comfortable in the ensuing lines, and the tabiya is actually quite simple to learn. So there is no reason to shy away.} ({If it is really bothering you, then you can have a look at the} 3... d6 {and 4...Bg4 alternative.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6] (The idea of trading on c6 to damage Black's structure is well-known from Rossolimo Sicilians 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 , where White wants to double Black's pawns and gain long-term positional pressure.)} (5. Bb5 {However, in this case, we can react with} Nd4 {. This move challenges the bishop immediately, forcing White to make a decision – leave the bishop where it is, retreat, or trade on [d4].}) 5... Nd4 {It's ideal to play ...[Nd4] when White has a knight on [c3], as capturing on [d4] allows Black to recapture with [cxd4], gaining a tempo. Also, Black avoids [Bxc6], which would yield structural weaknesses.} 6. O-O {This was played a lot by Grandmaster Aryan Tari. The point is to finish development and aim for an attack with [f5], but on the other hand, White loses the bishop on [b5].} Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d5 8. exd5 (8. e5 d4 {and the knight on [b5] is stuck.}) 8... a6 $1 (8... Qxd5 {would end the game after} 9. Nc7+ {.}) 9. Nc3 Nf6 $10 {[%cal Gf6d5] And next, we can capture on [d5] with a good game.} *

