1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} c5 {[%csl Rd4] X [d4]. One might think that we got tricked into a Closed Sicilian Grand Prix Attack, but that is not the case as Black is very comfortable in the ensuing lines, and the tabiya is actually quite simple to learn. So there is no reason to shy away.} ({If it is really bothering you, then you can have a look at the} 3... d6 {and 4...Bg4 alternative.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8]} e6 {[%csl Rc4] Restricting the bishop on [c4] immediately.} 6. f5 {This looks flashy but does not work effectively.} gxf5 7. d3 (7. exf5 d5 8. Bb5 Nge7 9. fxe6 fxe6 10. O-O O-O {and Black is on top, as we have good control over the center.}) 7... Nge7 8. O-O O-O {Though our king is exposed, the bishop on [g7] simply covers it from any direct attacks. To add to that, we have an extra pawn taking away a lot of squares from White's pieces.} 9. Qe1 {Shifting the queen to target our king, but this is slow.} fxe4 10. dxe4 d5 11. exd5 exd5 12. Bd3 Bf5 $17 {We have one pawn more with no attack for White.} *

