1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} c5 {[%csl Rd4] X [d4]. One might think that we got tricked into a Closed Sicilian Grand Prix Attack, but that is not the case as Black is very comfortable in the ensuing lines, and the tabiya is actually quite simple to learn. So there is no reason to shy away.} ({If it is really bothering you, then you can have a look at the} 3... d6 {and 4...Bg4 alternative.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8]} e6 {[%csl Rc4] Restricting the bishop on [c4] immediately.} 6. O-O Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Compared to the Grand Prix with 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 d6 tabiyas, Black gets the ...[d5] push in one go rather than ...[d6] followed by ...[e6] and ...[d5].} 7. d3 d5 8. Bb3 O-O {Black has finished development. The only thing we have to take care of is the plan of [Qe1]-[h4] with a kingside attack.} 9. e5 {White blocks the [g7]-bishop, but Black can release it anytime with the ...[f6] break.} Nf5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf5d4]} 10. Ne2 {White prevents ...[Nd4] jumps, but the drawback is that Black can now expand on the queenside with ...[b5] immediately.} b5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc5c4] Apart from the queenside expansion, we threaten to trap the bishop with ...[c4].} 11. c3 {Making room for the bishop to escape to [c2].} d4 12. cxd4 Ncxd4 $15 {White's backward pawn on [d3], in addition to Black's nice outpost on the [d4]-square, gives Black a better game.} *

