1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} d6 ({If you are not a Sicilian player and would like to stick to the setup of Modern/Pirc, then one can prefer this direction. The main suggestion is} 3... c5 {, which transposes to the Grand Prix Attack from the Closed Sicilian.}) 4. Nf3 (4. d4 {transposes to the Austrian Attack.}) 4... Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} (4... c5 {is again possible, transposing to the Grand Prix tabiya.}) 5. d4 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 {White sacrifices the pawn for activity, but I don't think they have some really special dynamism, and we can simply grab the central pawn. I always emphasize that the central pawns are an integral part of the position, and if they can be grabbed without too much danger, go ahead. :} Bxd4 7. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gg2g4,Gh2h4] White has the bishop pair and aims to castle long with [g4] and [h4] to follow, trying to create some play.} a6 $1 ({This is important. The direct} 7... Nc6 {is possible but is met by the} 8. Bb5 {pin and it is not that comfortable. So why allow it in the first place?}) 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. g4 Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] We cannot castle short, as White is rolling their pawns with [g4], [h4], and hence, this move makes sense in preparing a long castle.} 10. h4 O-O-O $10 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8e7] Followed by ...[e6] and Black's position is intact.} *

