1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} d6 ({If you are not a Sicilian player and would like to stick to the setup of Modern/Pirc, then one can prefer this direction. The main suggestion is} 3... c5 {, which transposes to the Grand Prix Attack from the Closed Sicilian.}) 4. Nf3 (4. d4 {transposes to the Austrian Attack.}) 4... Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} (4... c5 {is again possible, transposing to the Grand Prix tabiya.}) 5. d4 Bxf3 6. gxf3 {White maintains the pawn on [d4] but, on the other hand, exposes the king.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4] Seizing the opportunity to dampen the king's position.} 7. fxe5 {8.dxe5 is also met by 8...Qh4+ 9.Ke2 Nc6 followed by long castle, with great activity.} Qh4+ 8. Ke2 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] Momentum is the key here, and we hurry up to castle long to continue the attack around White's king.} 9. Nb5 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6] This is critical.} O-O-O 10. exd6 a6 $1 ({Important, as} 10... cxd6 {loses the momentum and closes the key d-file for our rook.} 11. d5 {and White has a huge advantage.}) 11. d5 (11. dxc7 {is met by} Rd7 {and White has the knight on [b5] and the [d4]-pawn hanging.}) 11... axb5 12. dxc6 Rxd6 (12... Rxd6 13. cxb7+ Kxb7 14. Qe1 Qh5 {and White's king is still not secure. This factor gives Black decent compensation.}) *

