1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 {White delays the [d4] push for the time being with some other intentions in mind, but it is not efficient as central control is key for any opening, and this option delays it.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7a1] Make way for the bishop!} 3. f4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3] White pushes the other pawn to gain control over the [e5]-square but the drawback is clear: the white king is now slightly exposed since the dark squares are exposed. If only White gets [d4] next, they will have more space like in the main lines of the Modern, but the drawback of pushing the f-pawn first is that we can prevent the [d4] advance instantly.} d6 ({If you are not a Sicilian player and would like to stick to the setup of Modern/Pirc, then one can prefer this direction. The main suggestion is} 3... c5 {, which transposes to the Grand Prix Attack from the Closed Sicilian.}) 4. Nf3 (4. d4 {transposes to the Austrian Attack.}) 4... Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} (4... c5 {is again possible, transposing to the Grand Prix tabiya.}) 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 e6 $1 (6... Nc6 {is met by} 7. Bb5 {again. We play 6...e6 so that when ...[Nc6] and [Bb5] happen over the board, we can immediately provide support to the [c6]-knight with ...[Nge7].}) 7. b3 (7. d3 c5 {followed by ...[Nc6] leads to a balanced game. We don't have the bishop pair, but on the other hand, the bishops are not of greater use as the position is closed and not an open one where bishops thrive in a dangerous manner.}) 7... Nc6 8. Bb5 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7c6,Ga7a6] And next ...[a6] is on the cards. Black is totally fine here.} *

