[GameId "2159115893338904"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Be3 {[%csl Rb2] This is a bit unusual as White develops the knights first.} c5 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2] Making use of the fact that [dxc5] is not possible due to the hanging pawn on [b2].} 5. Ne2 (5. Nc3 cxd4 {and White will have to take back with the bishop, which is not a good sign.} 6. Bxd4 Nf6 {and the bishop on [d4] will be under pressure after ...[Nc6].}) 5... Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 6. Nbc3 (6. Qd2 Nc6 {and White cannot maintain the tension anymore. White is clearly worse, as they will have to drop the [d4] or [b2]-pawn.}) 6... Qxb2 7. Rb1 (7. Nb5 cxd4 8. Rb1 Qxa2 {, and unfortunately, it is a repetition after} 9. Ra1 Qb2 {.}) 7... Qa3 {[%cal Ga3a5]} 8. Qd2 Qa5 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. Rb5 Qd8 $10 (10... Qd8 {Black is fine in this endgame arising after} 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Bxc5 b6 {.}) *

