1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Be3 {[%csl Rb2] This is a bit unusual as White develops the knights first.} c5 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2] Making use of the fact that [dxc5] is not possible due to the hanging pawn on [b2].} 5. Ne2 (5. Nc3 cxd4 {and White will have to take back with the bishop, which is not a good sign.} 6. Bxd4 Nf6 {and the bishop on [d4] will be under pressure after ...[Nc6].}) 5... Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 6. Nbc3 (6. Qd2 Nc6 {and White cannot maintain the tension anymore. White is clearly worse, as they will have to drop the [d4] or [b2]-pawn.}) 6... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} ({A playable alternative to} 6... Qxb2 {, to keep the game going rather than a forced draw, which happens after capturing the pawn on [b2].}) 7. dxc5 Qxb2 {[%cal Gg7c3]} 8. Rc1 dxc5 9. Nd5 {[%cal Gd5c7]} (9. Bxc5 Bg4 10. f3 Rd8 {, all the pieces are engaged with tempo.} 11. Qa4 Bd7 {⇆ and the position is quite scary for White with discovered threats like ...[Ne5]-[d3]+.}) 9... Kf8 {Away from the [Nc7]+ fork.} 10. Nec3 Nf6 11. Na4 Qe5 12. Nxc5 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e3] Complete chaos.} 13. Bf4 Qd4 {[%cal Gd4f2]} 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 {[%csl Rc5,Rf2]} 15. Nd3 f5 $132 {[%csl Gc8,Gd4,Gg4][%cal Gc8f5] And it's a game. I like Black's position as our pieces are active.} *

