1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. f3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gb1c3,Gg1e2] Trying for a Sämisch setup with [Be3], [Nc3], [Nge2], and so on. Once again waiting for Black to play ...[Nf6] so that White can steer the waters to King's Indian.} f5 $1 {[%csl Re4] Thanks to the fact that we have not committed ...[Nf6].} 5. Nc3 (5. exf5 Bxf5 6. Nc3 Nc6 7. d5 Nd4 {followed by ...[e5] seals the active knight on [d4].}) 5... fxe4 6. fxe4 Nf6 7. Nf3 O-O {Black has swiftly accomplished development and has fine control over the f-file.} 8. Be2 c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Challenging the center.} 9. d5 Nbd7 10. O-O Ng4 $10 {[%csl Rd4,Re3,Rf2,Rg1][%cal Gd7e5] Next on the agenda is ...[Nde5], and Black gains supreme control over the dark squares with a fine game.} *

