1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. f4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4] Aiming for a Four Pawns Attack, but since our knight is not on [f6] like in the King's Indian, we do have some extra options, and we make use of that.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} (4... f5 {is also very interesting, challenging the [e4]-pawn.}) 5. Nf3 (5. d5 Nd4 {secures the knight on [d4], and if} 6. Ne2 {, then we can protect it with} e5 {.}) 5... Bg4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Adding more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Be3 e5 {[%csl Rd4,Rf4]} 7. fxe5 dxe5 8. d5 Bxf3 ({An immediate} 8... Nd4 {is also possible, but White can perhaps play} 9. Nbd2 {and kind of maintain the knight on [f3]. Hence, we take on [f3] first.}) 9. gxf3 (9. Qxf3 Nd4 {is slightly worse for White, as they cannot challenge the [d4]-knight, and the [e4]-pawn is left lonely without any proper strengthening.}) 9... Nd4 10. Nc3 c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Ge5] Supporting the knight on [d4].} 11. Qa4+ Kf8 $1 (11... Qd7 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7 13. Bh3+ {and long castle gives White an advantage, as our king is vulnerable. So we refrain from it.}) 12. O-O-O b6 $10 {[%csl Gb6,Gc5,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gg7h6] Followed by ...[Bh6] next, and we exchange the key dark-squared bishop, and our king secures a safe spot on [g7].} *

