1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Pinning the [f3]-knight creates additional pressure on the [d4]-pawn – the advantages of not committing to ...[Nf6]. Now we can counter the center with ...[c5] or ...[Nc6] next.} 5. d5 {With this advance White prevents ...[Nc6] from Black, which would pressurize the [d4]-pawn.} Nd7 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 {The queen is slightly misplaced on [f3] under the radar of ...[Ne5] sometimes.} Ngf6 8. Nc3 O-O {Next, Black will undermine the [d5]-pawn with either ...[e6] or ...[c6] depending on the situation.} 9. Be2 (9. Bd3 {will come under the radar of} Ne5 {.}) 9... e6 $1 {The best way to undermine the [d5]-pawn.} (9... c6 {is inacurrate due to} 10. O-O Rc8 11. Bd3 cxd5 12. exd5 {, which is key, and White is slightly better. If White is forced to take back with the c-pawn on [d5], then we have good counterplay, but that is not the case here.}) 10. O-O Nc5 11. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} ({The direct} 11. b4 {fails to} Ncxe4 {, as the rook on [a1] will be under attack.}) 11... exd5 (11... a5 {maintaining the tension is also possible.}) 12. cxd5 (12. exd5 a5 {followed by ...[Nfd7] and Black has easy play.}) 12... Qe7 {[%csl Re4]} 13. Bd3 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Rae8 {[%csl Re4]} 15. Re1 Nd7 $10 {[%cal Gf7f5] Followed by ...[f5] and Black is totally fine.} *

