1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Pinning the [f3]-knight creates additional pressure on the [d4]-pawn – the advantages of not committing to ...[Nf6]. Now we can counter the center with ...[c5] or ...[Nc6] next.} 5. d5 {With this advance White prevents ...[Nc6] from Black, which would pressurize the [d4]-pawn.} Nd7 6. Be2 c6 {[%csl Rd5]} ({Undermining the pawn on d5. Apart from that,} 6... Nc5 {is also possible.}) 7. O-O Rc8 $1 (7... Rc8 {A subtle move with the point being: when White plays} 8. Nc3 {, Black can take on [d5], and White will not be able to recapture with the e-pawn.} cxd5 9. exd5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Rxc4 {is the problem.}) 8. Nc3 cxd5 9. cxd5 Ngf6 {Black has immense play on the open c-file.} 10. Be3 Rxc3 $1 {A nice shot.} 11. bxc3 Nxe4 {[%cal Ge4c3]} 12. Rc1 Nxc3 {One more pawn in the bag.} 13. Qd2 Ne4 14. Qb4 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nec5 {[%cal Gb7b6] Black has a very good compensation with a nice outpost for the knight on [c5], blocking White from entering into Black's seventh rank.} *

