1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Pinning the [f3]-knight creates additional pressure on the [d4]-pawn – the advantages of not committing to ...[Nf6]. Now we can counter the center with ...[c5] or ...[Nc6] next.} 5. Be2 {White has to unpin it; otherwise, Black's ...[c5] will become too powerful. This is by far the top choice, according to the lichess database.} Bxf3 ({Clarifying matters.} 5... Nc6 {is also possible, but it gives White some extra options like} 6. Nbd2 {.}) 6. Bxf3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. d5 {This allows Black to seal the knight on [d4].} Nd4 8. Nc3 c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4]} 9. O-O ({If} 9. Be3 {, then we have} Qb6 {, attacking the [b2]-pawn.} 10. Rb1 Nxf3+ {and White is forced to take} 11. gxf3 {, and we can shatter their pawn structure further by} Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qa6 {with good practical play.}) 9... Nf6 10. Be3 O-O ({We can play} 10... Nd7 {as well. Sacrificing the pawn only helps us to open up the [g7]-bishop and take control over the dark squares. Moreover, it leads to opposite-colored bishop kinds of positions, even if, in the worst case, some sort of ending happens. We don't need to worry about it too much, as an extra pawn is not of great importance.}) 11. Bxd4 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Nd7 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 13. Qd2 Qa5 {[%cal Gg7c3] Planning ...[Bxc3] to weaken White's pawns.} 14. Rac1 {[%cal Gc1c3]} a6 $132 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ga5d2,Gg7b2] Followed by ...[b5] and we get good counterplay. Black's pieces are active, and White has to answer every threat from Black.} *

