1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Pinning the [f3]-knight creates additional pressure on the [d4]-pawn – the advantages of not committing to ...[Nf6]. Now we can counter the center with ...[c5] or ...[Nc6] next.} 5. Be2 {White has to unpin it; otherwise, Black's ...[c5] will become too powerful. This is by far the top choice, according to the lichess database.} Bxf3 ({Clarifying matters.} 5... Nc6 {is also possible, but it gives White some extra options like} 6. Nbd2 {.}) 6. Bxf3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. Be3 e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. dxe5 {White releases the tension in the center and gives easy play for Black.} dxe5 9. Nc3 Nd4 {In these lines, the knight always lands on [d4].} 10. Qa4+ c6 11. O-O-O Nf6 12. Ne2 Nd7 {[%cal Gg7d4] With a concrete idea in mind.} 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Bxd4 Nb6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] The point – once we head to opposite-colored bishops where we have full control over the dark squares, our bishop is clearly better placed than the opponent's. On the downside, we are a pawn down.} 15. Bxb6 Qxb6 $10 {[%cal Gb6f2,Gb6b2] Next, we can castle and bring our rook to [d8] and the bishop on [f3] is stuck and cannot move freely, as the [b6]-queen always eyes the [f2]-pawn.} *

