1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. dxe5 {I'm not a big fan of this move, as it releases the tension, but some people would like to exchange queens. So, for them, we need to know how to play this endgame.} dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Bg5+ f6 8. O-O-O+ Nd7 9. Bd2 Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f7,Gc7c6,Gd8c7,Gd8e7]} ({There are many plans for Black. The text move is one of them, aiming for a ...Nf7, ...c6, ...Kc7/e7 setup. Apart from} 9... Nh6 {, there is also 9...Bh6 and so on.}) 10. Be2 c6 11. h4 Nf7 12. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} Bh6 $10 {[%cal Gd8e7] It is important to stop White from pushing [h6], as that will restrict our pieces. Black is rock solid here with ...[Ke7] next.} *

