1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. dxe5 {I'm not a big fan of this move, as it releases the tension, but some people would like to exchange queens. So, for them, we need to know how to play this endgame.} dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. f4 {White wants to open up the game.} Be6 8. Nf3 {[%csl Re5]} Nc6 9. fxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 (10. Bg5+ Kc8 11. O-O-O b6 {and Black escapes with the king to [b7].}) 10... Nxf3+ 11. gxf3 c6 12. O-O-O+ Ke8 13. Kc2 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6h5] One of the ideas is ...[Nh5] and ...[Be5] to control the dark squares.} 14. Be3 Ke7 (14... b6 {first seems like a very natural move to take away the [c5]-square from White's dark-squared bishop, but it has a positional drawback. After} 15. Be2 Ke7 16. a4 {and [a5] next, White just found a target on [b6] to annoy us with.}) ({By playing} 14... Ke7 {first, Black remains flexible. For example,} 15. Bc5+ Ke8 16. a4 {can now be met by} Nd7 {or 16...a5 with a balanced endgame.}) 15. Bc5+ Ke8 $10 {[%cal Gb7b6] Followed by ...[b6], kicking the bishop, and then again ...[Ke7], when Black connects the rooks with a fine game.} *

