1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. dxe5 {I'm not a big fan of this move, as it releases the tension, but some people would like to exchange queens. So, for them, we need to know how to play this endgame.} dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nf3 f6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6] Fortifying the pawn on [e5] and also facilitating ...[Be6] without the need to be concerned about [Ng5] jumps. The black knight on [g8] will either land on [e7] or [h6]-[f7].} 8. b4 {Played two times by the strong Polish GM Dariusz Swiercz.} Be6 9. Be2 Bf8 {[%csl Rb4]} 10. Rb1 a5 11. a3 axb4 {With this operation, Black has taken control over the a-file.} 12. axb4 Bh6 13. Bb2 Nd7 $10 {[%cal Gg8e7] Followed by ...[Ne7] and Black's position is solid here.} *

