1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. d5 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2] White's idea is to go for [Bd3], [Nge2], [O-O], and then expand on the queenside.} a5 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb8a6] Curbing the expansion on the queenside, especially [b4] stuff from White, which would set the queenside on fire. Next on the cards is the ...[Na6]-[c5] maneuver, securing the knight on [c5].} 6. Bd3 (6. Be3 Na6 {and White has nothing better than} 7. Bd3 {transposing.}) 6... Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]} 7. Be3 h5 $1 {[%cal Gg7h6]} ({We can also play the direct} 7... Bh6 {, but then after} 8. Bxh6 Nxh6 9. Qd2 {, we will have to waste some time with the knight for ...[Ng4]-[f6] and so on. With the text move, we not only plan for ...[Bh6] next but also expand in a nice manner.}) 8. Nge2 Bh6 {With the long diagonal closed, we should trade the bishop.} 9. Bxh6 Nxh6 10. Qd2 f5 11. f3 Bd7 $10 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gf5f4,Gd8f6,Gh6f7] We have a comfortable game with many ideas like ...[Nc5], ...[Qf6], ...[Nf7], and so on.} *

