1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. d5 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2] White's idea is to go for [Bd3], [Nge2], [O-O], and then expand on the queenside.} a5 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb8a6] Curbing the expansion on the queenside, especially [b4] stuff from White, which would set the queenside on fire. Next on the cards is the ...[Na6]-[c5] maneuver, securing the knight on [c5].} 6. Bd3 (6. Be3 Na6 {and White has nothing better than} 7. Bd3 {transposing.}) 6... Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]} 7. Bc2 Qe7 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({The direct} 7... f5 {is met by} 8. exf5 gxf5 9. Qh5+ {, so Black plays ...[Qe7] first to interpose it with ...[Qf7].}) 8. Nge2 f5 9. exf5 gxf5 10. O-O Nh6 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gh6][%cal Ge8g8,Gg7a1]} (10... Nf6 {is met by} 11. Ng3 {and we are forced to push the pawn to [f4] in an unfavorable version, weakening a lot of light squares on the go.}) 11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Preparing [b4], which is the key push.} O-O 12. b4 {White can afford to play [b4] here as our rook is not protected, and hence, we cannot capture on [b4] twice.} Kh8 $1 {Scooting the king so that the rook can come to [g8] in some of the lines and create play.} 13. Bd2 Bd7 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf8a8] Connecting the rooks, and the [b4]-pawn is now under attack.} 14. Rb1 axb4 15. axb4 c5 $1 {[%csl Rb4] Dismantling White's queenside pawns and another plus point for Black now is that the knight on [a6] will thrive.} 16. dxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Ga6c7] Of course, we have to capture with the pawn so as not to lose the piece by [b5].} 17. f3 (17. b5 {will always met by} Nc5 {, activating the knight.}) 17... Be6 $1 {[%csl Rc4] Targeting the weak [c4]-pawn.} 18. b5 Nc5 19. bxc6 Bxc4 20. Be3 Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c6]} (20... Qc7 {In time to capture the key c6-pawn. After} 21. Qd2 Ng8 22. Rfd1 Qxc6 23. Qxd6 Qxd6 24. Rxd6 Rac8 {, the game has fizzled out to an equal endgame.}) *

