ooting the king so that the rook can come to [g8] in some of the lines and create play.} 13. f3 {[%csl Re5,Rf5,Rh6]} axb4 14. axb4 Bd7 {[%cal Ga6b4,Gf8a8] Connecting the rooks and now the [b4]-pawn is under attack.} 15. Rb1 Qh4 {[%cal Gh4c4]} 16. f4 Rg8 {[%cal Gg8g1]} 17. Bd2 c5 $1 (17... c5 {This is another typical idea to break White's pawn structure and get our corner knight on a6 to the kingside. If} 18. dxc6 bxc6 {⇆ .}) *

