1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. d5 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2] White's idea is to go for [Bd3], [Nge2], [O-O], and then expand on the queenside.} a5 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb8a6] Curbing the expansion on the queenside, especially [b4] stuff from White, which would set the queenside on fire. Next on the cards is the ...[Na6]-[c5] maneuver, securing the knight on [c5].} 6. Bd3 (6. Be3 Na6 {and White has nothing better than} 7. Bd3 {transposing.}) 6... Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]} 7. Bc2 Qe7 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({The direct} 7... f5 {is met by} 8. exf5 gxf5 9. Qh5+ {, so Black plays ...[Qe7] first to interpose it with ...[Qf7].}) 8. Nge2 f5 9. exf5 gxf5 10. O-O Nh6 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gh6][%cal Ge8g8,Gg7a1]} (10... Nf6 {is met by} 11. Ng3 {and we are forced to push the pawn to [f4] in an unfavorable version, weakening a lot of light squares on the go.}) 11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Preparing [b4], which is the key push.} O-O 12. f4 Nc5 ({I like this option more than} 12... e4 {, which is also possible, but the drawback is that it fixes the pawn structure and gives away the [d4]-square. Play might continue with} 13. Rb1 Rf6 14. b4 Rg6 {and so on with a complex game.}) 13. Rb1 Ne4 $1 {A dynamic operation to activate all our pieces, files, diagonals, and whatnot. :} 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Bxe4 Bf5 {[%csl Gf5,Gg7][%cal Ga8e8] All our pieces are happy.} 16. Qd3 Rae8 17. Bd2 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Qh4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gh4c4,Ge8e2]} 19. Be1 Qg4 {[%cal Gg4e2,Ge5f4]} (19... Qg4 {With great compensation. Next, Black is threatening to take on f4. If} 20. h3 {, then} Qf5 21. Qxf5 Nxf5 22. fxe5 Rxe5 {.}) *

