1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 {With the plan of forming a Sämisch setup like [Be3], [f3], [Qd2], and so on.} Nf6 $1 (5... Nc6 6. d5 Nce7 7. Ng3 {and it is not easy for Black to strike with ...[f5] in the desired way – an inferior King's Indian position for Black.}) 6. d5 {This releases the tension and is not that ambitious.} a5 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c5] Aiming to create a nice outpost for the knight on [c5]. Now the white knight on [e2] is misplaced.} 7. f3 (7. Bg5 h6 {and White is not able to retreat to [e3] due to} 8. Be3 Ng4 {and ...[Qh4] followed by ...[f5].}) 7... Nfd7 $1 {8...Na6 is also possible, but White has a strong plan with 9.Bg5 provoking 9...h6 so that Black can never activate the [g7]-bishop via [h6]. Also, after White's [Qd2], the [h6]-pawn will be under attack. Play continues with 10.Be3 and [Nc1] with a pleasant game.} 8. h4 (8. Be3 {is met by a nice trick with} Bh6 9. Bxh6 Qh4+ {and we capture the bishop on [h6]. Once we get rid of our bad bishop on [g7], everything seems comfortable.}) 8... h5 9. Be3 Na6 10. Qd2 Ndc5 {[%cal Gf7f5] Next on the cards is ...[f5] as now the [c8]-bishop is opened up.} 11. O-O-O f5 $10 {With a complex game – there is no clear plan for either side.} *

