1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 {With the plan of forming a Sämisch setup like [Be3], [f3], [Qd2], and so on.} Nf6 $1 (5... Nc6 6. d5 Nce7 7. Ng3 {and it is not easy for Black to strike with ...[f5] in the desired way – an inferior King's Indian position for Black.}) 6. f3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2]} exd4 $1 (6... O-O 7. d5 {here is a different story compared to the 6.d5 a5 variation, as now Black has castled and White has targets with [h4]-[h5].}) 7. Nxd4 O-O {[%cal Gd6d5] Black's next idea is to strike with ...[d5] to break the bind created by the [c4] and [e4]-pawns as soon as possible before White stabilizes.} 8. Be2 d5 {Bam! A strong novelty that leads to concrete play.} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. exd5 Qh4+ {[%cal Gh4e1,Gh4d4]} 11. g3 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Bxd4 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Rd1 Be5 15. Kf2 Nd7 $10 {[%cal Gd7f6] Followed by ...[Nf6] and ...[Bd7] and Black stabilizes.} *

