1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 {With the plan of forming a Sämisch setup like [Be3], [f3], [Qd2], and so on.} Nf6 $1 (5... Nc6 6. d5 Nce7 7. Ng3 {and it is not easy for Black to strike with ...[f5] in the desired way – an inferior King's Indian position for Black.}) 6. f3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2]} exd4 $1 (6... O-O 7. d5 {here is a different story compared to the 6.d5 a5 variation, as now Black has castled and White has targets with [h4]-[h5].}) 7. Nxd4 O-O {[%cal Gd6d5] Black's next idea is to strike with ...[d5] to break the bind created by the [c4] and [e4]-pawns as soon as possible before White stabilizes.} 8. Be3 c6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 9. Qd2 d5 {As always, happy to get ...[d5] in.} 10. e5 Nfd7 {[%csl Re5]} 11. e6 ({White is not able to protect the e5-pawn with} 11. f4 {due to} c5 {and then ...[d4].}) 11... Ne5 12. exf7+ Rxf7 13. cxd5 cxd5 $10 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge5c4] Followed by ...[Nbc6] and the active knights provide Black good play.} *

