1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3]} ({Maintaining the tension. This option is the second-rated move in terms of number of games played. The first one, which is played in high numbers, is} 5. d5 {.}) 5... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Adding more attack towards the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Bg5 {Played in a couple of games, but it is nothing special for White.} Nge7 7. Nd5 {[%cal Gg5d8,Gd5f6]} h6 $1 {The pin is annoying, so we have to get rid of it.} 8. Bf6 Bxf6 9. Nxf6+ Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g7] We are in time to regroup our king to its safety net, the [g7]-square.} 10. dxe5 Kg7 $1 (10... dxe5 {is also possible, which occurs from the 7.dxe5 line. But the text is simply cleaner. So when we have a choice, I would prefer the text move of 10...Kg7 .}) 11. exd6 Kxf6 12. dxe7 Qxe7 {[%csl Re4]} 13. Qc2 Qb4+ 14. Qc3+ Qxc3+ 15. bxc3 Rd8 {[%csl Rc4,Rc3][%cal Gc8e6] Followed by ...[Be6], and the weak doubled c-pawns give Black a sound compensation.} *

