1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3]} ({Maintaining the tension. This option is the second-rated move in terms of number of games played. The first one, which is played in high numbers, is} 5. d5 {.}) 5... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Adding more attack towards the [d4]-pawn.} 6. d5 Nd4 $1 (6... Nce7 {is met by a strong pawn thrust:} 7. c5 dxc5 8. Qb3 {and Black is unable to coordinate their forces properly, or even 7.Be3 followed by [c5] is powerful. Hence, we need to play actively, and 6...Nd4 is a typical move in this scenario.}) 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Nb5 {[%csl Rd4] White tries to corner the [d4]-pawn, but the drawback is that their [e4]-pawn is not well defended.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 9. f3 (9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. Re1 a6 12. Nxd4 Nxd5 {simply equalizes.}) 9... O-O 10. Be2 (10. Nxd4 {fails to a nice shot with} Nxe4 11. fxe4 Qh4+ {and Black is winning.}) 10... c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4]} 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Nxd4 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Rc6] Protecting the [c6]-pawn and next, the ...[d5] breakthrough is incoming.} 13. O-O d5 {[%csl Rc4,Re4,Rg1][%cal Gg7a1] Even though Black is a pawn down, our tremendous activity and the weaknesses created by the [f3] move after Black unleashed the ...[d5] breakthrough give us great compensation.} *

