1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3]} ({Maintaining the tension. This option is the second-rated move in terms of number of games played. The first one, which is played in high numbers, is} 5. d5 {.}) 5... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Adding more attack towards the [d4]-pawn.} 6. d5 Nd4 $1 (6... Nce7 {is met by a strong pawn thrust:} 7. c5 dxc5 8. Qb3 {and Black is unable to coordinate their forces properly, or even 7.Be3 followed by [c5] is powerful. Hence, we need to play actively, and 6...Nd4 is a typical move in this scenario.}) 7. Be3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} 8. Be2 Bxf3 (8... Nxe2 {is possible, but I don't like to give up the active knight. If White takes on [d4], that's another story, as it changes the pawn structure and opens up our bishop on [g7].}) 9. Bxf3 c5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd4,Re5]} 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. O-O {We have transposed.} Rb8 $1 {Our usual reply once the b-file is open. Check the 4.Nf3 variation for more details.} *

