1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3]} ({Maintaining the tension. This option is the second-rated move in terms of number of games played. The first one, which is played in high numbers, is} 5. d5 {.}) 5... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Adding more attack towards the [d4]-pawn.} 6. dxe5 {According to my database, this is the third highest played move, but I would consider it as more critical than the other ones since it does not allow Black to seal with ...[Nd4].} Nxe5 (6... dxe5 {is dubious, as the king is stuck after} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Be3 {and Black is unable to stabilize. For example, if} Be6 {to provide room for the king to [c8], then} 9. Ng5 {is the issue.}) 7. Nxe5 Bxe5 ({Again,} 7... dxe5 {gives White some tempi after} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bg5+ {followed by long castle, and our king has no proper cover. If we had a knight on [b8], then it would be a different story, as we can hide our king with ...[Nd7]. For example} f6 10. O-O-O+ {and} Bd7 {is not effective since it is met by the} 11. Be2 {and [Bg4] trick.}) 8. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] This is a plan if White aims for long castle.} Nf6 {We can bravely develop the knight not concerned about [f4] as there is always ...[Bxc3] and [f4] would only weaken the [e4]-pawn.} 9. Qd2 O-O {[%cal Ge5c3,Gf6e4] Threatening ...[Bxc3] and ...[Nxe4].} 10. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3]} c6 {[%cal Gd8a5] Paving the way for the queen on [d8].} 11. O-O-O Qa5 {[%csl Rc3]} 12. Bd4 b5 {Typical counterplay on the queenside.} 13. Kb1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} (13. cxb5 cxb5 14. Bxb5 Be6 {with a fine game for Black.}) 13... b4 {One of White's ideas was this tactical trick with [Nd5], so we ought to be cautious.} 14. Ne2 c5 15. Bxe5 dxe5 16. Qg5 Rd8 $1 {A nice trick, saving the pawn on [e5].} 17. Rxd8+ Qxd8 18. Nc1 ({If White goes for the pawn grab with} 18. Qxe5 {, Black has two options:} Qd3+ {is the restrained one, when the endgame after} 19. Kc1 Qxc4+ 20. Nc3 Qe6 {is in Black's favor.}) (18. Nc1 {And now an option for the diehards:} Nxe4 $1 19. fxe4 Qd1 {Nc1 Bb7} 20. h4 Qe1 {, when White has to give up material, but it's just temporarily:} 21. Bd3 Qxh1 {Qc7 Ba6 Qa5 Qxh4 (Black has to part ways with the bishop in order to play for more than a draw) Qxa6 Qg5 and the engines prefer Black. It's still a complicated position, but with a clear plan for Black: to start rolling the h-pawn. The queen on [g5] has a double purpose: attack the pawn on [g2] and, even more importantly, protect the [c5]-pawn, which is a crucial aspect in minimizing White's counterplay.}) 18... Qd6 $10 {[%cal Gd6e5,Gd6c5] Black holds the game together.} *

