1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4]} (3. c4 {The Averbakh System contains a tricky move order, as it can lead to the King's Indian Defense if Black plays the natural move} Nf6 {. If one is not a King's Indian player, then this might not be sensible, but of course, we have other choices. Chess is vast. : Having said that, if one picks up this course, learning the King's Indian and adding it to one's own arsenal will be really useful, as many ideas coexist in both these openings.}) 3... d6 {[%csl Gd6,Rc4,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] Just one pawn acting up against the three forces on [e4], [d4] & [c4]. Later, Black will confront the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5].} 4. Nc3 {We are at a critical juncture. White is waiting for us to play ...[Nf6] so that they can comfortably transpose to the King's Indian. But we do have other options.} e5 {[%cal Gg7a1] This makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] is not obstructed by the knight on [f6] and we can use this chance to attack the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3]} ({Maintaining the tension. This option is the second-rated move in terms of number of games played. The first one, which is played in high numbers, is} 5. d5 {.}) 5... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Adding more attack towards the [d4]-pawn.} 6. dxe5 {According to my database, this is the third highest played move, but I would consider it as more critical than the other ones since it does not allow Black to seal with ...[Nd4].} Nxe5 (6... dxe5 {is dubious, as the king is stuck after} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Be3 {and Black is unable to stabilize. For example, if} Be6 {to provide room for the king to [c8], then} 9. Ng5 {is the issue.}) 7. Nxe5 Bxe5 ({Again,} 7... dxe5 {gives White some tempi after} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bg5+ {followed by long castle, and our king has no proper cover. If we had a knight on [b8], then it would be a different story, as we can hide our king with ...[Nd7]. For example} f6 10. O-O-O+ {and} Bd7 {is not effective since it is met by the} 11. Be2 {and [Bg4] trick.}) 8. Be2 Nf6 9. O-O O-O (9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxe4 {is not possible due to} 11. Qd4 Nf6 12. Bg5 {and we lose a piece.}) 10. Bh6 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Rh2,Rh6]} (10... Re8 {is met by} 11. Qd2 {and the threat of [f4] is annoying.}) 11. Bxg4 Qh4 {[%csl Rg4,Rh2,Rh6] The upcoming line is more or less forced until some point.} 12. f4 Bxc3 13. Bxf8 (13. Bxc8 Qxh6 14. Bxb7 Rab8 {equalizes.}) 13... Bxg4 14. Be7 {[%csl Rh4]} Qh5 {[%cal Gh5g4]} 15. Qd5 (15. Qc2 {, protecting the [b2]-pawn, will lose the [e7]-bishop and the game after} Bd4+ 16. Kh1 Re8 {.}) 15... Bxb2 16. Rab1 Qxd5 17. cxd5 Bd4+ 18. Kh1 Re8 {[%csl Re4,Re7]} 19. Bh4 Bb6 {Blocking the [b1]-rook and now the [e4]-pawn drops.} 20. Rfe1 Ba5 $132 {[%csl Re4] Black is now going to capture on [e4]. Our active pieces and a lot of pawns give us great compensation. The computer also agrees to it.} *

