1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd6d5] Black has completed development and now is already aiming for ...[Nxe4] ideas followed by ...[d5], double attacking the bishop on [c4] and the knight on [e4].} (5... Nxe4 {is not possible due to the obvious} 6. Bxf7+ {and our king is exposed there.}) 6. O-O Nxe4 $1 ({Black can play} 6... Bg4 {as well to keep more pieces on the board.} 7. h3 Bxf3 {Qxf3 Nc6 followed by ...[e5], exerting pressure on the [d4]-pawn. Since the queen is away from [d1], White loses some control over the [d4]-pawn.}) 7. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Rc4,Re4] Double attack.} 8. Bd3 dxe4 9. Bxe4 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Preparing the ...[c5] break to free up the position.} 10. c3 c5 11. Re1 cxd4 12. Nxd4 {White can take back with the pawn, but then it becomes isolated. Hence, the text move makes sense.} Nc5 13. Bc2 e5 $10 (13... e5 {Black gets a comfortable game.} 14. Nb3 Ne6 {and I will take Black here any day, thanks to the central pawn on [e5], which creates more space and restricts White's pieces.}) *

