1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd6d5] Black has completed development and now is already aiming for ...[Nxe4] ideas followed by ...[d5], double attacking the bishop on [c4] and the knight on [e4].} (5... Nxe4 {is not possible due to the obvious} 6. Bxf7+ {and our king is exposed there.}) 6. Qe2 {A mix-up of plans. Generally, White plays [Qe2] first without including [Nc3], keeping the option of [c3] flexible.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4e2]} 7. e5 (7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {and White has wasted too many moves with the queen.} Nc6 9. Be3 e5 {and Black again challenge the center in an effective way.}) 7... dxe5 8. dxe5 Nfd7 {[%csl Re5]} 9. e6 Ne5 10. exf7+ Kh8 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rf3] Maintaining the tension around the [f3]-knight. Taking the pawn on [f7] is dubious, as it only limits our own knight due to the pin along the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. In this manner, we aim for a greater goal: to weaken White's king. The [f7]-pawn is ours and will be grabbed at the right time.} 11. Be3 Bxf3 {[%cal Gd8d1] Shattering the pawn structure and exposing the king. One crucial point to note is that White cannot castle queenside.} 12. gxf3 Nbc6 13. Rd1 Qc8 $10 {[%cal Gc8h3]} (13... Qc8 {And the queen is coming all the way to h3 to create trouble. The game continues with} 14. Bd5 Qh3 15. f4 {and now we capture the [f7]-pawn} Nxf7 {with a balanced game. The white king is still in the center.}) *

