1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd6d5] Black has completed development and now is already aiming for ...[Nxe4] ideas followed by ...[d5], double attacking the bishop on [c4] and the knight on [e4].} (5... Nxe4 {is not possible due to the obvious} 6. Bxf7+ {and our king is exposed there.}) 6. Bb3 {This makes sense, as ...[Nxe4] followed by ...[d5] was one of Black's main ideas.} Bg4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1,Gb8c6] A typical idea is to give away the bishop for the [f3]-knight and then pressurize the [d4]-pawn, as White has fewer pieces to strengthen it.} 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 9. Be3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 $10 {[%cal Gc6d4] And ...[Nd4] is arriving next. Black has effortlessly equalized.} *

