1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White's next move is castle, and then [e5] will already be a big threat with the rook coming to [d1].} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2] There is nothing wrong with castling and then playing ...[Nc6], but I prefer this move, as it aligns with the spirit of the position, constantly putting pressure on White's center. Next, ...[Bg4] is coming, and the [d4]-pawn will be under pressure.} 6. c3 {Strengthening the [d4]-pawn so that the ...[Bg4] pins will become ineffective. But on the other hand, the white knight on [b1] cannot land on [c3].} O-O 7. O-O e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 ({It's crucial to take back the e5-pawn with the knight. If} 8... dxe5 {, then the knight on [c6] is quite misplaced there and can be targeted with} 9. b4 {.}) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. a4 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4] Planning to jump on [f4].} 12. g3 Bh3 13. a5 Rfd8 $10 {[%cal Gh5f6,Gc7c6] Black's position is rock solid here.} *

