1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White's next move is castle, and then [e5] will already be a big threat with the rook coming to [d1].} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2] There is nothing wrong with castling and then playing ...[Nc6], but I prefer this move, as it aligns with the spirit of the position, constantly putting pressure on White's center. Next, ...[Bg4] is coming, and the [d4]-pawn will be under pressure.} 6. e5 {Direct but ineffective.} dxe5 7. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Re5] Cornering the [e5]-pawn.} 8. Bf4 Nd4 $1 9. Bxf7+ (9. Qe4 c5 {followed by ...[Bf5] is annoying for White.}) 9... Kf8 $1 (9... Kxf7 {is also possible, but White has 9.Qc4+ .}) 10. Qe4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 Kxf7 12. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Nxf2 13. Qxf2 Rf8 $15 {[%cal Gf7g8] Followed by ...[Kg8] and the king is safe. Black is slightly better here once we consolidate.} *

