1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White's next move is castle, and then [e5] will already be a big threat with the rook coming to [d1].} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2] There is nothing wrong with castling and then playing ...[Nc6], but I prefer this move, as it aligns with the spirit of the position, constantly putting pressure on White's center. Next, ...[Bg4] is coming, and the [d4]-pawn will be under pressure.} 6. e5 {Direct but ineffective.} dxe5 7. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Re5] Cornering the [e5]-pawn.} 8. Bb5 Bd7 {Renewing the threat of ...[Nxe5].} 9. Bf4 a6 10. Bc4 Bf5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc6d4] And next ...[Nd4] is coming. Black's pieces are active around the [e5]-pawn and White always has to take care of it carefully.} 11. Nc3 Nd4 {Yes, time to chip in.} 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Nd5 {[%csl Rc7,Re7][%cal Gd5f4] With this knight move, White not only protects the [f4]-bishop but also attacks the [c7]-pawn and keeps an eye on the [e7]-pawn, not allowing us to castle.} Rd8 (13... O-O-O {is also possible, dropping the [e7]-pawn, but in return, we get a lot of counterplay.}) 14. Rd1 (14. Nxc7+ Kf8 {is losing to White, as they cannot hold all the things in the world, like the [f4]-bishop, the [b2] and [e5]-pawns, and the knight on [c7] is stuck as well.}) 14... Rxd5 $1 {Concreteness! If we drift the queen, then White can push [e6] with a winning attack. So it was time to be concrete.} 15. Rxd4 Rxd4 {[%csl Rf4]} 16. Be3 (16. Bc1 Re4 {is there.}) 16... Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bg4 $10 {[%csl Re2] White is forced to give the queen back, which evens the game.} *

