1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White's next move is castle, and then [e5] will already be a big threat with the rook coming to [d1].} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2] There is nothing wrong with castling and then playing ...[Nc6], but I prefer this move, as it aligns with the spirit of the position, constantly putting pressure on White's center. Next, ...[Bg4] is coming, and the [d4]-pawn will be under pressure.} 6. O-O Bg4 {[%cal Gg4e2,Gc6d4] White's center is under huge pressure now. First the [e4]-pawn and now the [d4]-pawn.} 7. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4] One of the reasons in this direction not to commit [Nc3] is that White can strengthen the [d4]-pawn by the [c3] push.} e5 {[%csl Rd4] Bestowing more pressure on [d4].} 8. d5 {Like in the King's Indian, but White's pieces are misplaced here, which makes a big difference. For example, the bishop on [c4] is obstructing the [c4] advance followed by [Nc3]. White lacks harmony here, and while it takes time for them, Black gets counterplay.} Ne7 9. h3 Bxf3 (9... Bc8 {is also possible, holding the bishop, and then ...[O-O], ...[h6], ...[g5], ...[Ng6] might be one of the plans to create an attack on the kingside.}) 10. Qxf3 O-O {[%cal Gf6d7,Gf7f5] Next on the agenda is ...[Nd7], ...[f5], and Black activates the action mode.} 11. Bd3 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gb1c3] With the idea of [c4] followed by [Nc3].} Nd7 12. c4 f5 13. Nc3 fxe4 14. Qxe4 Nc5 15. Qe2 Nf5 $10 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb7b6,Gf5d4] Black gets the [d4]-square for the knight and can also paste the knight on [c5] by ...[a5] and ...[b6]. Both these knights are not easy to shake, which maintains the balance.} *

