1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Bobby Fischer's favorite place for the bishop. If you notice, in his games, he liked to place the bishop on [c4] in the majority of cases.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 5. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White's next move is castle, and then [e5] will already be a big threat with the rook coming to [d1].} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gg4e2] There is nothing wrong with castling and then playing ...[Nc6], but I prefer this move, as it aligns with the spirit of the position, constantly putting pressure on White's center. Next, ...[Bg4] is coming, and the [d4]-pawn will be under pressure.} 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] This makes a lot of sense as White prevents the annoying pin of ...[Bg4], but on the other hand, White is behind in development now.} O-O {[%cal Ge7e5] Next on the cards is ...[e5].} 7. O-O e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. dxe5 ({White is unable to maintain the tension. For instance, if} 8. c3 {, then} exd4 9. cxd4 Re8 {creates pressure on the [e4]-pawn.}) 8... Nxe5 {I like this more than taking with the pawn due to the fact that after exchanges on [e5], whenever White plays [Nc3], we can restrict it by ...[c6].} 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Rd1 Qe7 $10 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf8d8] Black's position is solid. With ...[Be6] and ...[Rad8] coming next, Black is well on track to complete development and coordinate the pieces harmoniously. The upcoming exchanges will likely simplify the position.} *

