1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. d5 {White releases the tension but does disturb our knight.} Nb8 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ge7e6,Gg7a1] Black has wasted one move with this knight back and forth, but now the [g7]-bishop is open, and we can undermine the [d5]-pawn with ...[c6] or ...[e6].} 8. h3 {[%csl Rg4] This prevents ...[Bg4], so now Black has to shift focus towards challenging the [d5]-pawn.} e6 {[%csl Rd5]} 9. c4 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd3,Re4][%cal Gd7c5] The knight is heading towards [c5].} 10. Nc3 {To my surprise, no games were found in my database. The position is totally new.} Nc5 {[%csl Rd3]} 11. Bc2 Re8 {[%csl Re4]} 12. Re1 {It looks logical to challenge our rook on the e-file.} exd5 13. exd5 Bd7 {Connecting the pieces.} 14. Bg5 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Qf8 $10 {[%cal Ga8e8] Followed by ...[Re8], resulting in some more exchanges when White challenges it with [Re1]. The position is rock solid, though we lack some space. The dangerous [g7]-bishop compensates for the space factor.} *

