1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. d5 {White releases the tension but does disturb our knight.} Nb8 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ge7e6,Gg7a1] Black has wasted one move with this knight back and forth, but now the [g7]-bishop is open, and we can undermine the [d5]-pawn with ...[c6] or ...[e6].} 8. h3 {[%csl Rg4] This prevents ...[Bg4], so now Black has to shift focus towards challenging the [d5]-pawn.} e6 {[%csl Rd5]} 9. c4 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd3,Re4][%cal Gd7c5] The knight is heading towards [c5].} 10. Nc3 {To my surprise, no games were found in my database. The position is totally new.} Nc5 {[%csl Rd3]} 11. Bc2 Re8 {[%csl Re4]} 12. Re1 {It looks logical to challenge our rook on the e-file.} exd5 13. cxd5 a5 $1 {[%csl Gc5] No more [b4] and that means the knight on [c5] is a permanent worry for White.} 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 g5 17. Bg3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb5b4] White cannot take on [b5] because they will lose support over the [e4]-pawn.} 18. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3]} Nh5 {[%csl Rg3] Paving the way for the [g7]-bishop and also activating the knight.} 19. Bf2 b4 20. Nce2 Nf4 $132 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gg7a1] And slowly, Black is taking over with our well-pointed army of pieces.} *

