1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. d5 {White releases the tension but does disturb our knight.} Nb8 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ge7e6,Gg7a1] Black has wasted one move with this knight back and forth, but now the [g7]-bishop is open, and we can undermine the [d5]-pawn with ...[c6] or ...[e6].} 8. c4 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} 9. h3 (9. Nc3 Nbd7 {or 9...Nfd7 , and anyway, at some point, White needs to play [h3] to get rid of the pin.}) 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nfd7 {[%cal Gg7a1]} (10... Nfd7 {I like this more than ...Nbd7, as it paves the way for the g7-bishop. For example, if} 11. Nc3 {, we have extra options like} Bxc3 {, shattering White's pawn structure. Black's main idea is ...[Ne5] now.}) 11. Qe2 Nc5 {[%csl Rd3]} 12. Bc2 Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bxc3 $1 14. bxc3 Re8 $10 {[%cal Ge7e5] Followed by ...[e5] and Black's position is extremely solid and not easy to break. Though White has the bishop pair, Black's intact pawn structure and the dominating knights compensate for it. Moreover, the [c2]-bishop is blocked by its own pawns. The point of ...[Re8] and then ...[e5] is that whenever White captures on [e6], we can take it back with the rook pressurizing the [e4]-pawn.} *

