1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. Re1 e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. Nbd2 ({This is an independent line as} 8. h3 {transposes to the main stuff.}) (8. Nbd2 {White plans to reroute the knight, and if} Nd7 {for example, attacking the [d4]-pawn, White is in time to hold it with} 9. Nb3 {. So, in order to not allow [Nb3], we devise a nice strategy.}) 8... a5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6d7,Gg7a1] Next on the cards is ...[Nd7] and White has to take care of the [d4]-pawn.} 9. h3 Nd7 {[%csl Rd4] Now White is forced to release the tension, which hands over a favorable version of the King's Indian for Black. White's knight would be better placed on [c3] in the King's Indian, whereas here it is on [d2]. White would generally chip in [b4] in a prompt manner to expand on the queenside, which is also not possible here. So overall Black has got a much more favorable version.} 10. d5 Ne7 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 11. a4 f5 12. b4 h6 $132 {[%cal Gf5f4,Gg6g5,Gd7f6] With ...[f4], ...[g5], and ...[Nf6] ideas combined, practically it looks much easier to play with Black as our plans are very clear.} *

