1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Although ...[Bg4] is not such a big deal now and can be met by [Nbd2], in the future, it might be available for Black; hence, White plans to prevent it for a lifetime.} e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. d5 Ne7 9. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3]} Nd7 {Clearing up the f-file for the ...[f5] breakthrough.} 10. Nc3 a5 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gd7c5] First, making room for the [d7]-knight to [c5] without having to worry about [b4] from White. Next, we will go for ...[f5] with the [c8]-bishop open. But the main point is that it prevents White from rolling the pawns towards the queenside with [b4].} 11. a3 f5 ({Nothing wrong with} 11... Nc5 {& ...[f5].}) 12. b3 f4 $132 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg6g5] Followed by ...[h6] and ...[g5], and White has to be cautious on the kingside. Meanwhile, White has not even started to advance on the queenside, as our [a5]-pawn makes it tough for White to carry out [b4] and [c5] in a swift manner.} *

