1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Although ...[Bg4] is not such a big deal now and can be met by [Nbd2], in the future, it might be available for Black; hence, White plans to prevent it for a lifetime.} e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. Re1 {Passing the baton to Black of how we are going to place our army of pieces.} a5 $1 ({If} 8... Re8 {, then White can expand with} 9. d5 Ne7 10. c4 {and [Nc3], and Black has to waste one more move to scoot the rook to [f8] to make the ...[f5] break effective. The rook on [e8] is clearly misplaced. Hence, I prefer the text move, which is useful in not allowing White to expand in the future with [b4]. And somehow, I missed this subtle move in my Chessable 1.e4 course.}) 9. a4 {[%csl Rb4] Logical, to stop Black from further expanding, but the drawback is that the [b4]-square is punctured now.} h6 {A useful waiting move.} 10. Bc2 exd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 {[%csl Rc2] Only thanks to White's pawn on [a4], we can seal our knight on [b4].} 12. Nc3 Nxc2 13. Qxc2 c6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd6d5] Restricting the knight on [c3] and at the right time, Black can challenge the center with ...[d5].} 14. Bf4 Be6 15. Rad1 Rc8 $10 {[%cal Gc8c2]} (15... Rc8 {The position is complex. Some sample lines are} 16. Qc1 Bb3 {and the bishop annoys the rook, or 16.Bg3 d5 17.e5 Bf5 and the knight will jump to [e4].}) *

