1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Although ...[Bg4] is not such a big deal now and can be met by [Nbd2], in the future, it might be available for Black; hence, White plans to prevent it for a lifetime.} e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. Re1 {Passing the baton to Black of how we are going to place our army of pieces.} a5 $1 ({If} 8... Re8 {, then White can expand with} 9. d5 Ne7 10. c4 {and [Nc3], and Black has to waste one more move to scoot the rook to [f8] to make the ...[f5] break effective. The rook on [e8] is clearly misplaced. Hence, I prefer the text move, which is useful in not allowing White to expand in the future with [b4]. And somehow, I missed this subtle move in my Chessable 1.e4 course.}) 9. Bc2 {The main move with the plan of [Nbd2]-[f1] and the bishop will no longer obstruct the contact with the [d4]-pawn from the [d1]-queen.} h6 ({Black has many moves apart from} 9... h6 {like 9...b6 , 9...Bd7 , and so on. It more or less leads to the same kind of position.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f1]} exd4 (10... a4 {is another interesting option if Black does not like to release the tension.} 11. d5 Ne7 12. c4 Nh7 {, paving the way for ...[f5] and it's double edged.}) (10... exd4 {If} 11. Nbd2 {threatening [Bxa4], then we can indirectly support it with} Bd7 {. For example,} 12. Ba4 {Nxd4 is the point. Later, Black will expand with ...[a3] and create more space.}) 11. cxd4 Nb4 {[%csl Rc2] Always happy to obtain the bishop pair.} 12. Nc3 Nxc2 13. Qxc2 Re8 {[%csl Re4]} 14. Bf4 (14. e5 Bf5 15. Qb3 dxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 {is nothing special for White.}) 14... c6 $132 {[%cal Gc8e6] Followed by ...[Be6] and Black is doing fine here. Black's weak central control is compensated by the bishop pair.} *

