1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Although ...[Bg4] is not such a big deal now and can be met by [Nbd2], in the future, it might be available for Black; hence, White plans to prevent it for a lifetime.} e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. Re1 {Passing the baton to Black of how we are going to place our army of pieces.} a5 $1 ({If} 8... Re8 {, then White can expand with} 9. d5 Ne7 10. c4 {and [Nc3], and Black has to waste one more move to scoot the rook to [f8] to make the ...[f5] break effective. The rook on [e8] is clearly misplaced. Hence, I prefer the text move, which is useful in not allowing White to expand in the future with [b4]. And somehow, I missed this subtle move in my Chessable 1.e4 course.}) 9. Bc2 {The main move with the plan of [Nbd2]-[f1] and the bishop will no longer obstruct the contact with the [d4]-pawn from the [d1]-queen.} h6 ({Black has many moves apart from} 9... h6 {like 9...b6 , 9...Bd7 , and so on. It more or less leads to the same kind of position.}) 10. Nbd2 Bd7 {[%cal Ga5a4] Preparing ...[a4].} 11. Nf1 a4 (11... a4 12. Bxa4 Nxd4 {is the point.}) 12. Ng3 b5 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5] Black is unleashing the pawns on the queenside.} 13. Be3 Re8 14. Qd2 {[%csl Rh6] White has achieved their setup but what next?} Kh7 {[%csl Rh6]} 15. Rad1 {[%cal Gd1d8]} Qe7 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Gc7c5] One of Black's plans is to play ...[Na5] and ...[c5].} 16. d5 Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4]} 17. b3 Rec8 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5,Gc8c6,Gc6d6] A subtle maneuver with the idea of ...[c6]/[c5] so that when White captures on [c6], we can take with the rook, protecting the pawn on [d6].} 18. Nh2 axb3 19. axb3 c5 $1 ({In case of} 19... c6 {, maybe} 20. f4 {is stronger.}) 20. f4 c4 $1 {The idea behind 19...c5 instead of 19...c6 .} 21. b4 Nb3 $132 {[%cal Ga8a2] Followed by ...[Ra2] with great activity.} *

