1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rg7] Blunting the [g7]-bishop by forming a strong pawn chain [c3]-[d4]. This was my core repertoire in my Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 1.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({Obviously, here} 4... a6 {does not make any sense, as White has not developed the knight to [c3]. In general, the move ...[a6] looks effective only when the white knight is on [c3] so that we have ideas like ...[b5]-[b4], and of course, to fianchetto the other bishop is also one of the key points. This whole system of 4.c3 is very solid for White as now the center becomes formidable.}) 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] I like placing the knight on [c6] rather than on [d7] due to the simple fact that the [c8]-bishop has a free range.} 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Although ...[Bg4] is not such a big deal now and can be met by [Nbd2], in the future, it might be available for Black; hence, White plans to prevent it for a lifetime.} e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. Re1 {Passing the baton to Black of how we are going to place our army of pieces.} a5 $1 ({If} 8... Re8 {, then White can expand with} 9. d5 Ne7 10. c4 {and [Nc3], and Black has to waste one more move to scoot the rook to [f8] to make the ...[f5] break effective. The rook on [e8] is clearly misplaced. Hence, I prefer the text move, which is useful in not allowing White to expand in the future with [b4]. And somehow, I missed this subtle move in my Chessable 1.e4 course.}) 9. Bc2 {The main move with the plan of [Nbd2]-[f1] and the bishop will no longer obstruct the contact with the [d4]-pawn from the [d1]-queen.} h6 ({Black has many moves apart from} 9... h6 {like 9...b6 , 9...Bd7 , and so on. It more or less leads to the same kind of position.}) 10. Nbd2 Bd7 {[%cal Ga5a4] Preparing ...[a4].} 11. Nf1 a4 (11... a4 12. Bxa4 Nxd4 {is the point.}) 12. Ng3 b5 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5] Black is unleashing the pawns on the queenside.} 13. Be3 Re8 14. Qd2 {[%csl Rh6] White has achieved their setup but what next?} Kh7 {[%csl Rh6]} 15. b3 {[%csl Rc6]} axb3 16. axb3 b4 $1 {Changing the dynamism of the position by challenging the pawn on [c3], which holds a strong center on [d4].} 17. d5 bxc3 {Tempo! Tempi are important in chess; otherwise, half of the ideas would backfire. :} 18. Qxc3 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 Ne7 {So we have to come to a position where the pawn structure has changed drastically. Black has a weak pawn on [c7], and White has a lonely b-pawn. We have to rush to get rid of the [c7]-pawn by ...[c6].} 20. b4 {[%cal Gc2a4]} (20. Qc4 Qb8 {followed by ...[Bb5] brings Black's pieces to the queenside.}) 20... Nexd5 $1 {Changing the dynamics of the game by an unexpected shot. This is another typical sacrifice when our knights are lined up on [f6] and [e7], and moreover, it comes with tempo attacking the queen on [c3].} 21. exd5 Nxd5 22. Qb3 Nxe3 23. fxe3 e4 {[%csl Ra1,Rf3] All our moves are in sync, and only thanks to White's piece placement does the whole idea of ...[Nxd5] sacrifice work.} 24. Nd4 c5 {[%csl Rd4]} 25. bxc5 dxc5 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 26. Ra6 {[%cal Gb3f7,Gf7g6] Now, a concrete line is awaiting for us. Fasten your seat belts!} cxd4 27. Qxf7 {[%csl Rg6]} Qg5 {[%csl Rg3,Gg6]} 28. Qxd7 Qxg3 29. Qxe8 Qxe3+ 30. Kh1 Qc1+ 31. Bd1 Qxd1+ 32. Kh2 {[%csl Rg6]} Qh5 33. Qxe4 Qe5+ 34. Qxe5 Bxe5+ 35. Kg1 d3 $10 {[%csl Gd3,Ge5][%cal Gd3d2] The air has finally cleared up, and we have built a fortress. This endgame is a draw. We also have the d-pawn with us.} *

