1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Against invasions on [g4].} d5 $1 {[%csl Re4] A nice shortcut, which is efficient at the same time. Black uses White's slow play by striking in the center.} 7. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Re3]} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gg7a1] Next on the cards is ...[c5] to challenge the center.} 9. Be2 ({If} 9. c3 {, blocking the [g7]-bishop and preventing ...[c5], then Black has to play} b6 {followed by...[Bb7], ...[Nd7], and then ...[c5].}) 9... c5 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2]} 10. O-O (10. c4 Qd6 11. O-O cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 {, and once again, Black is making use of the monster bishop on [g7].}) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 12. Bf3 {[%cal Gf3a8]} Qa5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. c3 (14. Bxc6 Rb8 {and White cannot save the [b2]-pawn.}) 14... Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d1]} 15. Qc1 (15. Qc2 {will come under the radar of the light-squared bishop on [c8] after} Bf5 {.}) 15... Qc7 {[%cal Gc8e6] Followed by ...[Be6] and Black is doing fine.} *

