1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Against invasions on [g4].} d5 $1 {[%csl Re4] A nice shortcut, which is efficient at the same time. Black uses White's slow play by striking in the center.} 7. e5 Ne4 8. Bd3 {Instead of taking on [e4], White forces Black to take on [c3]. It is not clear which trade is preferable. In any case, Black is doing fine.} Nxc3 9. bxc3 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc5c4] Black also plans for ...[c4] in the latter stage to shut the [d3]-bishop, as the [d4]-pawn is well fortified.} 10. O-O Nc6 11. Re1 c4 {[%csl Rd3]} 12. Bf1 f6 {[%csl Gg7] We need to open up our bishop on [g7], which is restricted by the [e5]-pawn.} 13. exf6 exf6 $10 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8e6] Some of our plans are ...[b5], ...[Be6], ...[Qd7]. Black is doing totally fine here.} *

