1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Against invasions on [g4].} d5 $1 {[%csl Re4] A nice shortcut, which is efficient at the same time. Black uses White's slow play by striking in the center.} 7. e5 Ne4 8. Nxe4 {White captures the annoying knight immediately and tries to corner the [e4]-pawn.} dxe4 9. Ng5 {[%csl Re4]} c5 $1 {Striking in time.} 10. dxc5 Qc7 {[%cal Gc7e5] This is crucial.} 11. c3 (11. Nxe4 Rd8 {– this intermezzo followed by ...[Qxe5] sets up White in trouble as many things are attacked in White's camp along with their king stuck in the center.}) 11... Qxe5 12. Bc4 Nc6 (12... Nd7 13. O-O Nf6 {is also interesting.}) 13. Qd5 h6 {[%csl Rg5]} 14. Nxe4 Qc7 {[%cal Gc6e5] Followed by ...[Ne5], ...[Be6] ideas, or ...[Ne5], ...[Bf5], and ...[Rd8], cornering the queen.} *

