1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Against invasions on [g4].} d5 $1 {[%csl Re4] A nice shortcut, which is efficient at the same time. Black uses White's slow play by striking in the center.} 7. e5 Ne4 8. Nxe4 {White captures the annoying knight immediately and tries to corner the [e4]-pawn.} dxe4 9. Ng5 {[%csl Re4]} c5 $1 {Striking in time.} 10. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4]} Nc6 11. Nxe4 {White gains the pawn, but if you look closely, White is underdeveloped since the knight moved too many times, so Black can use this fact and exploit it by...} cxd4 12. cxd4 Qa5+ 13. Qd2 (13. Nc3 Rd8 {is no good for White either.}) 13... Qxd2+ 14. Nxd2 Rd8 {[%csl Rd4]} 15. Nf3 Be6 $10 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf7f6] Next, ...[f6] is incoming, and the [d4]-pawn is pressurized, which is left without any proper support. The point of placing the bishop on [e6] first is not to allow [Bc4]+.} *

