1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] White's idea is to exchange the Dragon/King's Indian bishop on [g7] by [Bh6], creating huge weaknesses on the dark squares around the king.} c5 $5 {Quite unusual here, as Black generally follows the standard plans with either ...[a6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] followed by ...[Nc6] and so on. However, these common moves tend to be slower in this position, giving White the upper hand in the typical race between a kingside attack vs. queenside counterplay. This calls for some out-of-the-box thinking – and that's when I stumbled upon the interesting concept of ...[c5], similar to the Sicilian approach of challenging the center early. The more I looked into it, the more I loved the idea. And to top it off, it was like a cherry on the cake to discover that this move is rarely played, making it an excellent practical surprise weapon!} 7. O-O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re3] Before White could play [f3].} 9. Bg5 h6 10. h3 (10. Bh4 {is a big blunder due to} Bxd4 11. Qxd4 e5 {and White loses a piece.}) 10... Nxf2 11. Qxf2 hxg5 12. h4 {White is trying to mate us on the h-file, but the [g7]-bishop protects the king from all sorts of flames.} Nc6 13. hxg5 Nxd4 14. Qh4 {[%cal Gh4h7] Threatening mate in one.} Re8 15. Bc4 e6 $10 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7] Blocking the bishop and I don't find any danger here for Black.} *

