1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] White's idea is to exchange the Dragon/King's Indian bishop on [g7] by [Bh6], creating huge weaknesses on the dark squares around the king.} c5 $5 {Quite unusual here, as Black generally follows the standard plans with either ...[a6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] followed by ...[Nc6] and so on. However, these common moves tend to be slower in this position, giving White the upper hand in the typical race between a kingside attack vs. queenside counterplay. This calls for some out-of-the-box thinking – and that's when I stumbled upon the interesting concept of ...[c5], similar to the Sicilian approach of challenging the center early. The more I looked into it, the more I loved the idea. And to top it off, it was like a cherry on the cake to discover that this move is rarely played, making it an excellent practical surprise weapon!} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Bxc5 Nc6 9. Bd3 {Avoiding the exchange of queens.} Bg4 {[%csl Rf3]} 10. Be3 (10. Ng5 h6 11. h3 Bh5 {and White has to retreat anyway to [f3].}) 10... Rc8 11. O-O-O Qa5 {Coordinating all the forces towards White's king.} 12. a3 Rfd8 {[%cal Gd8d1,Gg4d1,Gg7b2,Ga5e1,Gc8c2] All the black pieces are shining.} 13. Kb1 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Ne5 {Black is fine here with so many threats around White's camp.} 15. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2,Gf3]} Rxc3 $1 {Let's go for it! Sacrificing the rook on [c3] is a bold choice, aiming to expose White's king and seize the initiative. Material loss is secondary here – what truly matters is active piece play and king safety. With accurate follow-up moves, Black can launch a devastating attack, putting White on the back foot. Time to embrace the chaos!} 16. Bd2 Rdc8 {Another exchange sac incoming on [c3]! Sometimes, you just have to keep throwing wood into the fire! White's position might look stable, but with precise play, Black keeps up the initiative and forces the opponent to walk a tightrope. Let's keep the energy high and go all in.} 17. Bxc3 Rxc3 $3 {A double exchange sacrifice is already a rare beast, but sadly, no triple exchange sac this time – our rooks have vanished into the abyss! On the bright side, what we've lost in material, we've gained in activity, initiative, and sheer chaos!} 18. bxc3 Qxc3 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gg7a1] The battery of the pieces combined with the queen and White's exposed king gives Black the much-needed initiative.} 19. Qd2 (19. Ka2 Nxe4 20. Rb1 Nc5 {(and White's pieces are simply restricted. Though White is much ahead in material, White is not able to neutralize our active pieces or exchange our main active pieces our queen on [c3].)}) 19... Qxa3 20. Be2 Nxf3 {Grabbing as many pawns as possible.} 21. Qe3 Qb4+ 22. Kc1 Bh6 (22... Bh6 {A nice tactical idea ending in perpetual:} 23. Qxh6 Qa3+ 24. Kb1 Qb4+ {. Yeah, after all the chaos, sacrifices, and fireworks, it just ends in a draw. Sometimes, that's just how chess works – brilliant play, dynamic ideas, and in the end, balance is restored. But hey, at least we had some fun along the way!}) *

