1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] White's idea is to exchange the Dragon/King's Indian bishop on [g7] by [Bh6], creating huge weaknesses on the dark squares around the king.} c5 $5 {Quite unusual here, as Black generally follows the standard plans with either ...[a6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] followed by ...[Nc6] and so on. However, these common moves tend to be slower in this position, giving White the upper hand in the typical race between a kingside attack vs. queenside counterplay. This calls for some out-of-the-box thinking – and that's when I stumbled upon the interesting concept of ...[c5], similar to the Sicilian approach of challenging the center early. The more I looked into it, the more I loved the idea. And to top it off, it was like a cherry on the cake to discover that this move is rarely played, making it an excellent practical surprise weapon!} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc5 {This reminds me of the Sämisch King's Indian: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.f3 O-O 6.Be3 c5 7.dxc5 dxc5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.Bxc5 .} Nc6 {Exactly! This idea mirrors the Sämisch King's Indian structure, where Black willingly gives up a pawn but gains dynamic piece activity in return. Black typically follows up with ...[Nc6], ...[Be6], and ...[Nd7], aiming to pressure White's position and compensate for the material deficit with superior piece coordination. It's one of those positions where engines might initially frown upon Black's play, but from a practical standpoint, it's very playable, especially in dynamic, over-the-board settings. This is a classic example of material vs. activity!} 10. Bd3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gf6d7,Gg7a1] It's evident that we have to play actively as we are a pawn down. Next on the cards is ...[Nd7] followed by ...[Bxc3].} 11. Be3 Nd7 {[%cal Rg7a1]} 12. O-O-O Bxc3 $1 {And now the double c-pawns will give Black good compensation for the pawn loss.} 13. bxc3 Nb6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb6a4] Coming for the [c3]-pawn.} 14. Bb5 Rdc8 {[%csl Gb6,Gc6][%cal Gc8c1] Black is totally fine here with a lot of pressure on the c-file. Our position is rock solid with menacing knights around.} *

