ng it an excellent practical surprise weapon!} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc5 {This reminds me of the Sämisch King's Indian: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.f3 O-O 6.Be3 c5 7.dxc5 dxc5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.Bxc5 .} Nc6 {Exactly! This idea mirrors the Sämisch King's Indian structure, where Black willingly gives up a pawn but gains dynamic piece activity in return. Black typically follows up with ...[Nc6], ...[Be6], and ...[Nd7], aiming to pressure White's position and compensate for the material deficit with superior piece coordination. It's one of those positions where engines might initially frown upon Black's play, but from a practical standpoint, it's very playable, especially in dynamic, over-the-board settings. This is a classic example of material vs. activity!} 10. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rc6]} Nd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 11. Ba3 {[%csl Ga3,Gb2,Re7]} Nb6 {[%csl Gc8] The [c8]-bishop has to be activated to bring more energy in creating play.} 12. Nd1 {Since Black is always threatening ...[Bxc3], White drifts away the knight to a different square.} Be6 13. Ne3 {White has rotated the knight and, at the same time, has also prevented ...[Nc4], so how to induce counterplay now is a big question.} Nd4 $1 14. Nxd4 Rxd4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd4d1]} 15. Bd3 Ra4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a3,Gg7a1] The bishop on [a3] is cornered.} 16. O-O-O (16. O-O {is worse for White after} Rxa3 17. bxa3 Bxa1 18. Rxa1 Rc8 {and White's pawns are lonely and vulnerable along with the pressure on the c-file. Though on paper, White has an extra pawn, their rook tied down to protect the [a2]-pawn, the doubled a-pawns, and the c-file factor give Black a slightly better position.}) 16... Rc8 17. f4 (17. Kb1 {is met by a nice shot:} Rxa3 18. bxa3 Na4 {and Black is on top since ...[Nc3] is unavoidable.}) 17... Bd4 {[%csl Re3]} (17... Bxa2 {is also possible.} 18. Bxe7 Bc4 {with counterplay.}) 18. Rhe1 a6 $1 {[%csl Rb5] White was planning [Bb5] so it is important to prevent it. Next on the agenda is ...[Bxa2].} 19. f5 Rxa3 $1 20. bxa3 Bxa2 {[%cal Gb6a4] Followed by ...[Na4] and Black has great compensation for the exchange loss. White's king is also exposed, so at some point, White needs to give up the exchange, which balances the game.} *

