1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be3 ({Like} 4. Be2 {, this is another tricky move order, keeping the option of [c4] open if Black plays} a6 {. This subtle nuance allows White to get a much better version of the King's Indian, as Black's early ...[a6] can be considered a loss of tempo compared to typical setups involving ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7] and ...[e5]. This flexibility makes it harder for Black to commit to ...[a6], while White retains the ability to choose between classical development or a space-gaining approach with [c4] at the right moment. And this is exactly the direction my good friend Adhiban recommended in his course on 1.e4.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (4... a6 5. c4 {is the issue.}) 5. Nc3 O-O (5... a6 {transposes to the 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 line, which is also possible as an alternative to the mentioned variation.}) (5... O-O {is the preferred continuation to make use of White's move order. It gives us more flexibility and chances to keep the fight going. However, if you'd rather cut down on memorisation, transposing with 5...a6 is certainly a valid choice.}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] White's idea is to exchange the Dragon/King's Indian bishop on [g7] by [Bh6], creating huge weaknesses on the dark squares around the king.} c5 $5 {Quite unusual here, as Black generally follows the standard plans with either ...[a6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] followed by ...[Nc6] and so on. However, these common moves tend to be slower in this position, giving White the upper hand in the typical race between a kingside attack vs. queenside counterplay. This calls for some out-of-the-box thinking – and that's when I stumbled upon the interesting concept of ...[c5], similar to the Sicilian approach of challenging the center early. The more I looked into it, the more I loved the idea. And to top it off, it was like a cherry on the cake to discover that this move is rarely played, making it an excellent practical surprise weapon!} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc5 {This reminds me of the Sämisch King's Indian: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.f3 O-O 6.Be3 c5 7.dxc5 dxc5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.Bxc5 .} Nc6 {Exactly! This idea mirrors the Sämisch King's Indian structure, where Black willingly gives up a pawn but gains dynamic piece activity in return. Black typically follows up with ...[Nc6], ...[Be6], and ...[Nd7], aiming to pressure White's position and compensate for the material deficit with superior piece coordination. It's one of those positions where engines might initially frown upon Black's play, but from a practical standpoint, it's very playable, especially in dynamic, over-the-board settings. This is a classic example of material vs. activity!} 10. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rc6]} Nd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 11. Ba3 {[%csl Ga3,Gb2,Re7]} Nb6 {[%csl Gc8] The [c8]-bishop has to be activated to bring more energy in creating play.} 12. Nd1 {Since Black is always threatening ...[Bxc3], White drifts away the knight to a different square.} Be6 13. Ne3 {White has rotated the knight and, at the same time, has also prevented ...[Nc4], so how to induce counterplay now is a big question.} Nd4 $1 14. Nxd4 Rxd4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd4d1]} 15. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3]} a6 {[%csl Rb5] This bishop is clearly annoying, so it's time to kick it back and then we can place the rook on a4 like in the variation of 15.Bd3 .} 16. c3 (16. Be2 Ra4 {against the bishop on [a3] creates good counterplay.}) 16... axb5 {If we scoot away with the rook, then no ideas like ...[Ra4] exist. Hence, we are forced to sacrifice some material in order not to lose momentum.} 17. cxd4 Bxd4 {[%csl Ra1,Ra2,Ra3,Rb2,Gd4,Re3,Ge6] Black's pieces are extremely active, posing a lot of questions to White's pawns and pieces.} 18. Ke2 Nc4 {Throwing more pieces in.} 19. Nxc4 bxc4 {[%cal Gc4c3]} 20. Kd2 Be5 $1 {[%cal Gc4c3] The immediate ...[c3]+ would have attacked our bishop on [d4] after [bxc3], so we step back one square.} 21. g3 c3+ 22. Kc2 f5 $132 {[%csl Ra3] With good counterplay against the exposed king. The bishop on [a3] is also quite bad there.} *

