ng it an excellent practical surprise weapon!} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc5 {This reminds me of the Sämisch King's Indian: 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.f3 O-O 6.Be3 c5 7.dxc5 dxc5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.Bxc5 .} Nc6 {Exactly! This idea mirrors the Sämisch King's Indian structure, where Black willingly gives up a pawn but gains dynamic piece activity in return. Black typically follows up with ...[Nc6], ...[Be6], and ...[Nd7], aiming to pressure White's position and compensate for the material deficit with superior piece coordination. It's one of those positions where engines might initially frown upon Black's play, but from a practical standpoint, it's very playable, especially in dynamic, over-the-board settings. This is a classic example of material vs. activity!} 10. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rc6]} Nd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 11. Ba3 {[%csl Ga3,Gb2,Re7]} Nb6 {[%csl Gc8] The [c8]-bishop has to be activated to bring more energy in creating play.} 12. Nd1 {Since Black is always threatening ...[Bxc3], White drifts away the knight to a different square.} Be6 13. Ne3 {White has rotated the knight and, at the same time, has also prevented ...[Nc4], so how to induce counterplay now is a big question.} Nd4 $1 14. Nxd4 Rxd4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd4d1]} 15. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3]} a6 {[%csl Rb5] This bishop is clearly annoying, so it's time to kick it back and then we can place the rook on a4 like in the variation of 15.Bd3 .} 16. c3 (16. Be2 Ra4 {against the bishop on [a3] creates good counterplay.}) 16... axb5 {If we scoot away with the rook, then no ideas like ...[Ra4] exist. Hence, we are forced to sacrifice some material in order not to lose momentum.} 17. cxd4 Bxd4 {[%csl Ra1,Ra2,Ra3,Rb2,Gd4,Re3,Ge6] Black's pieces are extremely active, posing a lot of questions to White's pawns and pieces.} 18. Nc2 Bf6 {[%csl Re1,Ge7,Gf6][%cal Gb6c4] Next on the cards is ...[Nc4].} 19. O-O-O (19. O-O Nc4 {creates a lot of play.}) 19... Bxa2 20. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} e5 {Necessary before White blocks our key bishop on [f6].} 21. Rd6 Bd8 {[%csl Gb6,Gd8] Just in time.} 22. Rhd1 Bc7 23. R6d3 Bc4 {[%csl Rd3]} 24. Rc3 exf4 (24... exf4 {And if} 25. b3 {we have} Be5 {, so nothing to worry about. We have active bishops, which always create constant threats to White's rook and king.}) *

