1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nbd2 {This is a bit abrupt. It doesn't look harmonious at all but is played in some games of strong players like Gelfand and Kuzubov.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} 6. d5 O-O 7. O-O e6 8. c4 Re8 9. Re1 exd5 10. cxd5 a6 $132 ({We have a much better version of the Benoni.} 10... Nxe4 {fails to} 11. Bb5 {.}) ({With} 10... a6 {, we curb the threat of [Bb5], and now the [e4]-pawn is threatened, and of course, in the future, we are aiming for the ...[b5] push. Play will continue after} 11. Bf1 Bg4 {followed by ...[Nbd7] and Black is comfortable. One sample line might be} 12. Qc2 Nbd7 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 c4 {– a typical Benoni-like sacrifice with the intention of ...[Nc5] and Black has abundant counterplay.}) *

