1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nbd2 {This is a bit abrupt. It doesn't look harmonious at all but is played in some games of strong players like Gelfand and Kuzubov.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} 6. c3 O-O 7. O-O {What I don't like about White's play is that the [c1]-bishop is blocked by the [d2]-knight.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Nc6 $10 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8b6] Followed by ...[Bd7] and ...[Rc8] and White is still unable to free their position and has no proper coordination. Black also has ideas like ...[Qb6] floating in the air.} *

