1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White prevents ...[Bg4].} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Since White's play is too slow, it is the right time to strike in the center.} 7. O-O cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {This resembles the Dragon, but White has a stupid extra move with [h3], which does not go in hand.} 9. Be3 d5 $1 {This never comes easy in the Dragon, but here, thanks to White's useless moves like [h3], we get the opportunity to ease our position by this breakthrough.} 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Qxd5 13. Bxg7 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Kxg7 $10 {[%cal Gc8e6] Everything has fizzled out with an equal endgame. Next, Black will play ...[Be6] and connect the rooks.} *

