1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. Be3 e5 {[%csl Rd4] If not ...[c5], then ...[e5]. :} 7. dxe5 {This is harmless and leads to some exchanges.} dxe5 8. Qxd8 (8. Nxe5 Nxe4 {is the same story.}) 8... Rxd8 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe5 {[%cal Ge5b2]} 11. c3 Nc6 {The structure is symmetrical with no weakness on either side. The only slight drawback is that the [c3]-pawn restricts our pieces, whereas White's pieces have free range.} 12. O-O Re8 $10 {[%cal Ge5h2] Threatening ...[Bxh2] and White is in no position to create a pleasant endgame.} *

