1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. O-O e5 ({If you don't like entering this equalish endgame, then I suggest} 6... a6 {, aiming for a fight with many options for both sides. This move keeps the tension in the position and avoids early simplifications, allowing Black to maintain flexibility and counterplay.}) ({That said, my personal preference would be} 6... e5 {, immediately challenging the center. This move is objectively the best, as Black strikes in the center without any further delay, ensuring an active position right from the start.}) 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Qxd1 (9... Bxe5 {is inaccurate due to} 10. Bg5 {and White connects all their pieces with the other rook coming to [d1] when Black exchanges queens.}) 10. Rxd1 Bxe5 11. c3 {[%csl Re5] Compared to the line with 6.Be3 e5 7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Nxe5 Nxe4 9.Qxd8 Rxd8 10.Nxe4 Bxe5 11.c3 , there the bishop was on [e3], which allowed us to create concrete threats with ...[Re8], and here it's a different story as the bishop can land on [g5] directly. Having said that, Black has other plans to neutralize.} Nd7 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd7f6] It is important to place the knight to [d7] to challenge the [e4]-knight with ...[Nf6] next.} 12. Bg5 {[%csl Rf6]} Kg7 {[%cal Gd7f6] And ...[Nf6] next is unavoidable. Thanks to this plan, Black frees up the position and maintains the balance.} 13. Be3 Nf6 $1 ({Anish, in his Chessable course 1.e4 – Part 2, while dealing with the Modern, only gives} 13... Re8 {as Black's choice, after which Black is under pressure:} 14. Bb5 {and the line ends as good for White in his course.}) 14. f4 Bxf4 15. Bxf4 Nxe4 16. Bxc7 Re8 {The knight on [e4] holds the position together.} 17. Bf3 (17. Bb5 Re7 18. Bd8 Re5 {and the rook escapes.}) 17... f5 $10 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8e6] Sealing the knight on [e4] and next, we will develop the [c8]-bishop to [e6].} *

