1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. O-O a6 ({Another idea is} 6... Nc6 {followed by ...[e5], but there is a drawback. After} 7. d5 {, Black is forced to play} Ne5 {, which leads to doubled e-pawns following} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 {, and then White has this strong bishop move} 9. Bc4 {, not even allowing us to undermine the [d5]-pawn easily. It is unpleasant.}) ({Hence, I would like to include} 6... a6 {before placing the knight to [c6] so that Black can go back to [a7] as well when attacked. I must say it is a strange square but works concretely, as we can immediately challenge the [d5]-pawn with the ...[c6] thrust.}) 7. Re1 (7. Re1 {is the direction prescribed in The Aggressive 1.e4 by Gustafsson and Nemec. White's rook is useful on [e1], reinforcing central control and preparing the thematic [e5] push.}) 7... Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] The next move is the obvious ...[e5].} 8. d5 Ne5 {Here, it is possible compared to the previous line without the inclusion of ...[a6], as Black is able to challenge the [d5]-pawn without having to worry about [Bc4] stuff.} (8... Na7 {is also possible with the idea of ...[e5]. The knight will always reroute if it needs to, via ...[Bd7] and ...[Nc8]-[e7].}) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Bc4 {If White had another move of [a4], then they would claim that White is better.} b5 {[%csl Ga6] Now we can understand why ...[a6] is useful. White is not able to create a nice setup not allowing Black to undermine the [d5]-pawn.} 11. Bb3 Bb7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc7c6] Yes, the move ...[c6] is a key idea in this setup, challenging White's central control and dissolving the [d5]-pawn. By playing ...[c6], Black undermines White's central structure while seeking dynamic counterplay.} (11... Bb7 {The game continues with} 12. f3 {, reinforcing the [e4]-pawn, followed by} c6 13. dxc6 Bxc6 14. a4 Qc7 15. Be3 e6 16. Qe2 {. In The Aggressive 1.e4 by Gustafsson and Nemec, they concluded that White is slightly better due to structural advantages – namely, the 3 vs. 2 queenside majority and Black's doubled e-pawns. However, let's dive deeper, as surface-level evaluations can be misleading. The game could continue} Rab8 17. axb5 Bxb5 $1 {, which is an important move. ( If instead 17...axb5 , then 18.Na2! is an issue, as the [c6]-bishop becomes passive. ) After} 18. Nxb5 axb5 19. Ra7 {, White is trying to pressure Black's position. ( An alternative is 19.c4 , aiming to create a passed pawn. Here, 19...bxc4 20.Bxc4 Rb7! is a key resource, allowing Black to double rooks on the b-file and put pressure on the weak b-pawn while also clearing the [b8]-square for the queen. Once Black establishes control over the b-file, we can reroute our knight and bishop to shift play toward the kingside or center. ) Following} Rb7 20. Rxb7 Qxb7 21. Ra1 Rb8 22. Ra7 Qc6 {and ...[Bf8], the computer evaluates the position as 0.10, suggesting near equality. While White retains a microscopic edge due to structural considerations, it is not significant enough to pose serious problems for Black. White's 3 vs. 2 queenside majority does not translate into a tangible advantage, as Black's piece activity and coordination compensate fully. I do agree that White has a slight pull in these lines, but it is nothing more than that.}) *

