1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. O-O a6 ({Another idea is} 6... Nc6 {followed by ...[e5], but there is a drawback. After} 7. d5 {, Black is forced to play} Ne5 {, which leads to doubled e-pawns following} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 {, and then White has this strong bishop move} 9. Bc4 {, not even allowing us to undermine the [d5]-pawn easily. It is unpleasant.}) ({Hence, I would like to include} 6... a6 {before placing the knight to [c6] so that Black can go back to [a7] as well when attacked. I must say it is a strange square but works concretely, as we can immediately challenge the [d5]-pawn with the ...[c6] thrust.}) 7. h3 {[%cal Ge4e5] With this move, White intends to push [e5] without having to worry about ...[Ng4].} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] Continuing our plans on the queenside.} 8. e5 {Otherwise, Black will just play ...[Bb7] with a comfortable game.} Nfd7 9. e6 $5 {This happened in my game against the strong IM Laxman from India way back in 2013.} fxe6 10. Ng5 Nf6 $1 ({Necessary. I placed the knight in the other direction with} 10... Nb6 {, which was a mistake due to} 11. Bg4 {.}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge2f3,Ge1e6] Preparing [Bf3].} d5 12. Bf1 Nc6 13. Rxe6 Bxe6 14. Nxe6 Qd6 15. Nxf8 Rxf8 $10 {[%cal Ge7e5] Next on the agenda is ...[e5], and Black is doing well.} *

