1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. O-O a6 ({Another idea is} 6... Nc6 {followed by ...[e5], but there is a drawback. After} 7. d5 {, Black is forced to play} Ne5 {, which leads to doubled e-pawns following} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 {, and then White has this strong bishop move} 9. Bc4 {, not even allowing us to undermine the [d5]-pawn easily. It is unpleasant.}) ({Hence, I would like to include} 6... a6 {before placing the knight to [c6] so that Black can go back to [a7] as well when attacked. I must say it is a strange square but works concretely, as we can immediately challenge the [d5]-pawn with the ...[c6] thrust.}) 7. h3 {[%cal Ge4e5] With this move, White intends to push [e5] without having to worry about ...[Ng4].} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] Continuing our plans on the queenside.} 8. e5 {Otherwise, Black will just play ...[Bb7] with a comfortable game.} Nfd7 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e7]} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Re5] We cannot capture the pawn because of the [Bf3] trick in the end, attacking the rook on [a8] and the bishop on [e5].} 10. e6 $5 {An interesting pawn sacrifice in order to blow the cover of the kingside.} fxe6 11. d5 Nce5 12. dxe6 (12. Ng5 {or 12.Nd4 is met by 12...Nc5 , coordinating the pieces.}) 12... Nf6 {[%csl Re6]} 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Bf3 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Rb8 {[%csl Re6]} 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 e4 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1] The best and only move that helps Black maintain the balance. The key idea is to open up the long diagonal for the bishop, making it difficult for White to develop the [c1]-bishop smoothly.} 18. Rb1 {[%csl Gb1,Gb2] In order to free the [c1]-bishop.} c6 $1 19. Bxc6 (19. Bb3 a5 {and White is not able to maintain the pawn on [e6].}) 19... Bxe6 $10 {[%cal Ge6a2,Gg7b2] The wide open bishops create counterplay.} *

