1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 {White starts with [Nf3] and intends to complete development on the kingside first, delaying [Nc3].} d6 4. Be2 {This is a tricky move order by White, deliberately delaying [Nc3] to see how Black commits their setup. By refraining from an early knight development, White keeps the option of [c4].} (4. Be2 {The key point is that if Black plays the natural-looking} a6 {, White can respond with} 5. c4 {, securing a more favorable version of the King's Indian Defense. The inclusion of ...[a6] is often a slight concession, as it does not contribute directly to central control and can be considered a loss of tempo compared to more standard setups with ...[Nc6], ...[Nbd7], and ...[e5]. This subtle nuance allows White to steer the game toward positions where Black's move order can be slightly suboptimal, granting White greater flexibility and improved control over the center.}) 4... Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} ({So here, as well, I have to refrain from} 4... a6 {because of} 5. c4 {, as I mentioned in the previous comment. Instead, we shift to 4...Nf6 here.}) 5. Nc3 O-O {Steering the waters to the Classical System, which arises after 3.Nc3 d6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be2 .} 6. O-O a6 ({Another idea is} 6... Nc6 {followed by ...[e5], but there is a drawback. After} 7. d5 {, Black is forced to play} Ne5 {, which leads to doubled e-pawns following} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 {, and then White has this strong bishop move} 9. Bc4 {, not even allowing us to undermine the [d5]-pawn easily. It is unpleasant.}) ({Hence, I would like to include} 6... a6 {before placing the knight to [c6] so that Black can go back to [a7] as well when attacked. I must say it is a strange square but works concretely, as we can immediately challenge the [d5]-pawn with the ...[c6] thrust.}) 7. a4 {White prevents ...[b5] while also gaining space, aiming to restrict Black's counterplay on the queenside.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] This position has been tested in numerous games, each showcasing different plans and nuances for both sides.} 8. a5 $1 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] Again, this is key move planning for ...[e5] and then ...[Nd4] when White advances their pawn to [d5]. I see only one GM game here between my two compatriots, Praneeth-Aryan Chopra 2023. This option is missed by Anish in his course as well.} 9. d5 Na7 $1 ({The advantage of including ...a6 in the initial stage.} 9... Nb8 {leaves our pieces disconnected.}) 10. Re1 e6 11. Be3 Bd7 (11... exd5 12. exd5 c6 {is not effective here due to the bishop landing on [b6] by} 13. Bb6 {.}) 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Ng5 Nc6 {The knight is back.} 14. Nxe6 {White gets the bishop pair, but the [e4]-pawn is not fortified, and hence, Black is not worse here.} Rxe6 {[%csl Re4]} 15. Ra4 {[%cal Ga4e4]} (15. Bc4 Re5 {exists, which leaves both the [e4] and [a5]-pawns vulnerable. 15.Bf3 is possible, but the bishop becomes passive there, and we can react with 15...h5 .}) 15... Qe8 {[%csl Re4] We have to hurry up in creating threats. Otherwise, we are strategically worse.} 16. Bc4 Re5 {[%csl Ra5] Going for the [a5]-pawn.} 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 Nb8 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Ge8][%cal Gb8d7] The knight will establish itself on [d7] nicely.} 19. Rb4 Bh6 $132 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge8e1] Thanks to the supreme control over the e-file, Black exerts pressure on the [e3]-bishop.} *

