1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nge2 ({This is a better move order to reach the fianchetto setup, as} 4. g3 {gives a lot of options for Black.}) 4... Nf6 {Black aims for castle and a quick ...[e5].} 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 e5 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... exd4 {followed by ...[Nc6] is equally possible but might give an extra option for White after} 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {. The pawn structure is changed here.}) 8. dxe5 {This is harmless, and in fact, White has to be careful not to end up in an unpleasant situation.} dxe5 9. Qxd8 (9. Bg5 {is met by} Nd4 {.}) 9... Rxd8 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] With Black's knight jumping to [d4] and [b4], White has to be careful.} 10. Bg5 Nb4 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb4c2]} 11. Rc1 h6 12. Be3 b6 $10 {[%cal Gc8b7] Followed by ...[Bb7], Black has a pleasant game with pressure on the [e4]-pawn. One more main idea of ...[b6] is to push ...[c5], followed by ...[Nc6]-[d4] just dominating the game.} *

