1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nge2 ({This is a better move order to reach the fianchetto setup, as} 4. g3 {gives a lot of options for Black.}) 4... Nf6 {Black aims for castle and a quick ...[e5].} 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 e5 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... exd4 {followed by ...[Nc6] is equally possible but might give an extra option for White after} 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {. The pawn structure is changed here.}) 8. O-O {This gives Black momentum.} exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 {[%cal Gg7d4] White is forced to capture with the queen, which now comes under the radar of the bishop on [g7]. So, White has to waste one more move with the queen, which is not ideal.} Re8 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gg7a1] Threatening ...[Nxe4].} 11. Qd3 {The usual square for the queen, overprotecting the pawn on [e4].} Nd7 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd7c5,Gg7a1] The queen will be disturbed again by ...[Ne5]/[c5]. The diagonal is also opened up now, and the Dragon bishop puts immense pressure on White's queenside.} 12. Re1 a5 $10 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3,Gd7e5,Gc8e6] Black is the one who is having the momentum with ideas like ...[Ne5], ...[Be6], ...[a4]-[a3], etc.} *

