1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nge2 ({This is a better move order to reach the fianchetto setup, as} 4. g3 {gives a lot of options for Black.}) 4... Nf6 {Black aims for castle and a quick ...[e5].} 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 e5 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... exd4 {followed by ...[Nc6] is equally possible but might give an extra option for White after} 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {. The pawn structure is changed here.}) 8. Be3 {Thanks to the pawn on [h3], White doesn't need to worry about ...[Ng4].} exd4 {Now it's time to take on [d4].} 9. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gd7] Holding on to the knight on [c6].} 10. O-O Re8 {[%csl Re4] And now the [e4]-pawn is pressurized. Here, there are a couple of options for White.} 11. Qd3 {We have transposed.} Ne5 {See the 4.g3 move order for more details.} *

