1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nge2 ({This is a better move order to reach the fianchetto setup, as} 4. g3 {gives a lot of options for Black.}) 4... Nf6 {Black aims for castle and a quick ...[e5].} 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 e5 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... exd4 {followed by ...[Nc6] is equally possible but might give an extra option for White after} 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {. The pawn structure is changed here.}) 8. Be3 {Thanks to the pawn on [h3], White doesn't need to worry about ...[Ng4].} exd4 {Now it's time to take on [d4].} 9. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gd7] Holding on to the knight on [c6].} 10. O-O Re8 {[%csl Re4] And now the [e4]-pawn is pressurized. Here, there are a couple of options for White.} 11. a4 {This move has no idea, just an expansion to gain space.} Nxd4 $1 {One of the main concrete ideas Black has.} 12. Bxd4 c5 13. Be3 Bc6 {[%csl Re4] The [e4]-pawn is vulnerable since the bishop on [e3] blocks the rook from protecting it.} 14. Qd3 Re6 {[%cal Ge6d6,Gd8e8] Another typical idea here, which we will see in the 11.Re1 line as well. Black protects the pawn on [d6] to release the queen on [d8], and we can now double on the e-file with ...[Qe8], attacking the [e4]-pawn.} 15. Nd5 (15. Rad1 Qe8 {is the main point behind ...[Re6]. White's pawns on [a4] and [e4] are attacked.} 16. b3 Nxe4 {, time to liquidate:} 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Qxd6 b6 {.}) 15... Bxd5 16. exd5 Re8 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5] Followed by ...[Nd7] and Black is totally fine. Though White has the bishop pair, the light-squared bishop is dull and restricted.} *

