1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2]} ({White also fianchettos their bishop to g2 like Black. This is the slower approach in facing the Modern, unlike all the sharp systems with} 4. Be3 {and [Qd2], [O-O-O], or 4.f4 , and so on. White claims that they have a strong center and space advantage, and they can also play positionally, placing their pieces in perfect squares in contact with the center and then outclassing the opponent.}) 4... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Asking questions to the [d4]-pawn.} 5. d5 Ne5 {[%cal Gc7c6] Next, we will undermine the [d5]-pawn with ...[c6].} 6. Bg2 c6 {[%csl Rd5]} 7. h3 {White cannot disturb the [e5]-knight by [f4] without covering up the [g4]-square.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 8. dxc6 Rb8 {[%csl Gb5,Gb8,Rc6]} 9. Nf3 Nxc6 10. O-O b4 11. Nd5 Nf6 $10 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge8g8] Challenging the knight on [d5] and, of course, Black will castle next.} *

