1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2]} ({White also fianchettos their bishop to g2 like Black. This is the slower approach in facing the Modern, unlike all the sharp systems with} 4. Be3 {and [Qd2], [O-O-O], or 4.f4 , and so on. White claims that they have a strong center and space advantage, and they can also play positionally, placing their pieces in perfect squares in contact with the center and then outclassing the opponent.}) 4... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Asking questions to the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 e5 {The combination of ...[Nc6] and ...[e5] is effective in exerting pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Nxd8 {This endgame is nothing special for White, as Black has not created any weaknesses in our camp.} 8. Nd5 Ne6 {[%csl Gc7,Ge6]} 9. Bh3 Kd8 $10 {[%cal Gc7c6] Followed by ...[c6], ...[Kc7], and Black stabilizes.} *

