1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2]} ({White also fianchettos their bishop to g2 like Black. This is the slower approach in facing the Modern, unlike all the sharp systems with} 4. Be3 {and [Qd2], [O-O-O], or 4.f4 , and so on. White claims that they have a strong center and space advantage, and they can also play positionally, placing their pieces in perfect squares in contact with the center and then outclassing the opponent.}) 4... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Asking questions to the [d4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 e5 {The combination of ...[Nc6] and ...[e5] is effective in exerting pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Be3 Nf6 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf6g4]} 7. h3 exd4 {Opening up the game, as White has still not completed development, and the white king in the center gives Black a lucrative option to do so.} ({The order of the moves is not so important. We can also start with} 7... O-O {and then capture on [d4].}) 8. Nxd4 O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e1]} 9. Bg2 (9. Nxc6 {is one moment where White can capture on [c6] before ...[Bd7] arrives to double the c-pawns, but the problem is} bxc6 10. Bg2 Rb8 11. b3 Ba6 {⇆ and White cannot castle kingside.}) 9... Bd7 {[%csl Gd7,Gc6]} 10. O-O Re8 {[%csl Re4]} 11. Qd3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4]} (11. Qd2 Nxd4 $1 12. Bxd4 c5 {, a very nice idea to push the bishop back to [e3] so that White cannot strengthen the [e4]-pawn by [Re1] when attacked.} 13. Be3 Bc6 {and} 14. f3 {will be met by} d5 {with a slightly better position as White's pieces are passive.}) 11... Ne5 12. Qe2 c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] The knight on [d4] is annoying, so Black kicks it away. Thanks to the ...[Be6] follow-up, the weakened control over [d5] is not a problem.} 13. Nb3 Be6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge6c4,Gc4f1] The pieces are heading towards the [c4]-square.} 14. Rfd1 Qb6 {[%cal Ge5c4] And now ...[Nc4] cannot be prevented.} *

