1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. Nf3 {A normal development. This position can also be reached via 4.Nf3 a6 5.Bg5 .} b5 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4] This would be a nice setup if the white bishop was on [e3], as now we can pin the [g4]-knight, attacking the [d4]-pawn at the same time.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1,Gg7d4]} 7. O-O Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... Bxd4 {is not possible due to} 8. Bxb5+ {, so we add some more energy to targeting the [d4]-pawn.}) 8. d5 Ne5 {[%csl Rf3]} 9. Be2 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nf6 $10 {[%cal Ge5f3,Gb5b4]} (10... Nf6 {Black is comfortable here with ...Nxf3, ...b4, and all sorts of ideas. White cannot preserve the f3-bishop by} 11. Be2 {due to} b4 {and either the [e4]-pawn will fall, or White will have to give up the bishop pair with [Bxf6].}) *

