1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. Nf3 {A normal development. This position can also be reached via 4.Nf3 a6 5.Bg5 .} b5 6. a4 {Whenever we play ...[b5], we have to watch out for this breakthrough.} b4 7. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2g3] With the intention to reroute to [g3] is one of the options.} h6 8. Be3 Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} 9. Ng3 h5 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gh5h4] Another typical idea to make note of is pushing Harry when White's knight arrives on [g3]; Black's idea is obvious: to push ...[h4] and capture the [e4]-pawn.} 10. Bd3 (10. Bg5 {is met by} Nh7 {.}) 10... c5 {Keeping the option of ...[h4] for later – we counter with ...[c5].} 11. dxc5 Ng4 $132 {[%csl Rb2,Re3] Black is not able to hold both the [e3]-bishop and the [b2]-pawn.} *

