1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. Nf3 {A normal development. This position can also be reached via 4.Nf3 a6 5.Bg5 .} b5 6. a4 {Whenever we play ...[b5], we have to watch out for this breakthrough.} b4 7. Nd5 {[%csl Rb4]} h6 {To include this is in Black's favor, as we can later free up with ...[e5] or ...[e6].} 8. Bh4 {White maintains the pressure along the diagonal.} Bb7 {[%cal Gb7e4]} 9. Bc4 {Holding on to the [d5]-knight; otherwise, Black will take on [d5] and corner the [d5]-pawn with ...[Ngf6].} g5 10. Bg3 e6 11. Nxb4 a5 ({A key move, as the immediate} 11... Bxe4 {is met by} 12. Qe2 {and our [a6]-pawn is hanging.}) 12. Na2 Bxe4 {We have dissolved White's powerful center now.} 13. Nc3 Bg6 $10 (13... Bg6 {Black is fine here. We can develop the g8-knight to e7 and} 14. d5 {will always be met by} e5 {, closing the position.}) *

