1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Planning to castle long and whenever our knight moves away from [g8], they can insert [Bh6].} b5 {Continuing the flow of creating play on the queenside.} 6. a4 b4 7. Nd1 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. d5 ({The alternatives} 8. Ne2 d5 {, 8.c3 Nf6 , and 8.Nf3 Bg4 give Black good play.}) 8... Ne5 9. Qxb4 Nf6 {Black's pieces are springing into action, whereas White's pieces are still underdeveloped.} 10. Nc3 c5 11. dxc6 Nxc6 $132 {[%cal Ga8b8] Followed by ...[Rb8] and White is under pressure on the b-file.} *

