[GameId "2159115897316274"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Planning to castle long and whenever our knight moves away from [g8], they can insert [Bh6].} b5 {Continuing the flow of creating play on the queenside.} 6. O-O-O Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} 7. f4 {The bishop on [g5] and the pawn on [f4] is a nice combination compared to the bishop on [e3] and pawn on [f4]. And this is one more point of placing the bishop to [g5]. Black cannot develop freely, as ...[e5] is never possible, and our queenside pieces are stuck. Once White develops properly, they will strike with [e5].} Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gg7c3]} 8. Nf3 (8. e5 {will be met by} f6 9. Bh4 Nh6 {with good counterplay.}) 8... b4 {[%csl Re4]} (8... c5 {is also interesting, which leads to complex play after} 9. e5 {. I like the text move, as it is simpler.}) 9. Nd5 {White cannot move to any other square, as the [e4]-pawn was hanging.} Bxd5 10. exd5 {The central pawn mass has vanished, and now White's pawn structure is awful with doubled d-pawns. The advantage of this operation for White is the bishop pair and our weak pawn on [b4].} Ngf6 {[%csl Rd5]} 11. Bc4 Nb6 {[%csl Rd5]} 12. Bxf6 {White is forced to give away the bishop pair in order not to lose the [d5]-pawn.} Bxf6 13. Qxb4 Qd7 {[%cal Gd7f5,Gf5g4,Ge8g8,Ga6a5] Black has many ideas here like ...[Qg4], ...[Qf5], castling followed by ...[a5], and so on. The extra pawn is of no use to White.} *

