1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Planning to castle long and whenever our knight moves away from [g8], they can insert [Bh6].} b5 {Continuing the flow of creating play on the queenside.} 6. O-O-O Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} 7. f3 {[%csl Ge4] Since ...[b4] is always possible, White strengthens the [e4]-pawn.} Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 8. Kb1 (8. h4 h5 {, renewing the threat of ...[c5], is also nothing special for White.}) 8... c5 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. Nge2 h5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6]} ({An unusual move. The point is that if the direct} 10... Nf6 {, then} 11. Bh6 {was bothering Black. Moreover, it barricades White's attack with [g4].}) 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 Na4 13. b3 Nb6 14. Be3 Nf6 $10 (14... Nf6 15. Bd4 h4 {and Black is totally fine here.}) *

