1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. a4 {Stopping ...[b5], but on the other hand, White cannot castle long now. A strong Chinese player, Dai, played this against me in the Binhai Chess Cup 2019, and I did not react well here. I developed the knight to [d7] followed by ...[c5] but got stuck without ...[b5] and was lucky to escape in a lost position.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] The knight is much more active on [c6] than on [d7] and, of course, it keeps an eye on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. d5 Ne5 (6... Nb4 {is also possible, but somehow I don't feel safe with the lonely knight here after White's} 7. a5 {.}) 7. f4 Nd7 {One might wonder why we wasted so many moves with the knight, but on the other hand, we have provoked White to push their pawns. We can undermine now with ...[c6] and the [g7]-bishop is open to add to it.} 8. Nf3 c6 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gg7b2] Black is planning ...[Qb6], after which White will be under huge pressure.} 9. a5 cxd5 10. exd5 b5 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black has a much better position. We will develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7] with ...[b4] on the cards.} *

