1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. a4 {Stopping ...[b5], but on the other hand, White cannot castle long now. A strong Chinese player, Dai, played this against me in the Binhai Chess Cup 2019, and I did not react well here. I developed the knight to [d7] followed by ...[c5] but got stuck without ...[b5] and was lucky to escape in a lost position.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] The knight is much more active on [c6] than on [d7] and, of course, it keeps an eye on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. d5 Ne5 (6... Nb4 {is also possible, but somehow I don't feel safe with the lonely knight here after White's} 7. a5 {.}) 7. Be2 ({The direct} 7. Nf3 {is met by the} Bg4 {pin and hence White first places the bishop to [e2], preparing for [Nf3].}) 7... Nf6 8. Nf3 (8. f4 {is met by} Ned7 {and ...[c6].}) 8... Nxf3+ 9. Bxf3 h6 (9... O-O 10. Qd2 {and we will not be able to play ...[h6]. The bishop will become annoying on [g5], so let's kick that back.}) 10. Be3 O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge7e6]} 11. O-O Re8 $10 {[%cal Ge7e6]} ({Preparing ...e6 so that when White takes on e6, we can take back with the rook.} 11... e6 {is not good due to} 12. dxe6 {followed by [e5] and we will be in trouble.}) *

