1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. a4 {Stopping ...[b5], but on the other hand, White cannot castle long now. A strong Chinese player, Dai, played this against me in the Binhai Chess Cup 2019, and I did not react well here. I developed the knight to [d7] followed by ...[c5] but got stuck without ...[b5] and was lucky to escape in a lost position.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] The knight is much more active on [c6] than on [d7] and, of course, it keeps an eye on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Nge2 ({If White does not want to release the tension with} 6. d5 {, then they have to hold the pawn with this knight move.}) (6. Nf3 {is another way, but not good due to} Bg4 {. Here, we cannot pin the [e2]-knight because of [f3]. Vjeko missed this option in his analysis for his Chessable course on the Modern. Looks to be the most critical.}) 6... h6 {Disturbing the bishop, as it is not allowing us to breakthrough with ...[e5].} 7. Bh4 {[%cal Gh4d8] Keeping the bishop on the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, but now White doesn't have [Qd2] and [Bh6] ideas. Also, it is not easy to develop the [f1]-bishop. Their setup lacks harmony.} Nf6 8. f3 O-O {[%csl Re2,Rf1] White is unable to complete development on the kingside, and castling on the queenside runs into ...[b5].} 9. Qd2 (9. a5 b5 10. axb6 cxb6 {is nothing special for White.}) 9... Na5 $1 {[%cal Ga5c4] A nice maneuver, which not only threatens ...[Nc4] but also ...[c5] ideas are floating in the air.} 10. b3 b6 $132 {[%cal Gc7c5] And ...[c5] is coming next with a preferable position.} *

