1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. a4 {Stopping ...[b5], but on the other hand, White cannot castle long now. A strong Chinese player, Dai, played this against me in the Binhai Chess Cup 2019, and I did not react well here. I developed the knight to [d7] followed by ...[c5] but got stuck without ...[b5] and was lucky to escape in a lost position.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] The knight is much more active on [c6] than on [d7] and, of course, it keeps an eye on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Nge2 ({If White does not want to release the tension with} 6. d5 {, then they have to hold the pawn with this knight move.}) (6. Nf3 {is another way, but not good due to} Bg4 {. Here, we cannot pin the [e2]-knight because of [f3]. Vjeko missed this option in his analysis for his Chessable course on the Modern. Looks to be the most critical.}) 6... h6 {Disturbing the bishop, as it is not allowing us to breakthrough with ...[e5].} 7. Be3 e5 {Challenging the center.} 8. d5 Nce7 {[%cal Gf7f5] A typical King's Indian kind of position. Black is preparing ...[f5] here.} 9. Ng3 (9. f3 f5 {and ...[Nf6] and the moves flow easily.}) 9... f5 (9... h5 {is another plan intending ...[h4]. Play could continue} 10. h4 Nf6 {followed by ...[Bd7], ...[c6], and it's double edged.}) 10. exf5 Nxf5 (10... gxf5 11. Nh5 {is the problem, and hence, we are forced to capture with the knight.}) 11. Nxf5 gxf5 $1 (11... Bxf5 {is bad due to} 12. g4 {and [Bd3] stuff, so we have to be cautious every time in deciding with which piece/pawn to capture back on [f5].}) 12. Qh5+ Kf8 $10 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gc8d7] Black is fine with ...[Nf6] and ...[Bd7] next. The king is safe on [f8] and well guarded by the pawns on the fifth rank.} *

