1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] This is not that popular here compared to the Pirc Defense, which occurs after 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5 . In fact, that is my recommendation against Pirc in my 1.e4 Chessable series. The point is that when Black's knight is on [f6], White puts pressure on it by placing the bishop on [g5]. Here, it is not the case, and it feels empty. However, we should not disregard the fact that it slows down ...[e5] or ...[e6] due to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal, and it can be a bit annoying if we don't react properly.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Carrying out the main agenda of a flank attack.} 5. a4 {Stopping ...[b5], but on the other hand, White cannot castle long now. A strong Chinese player, Dai, played this against me in the Binhai Chess Cup 2019, and I did not react well here. I developed the knight to [d7] followed by ...[c5] but got stuck without ...[b5] and was lucky to escape in a lost position.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] The knight is much more active on [c6] than on [d7] and, of course, it keeps an eye on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Nge2 ({If White does not want to release the tension with} 6. d5 {, then they have to hold the pawn with this knight move.}) (6. Nf3 {is another way, but not good due to} Bg4 {. Here, we cannot pin the [e2]-knight because of [f3]. Vjeko missed this option in his analysis for his Chessable course on the Modern. Looks to be the most critical.}) 6... h6 {Disturbing the bishop, as it is not allowing us to breakthrough with ...[e5].} 7. Be3 e5 {Challenging the center.} 8. Qd2 {White is maintaining the tension in the center. Next, they will play [f3] or long castle despite weakening their queenside with [a4].} exd4 (8... Nf6 9. d5 Ne7 {and there is no...[f5] for us, which is the key break, and we are doomed.}) 9. Nxd4 Nf6 10. Be2 Nxd4 {Deflecting the bishop so that we can castle without being concerned about the [h6]-pawn.} 11. Bxd4 O-O 12. O-O Re8 {[%csl Re4]} 13. f3 Be6 {[%cal Gd6d5] So far, all the moves are natural from both sides and now we are aiming to free with ...[d5] next.} 14. Rad1 d5 15. e5 Nd7 16. f4 f6 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Bf3 c6 $10 {[%csl Ga8,Ge8][%cal Gd8e7,Gd8d7] Black's position is solid. We will bring the other rook on [a8] into play with ...[Qe7]/[d7], and it's all good.} *

