1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be2 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White delays the [g1]-knight development for ideas like [h4]-[h5] or [Be3] and [Qd2] without having to worry about ...[Ng4] jumps.} Nf6 (4... a6 {is also possible, but I would like to not stick with one plan of ...[b5]; hence, I prefer development first so that we can adapt according to what the position needs, like ...[e5] or ...[c5] breaks, and so on.}) 5. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] A flank attack.} c5 {Met by counterplay in the center. :} 6. dxc5 Qa5 {[%csl Rc5,Rc3,Re4][%cal Ga5e1,Gf6e4,Gg7c3] Obviously, we cannot capture back on [c5], which will expose our king after the exchange of queens, so this intermezzo is important.} 7. Bd2 (7. cxd6 {would hand the initiative to Black after} Nxe4 8. Bd2 (8. dxe7 Nc6 {– stronger than grabbing the pawn immediately with Kxe7 , as a quick development, has priority when playing material down.}) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 exd6 10. Nf3 O-O {, and just like in the previous variation, we get our priorities straight; finishing development with ...[Nc6], ...[Bg4], etc., is more important than giving up our strong asset on [g7] for the [c3]-pawn.}) 7... Qxc5 8. h5 {White has created an opportunity on the h-file, but it is not enough for a powerful attack.} O-O {Ignoring is the best policy here.} 9. h6 (9. hxg6 {will always be faced by} fxg6 {and not 9...hxg6 because that will open up the h-file.}) 9... Bh8 {Yes, the bishop has retreated, but it still has a wide range along the [h8]-[a1] diagonal.} 10. Nf3 Bg4 $10 {[%cal Gb8d7] Followed by ...[Nb7] and Black has accomplished development with a comfortable position.} *

