1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be2 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White delays the [g1]-knight development for ideas like [h4]-[h5] or [Be3] and [Qd2] without having to worry about ...[Ng4] jumps.} Nf6 (4... a6 {is also possible, but I would like to not stick with one plan of ...[b5]; hence, I prefer development first so that we can adapt according to what the position needs, like ...[e5] or ...[c5] breaks, and so on.}) 5. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Gf2f4,Gh2h4] Keeping all the plans open, like [f4], [h4], [Qd2] followed by long castle, and so on.} O-O 6. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 {[%csl Rg4]} ({We stop the h-pawn here instead of} 6... c5 {, which is also interesting.} 7. dxc5 Qa5 8. Kf1 {and so on. The text seems simpler.}) 7. f3 {[%csl Rg4]} (7. Qd2 {is met by} c5 {like in the variation of 6.Qd2 c5 7.Nf3 Ng4 .}) 7... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge7e5]} (7... Nc6 {Preparing ...e5 next and not worried about} 8. d5 {, as it will only activate our knight, which will have a nice post on [e5].}) 8. Qd2 e5 9. d5 Nd4 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6] And next ...[c6] is on the cards. White has no proper breakthrough on the kingside.} *

