1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be2 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White delays the [g1]-knight development for ideas like [h4]-[h5] or [Be3] and [Qd2] without having to worry about ...[Ng4] jumps.} Nf6 (4... a6 {is also possible, but I would like to not stick with one plan of ...[b5]; hence, I prefer development first so that we can adapt according to what the position needs, like ...[e5] or ...[c5] breaks, and so on.}) 5. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Gf2f4,Gh2h4] Keeping all the plans open, like [f4], [h4], [Qd2] followed by long castle, and so on.} O-O 6. f4 {Rarely played in the top-level games, but it is an interesting option to conquer the center.} c5 $1 {Again, before White stabilizes, we have to create counterplay.} 7. dxc5 (7. e5 {is a big structural concession and a mistake as well. After} Nfd7 8. exd6 exd6 9. Nf3 Nc6 {, Black has too much pressure on the center since ...[Qb6] could be played next, while} 10. d5 Ne7 {would only increase our advantage.}) 7... Nc6 8. Bf3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3][%cal Gg1e2]} (8. Nf3 {is met by} Ng4 {and Black regains the pawn on [c5].}) 8... e5 $1 9. cxd6 exf4 10. Bxf4 Qb6 {[%cal Gb6g1,Gb6b2] Exploiting the weak dark squares.} 11. Nge2 Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gb6f2] White cannot castle, and Black is going to invade with the queen on [f2].} 12. Nd5 Qf2+ 13. Kd2 Nge5 {[%csl Rd2,Rf3]} 14. Kc1 (14. Bxe5 $2 Nxe5 {is almost game over for White on the dark squares, as defending against ...[Bh6]+, ...[Nc4]+, ...[Nxf3]+ simultaneously is a difficult task.}) 14... Qc5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc5d6] With good compensation thanks to White's king on [c1].} *

