1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. g4 ({This is not that efficient here compared to the case of} 4. Be3 a6 5. g4 {, as Black can create immediate counterplay around the [d4]-pawn.}) 4... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Had the white bishop been on [e3] already, it would be a different story, but now White is not in time to consolidate the center.} 5. Be3 e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 6. dxe5 Bxe5 $1 {[%cal Ge5b2] A clever approach, as now White cannot fortify the [c3]-knight by [Qd2] due to the hanging pawn on [g4].} 7. f3 Bxc3+ $1 {Shattering White's pawn structure and making White's life difficult in castling on either side.} 8. bxc3 Qh4+ 9. Bf2 Qf6 {[%csl Rc3]} 10. Qd2 Nge7 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ge8c8,Gd6d5] Black has a clear plan of ...[Be6], ...[O-O-O], and ...[d5].} *

