1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. g4 ({This is not that efficient here compared to the case of} 4. Be3 a6 5. g4 {, as Black can create immediate counterplay around the [d4]-pawn.}) 4... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Had the white bishop been on [e3] already, it would be a different story, but now White is not in time to consolidate the center.} 5. d5 Nd4 {Yes, this is the point, and it is not easy for White to develop the [g1]-knight.} 6. h3 (6. Be3 c5 {is no good for White, as they need to support the [h3]-pawn anyway to bring the [g1]-knight into play.}) 6... e5 $1 7. Nb1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc2c3] Threatening [c3] next to trap the [d4]-knight.} c6 {[%csl Gb5,Gc6][%cal Gd4b5]} 8. Na3 {White plays just to corner the [d4]-knight without developing other pieces, which is not that efficient.} Nf6 $1 {[%csl Re4] Sacrificing the [d4]-knight but, in turn, creating a lot of play around White's king since they are severely underdeveloped.} 9. c3 Nxe4 10. Bg2 f5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Ge5,Gf5] A beautiful sight to behold.} 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Ne2 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5d5]} 13. Bd2 Qxd5 14. O-O O-O {Black has three pawns for the piece, and our pieces are also clearly dominating.} *

