1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bf4 {London-ish way of placing the bishop.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We can exploit the drawback of White's dark-squared bishop on [f4] instead of playing ...[e5] by targeting the [d4]-pawn.} (4... e5 {is also interesting to just fizzle out into an endgame after} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. O-O-O+ Nd7 8. Bd2 c6 9. Nf3 f6 10. g4 Nh6 11. g5 Nf7 {and so on...}) 5. Nf3 (5. d5 {will be met by a cool} e5 {.}) 5... Nf6 {[%csl Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc8g4]} 6. d5 e5 $1 {[%csl Rf4] This is the point, and Black achieves a good King's Indian setup.} 7. Bg5 Ne7 8. Bb5+ Nd7 $10 {[%cal Gh7h6,Ge8g8] Followed by ...[h6], ...[O-O], ...[f5], and Black achieves a comfortable game.} *

