1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Bf4 {London-ish way of placing the bishop.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We can exploit the drawback of White's dark-squared bishop on [f4] instead of playing ...[e5] by targeting the [d4]-pawn.} (4... e5 {is also interesting to just fizzle out into an endgame after} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. O-O-O+ Nd7 8. Bd2 c6 9. Nf3 f6 10. g4 Nh6 11. g5 Nf7 {and so on...}) 5. Nf3 (5. d5 {will be met by a cool} e5 {.}) 5... Nf6 {[%csl Rd4,Re4][%cal Gc8g4]} 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gf4h6]} Bg4 {[%csl Rf3] Pressurizing the [d4]-pawn.} 7. O-O-O O-O 8. Qe3 {[%cal Gd1d8]} (8. Bh6 {is met by} e5 {, and 8.Be2 is met by 8...Bxf3 followed by ...[e5], freeing the game. With the text move, White prevents Black from carrying out the freeing break with ...[e5].}) 8... Nh5 $1 {[%csl Rf4]} 9. Bg5 (9. Bh6 {is faced with} Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e5 {and Black controls the dark squares, with the knight on [h5] acting as a barricade against White's attack.}) 9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 f6 $1 11. Bh6 (11. Bh4 Qc8 {is a key move preparing ...[e5] and once again Black gets nice play.}) 11... e5 {[%csl Rd4,Rf4,Gh5] Black has achieved a balanced game with good control over the dark squares.} *

