1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh2h4] An interesting option to bring the bishop to [g2] in a dynamic manner.} Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. h4 {, and it is not easy for Black to coordinate the pieces. For instance, if} Nf6 {, then} 8. h5 gxh5 9. g5 {is really powerful, crushing Black. So, anyway, at some point, we need to develop our [b8]-knight to [d7] to push ...[c5].}) 6. Bg2 {If you switch on the online database, then you can see yours truly there.} h5 $1 {Forcing the g-pawn forward, so that after a subsequent ...[e6] and ...[Ne7], we gain a firm grip over the [f5]-square.} 7. g5 e6 ({The only way to develop the knight.} 7... e5 {is a mistake due to} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qd2 {followed by long castle.}) 8. f4 Ne7 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Ge6,Ge7,Gg6,Gg7] Accomplishing a hippopotamus structure that is solid and not easy to break.} 9. Nf3 d5 {Whenever White pushes [e5], Black gets full control over (and a nice outpost on) the [f5]-square.} 10. O-O b5 $10 {[%cal Gc8b7] I prefer Black, as our play is simple and automatic. Next, ...[Bb7] is on the cards.} *

