1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh2h4] An interesting option to bring the bishop to [g2] in a dynamic manner.} Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. h4 {, and it is not easy for Black to coordinate the pieces. For instance, if} Nf6 {, then} 8. h5 gxh5 9. g5 {is really powerful, crushing Black. So, anyway, at some point, we need to develop our [b8]-knight to [d7] to push ...[c5].}) 6. Bg2 {If you switch on the online database, then you can see yours truly there.} h5 $1 {Forcing the g-pawn forward, so that after a subsequent ...[e6] and ...[Ne7], we gain a firm grip over the [f5]-square.} 7. gxh5 Rxh5 {Yes, we have moved the rook, which means we cannot castle short. On the other hand, there is no rampage on the kingside, and we can now move with our pieces freely without having to worry about [h4], [g5], and [h5] stuff from White.} 8. f4 (8. Nge2 c5 {leads to the same story after} 9. f4 {.}) 8... c5 $1 ({This is critical. I went for} 8... Nb6 {, which is not good and I suffered in my game against Suarez but did win after some unexpected errors from my opponent.}) 9. Nge2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. Bxd4 Bxd4 {followed by ...[Ngf6] is also fine for Black.}) 10... Ngf6 11. h3 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gd7b6] Black has many plans like ...[e5] or ...[Nb6] to get the [c8]-bishop out.} *

