1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh2h4] An interesting option to bring the bishop to [g2] in a dynamic manner.} Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. h4 {, and it is not easy for Black to coordinate the pieces. For instance, if} Nf6 {, then} 8. h5 gxh5 9. g5 {is really powerful, crushing Black. So, anyway, at some point, we need to develop our [b8]-knight to [d7] to push ...[c5].}) 6. h4 {The juicers are coming to haunt our kingside.} h6 (6... h6 {Just sticking to the groove to face} 7. h5 {with} g5 {.}) (6... h5 {is not effective here due to} 7. gxh5 Rxh5 {, and the difference is that White's bishop is on [f1] and not [g2]. White can continue with} 8. Nf3 {, [Ng5], [Be2], and, after the rook retreats, [h5].}) 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White's plan is very obvious: to castle long and continue the rampage on the kingside.} b5 8. O-O-O Ngf6 {[%csl Rg4]} 9. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3,Gg4]} Nb6 {Keeping an eye on the [c4]-square. One of the ideas is ...[b4] followed by ...[Nc4] when White's knight retreats to [e2], cutting off the connection of the [f1]-bishop with the [c4]-square.} 10. Nh3 {The knight cannot head to [e2] due to ...[Nc4].} (10. Bd3 {is another natural move, but now we have the nice plan of regrouping the other knight with} Nfd7 {, preparing ...[c5].}) 10... h5 $1 {Now that we have the [d7]-square for the [f6]-knight, we can challenge the pawn on [g4].} 11. e5 (11. g5 {only helps Black:} Nfd7 {and ...[c5] will happen in the near future.}) 11... b4 ({Counterattack.} 11... Nfd5 {is met by} 12. Ng5 {.}) 12. exf6 bxc3 13. Qxc3 Bxf6 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Rc8g4,Rh5g4]} 14. gxh5 Rxh5 {[%csl Rh4] The [h4]-pawn is under attack now.} 15. Bg5 Rb8 $1 (15... Rb8 {Exerting pressure along the b-file:} 16. Bxf6 Nd5 17. Qd2 Bxh3 18. Bxh3 Nxf6 {with a balanced game.}) *

