1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh2h4] An interesting option to bring the bishop to [g2] in a dynamic manner.} Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. h4 {, and it is not easy for Black to coordinate the pieces. For instance, if} Nf6 {, then} 8. h5 gxh5 9. g5 {is really powerful, crushing Black. So, anyway, at some point, we need to develop our [b8]-knight to [d7] to push ...[c5].}) 6. h4 {The juicers are coming to haunt our kingside.} h6 (6... h6 {Just sticking to the groove to face} 7. h5 {with} g5 {.}) (6... h5 {is not effective here due to} 7. gxh5 Rxh5 {, and the difference is that White's bishop is on [f1] and not [g2]. White can continue with} 8. Nf3 {, [Ng5], [Be2], and, after the rook retreats, [h5].}) 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White's plan is very obvious: to castle long and continue the rampage on the kingside.} b5 8. O-O-O Ngf6 {[%csl Rg4]} 9. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3,Gg4]} Nb6 {Keeping an eye on the [c4]-square. One of the ideas is ...[b4] followed by ...[Nc4] when White's knight retreats to [e2], cutting off the connection of the [f1]-bishop with the [c4]-square.} 10. Nh3 {The knight cannot head to [e2] due to ...[Nc4].} (10. Bd3 {is another natural move, but now we have the nice plan of regrouping the other knight with} Nfd7 {, preparing ...[c5].}) 10... h5 $1 {Now that we have the [d7]-square for the [f6]-knight, we can challenge the pawn on [g4].} 11. gxh5 (11. g5 {only helps Black:} Nfd7 {and ...[c5] will happen in the near future.}) 11... Nxh5 12. Qf2 {[%csl Rg3] This move makes sense, as Black was planning to invade with ...[Ng3].} b4 {Black has to be quick in creating counterplay; otherwise, with our exposed king, we will certainly have some problems in the near future.} 13. Ne2 (13. Nb1 a5 14. Nd2 a4 {and the tables have turned in Black's favour as now our attack is faster on the queenside.}) 13... c5 {[%cal Gg7b2] This is the follow-up. Otherwise, the pawn push to [b4] would not make much sense.} 14. dxc5 Nc4 {[%cal Gg7b2]} 15. Bd4 (15. cxd6 Bxb2+ 16. Kb1 Be5 {and White's king is in danger.}) 15... e5 16. Ng3 (16. Be3 {fails to} Bxh3 17. Bxh3 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Bh6 {, and White loses the queen.}) 16... Bh6+ {[%cal Gh6c1]} 17. Kb1 Nxg3 18. Qxg3 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gf1c4]} Nd2+ {Black is winning an exchange now.} 19. Rxd2 Bxd2 20. Bxe5 Rh5 (20... Qxh4 {is premature in view of} 21. Nf2 Qxh1 22. Nxh1 Rxh1 23. Qg2 Rxf1+ 24. Qxf1 dxe5 25. Qh1 {⩲ followed by [Qh8]+. Material-wise, Black seems to be fine, but our pieces lack harmony.}) 21. Bxd6 Qxh4 $15 {White's attack is not enough for the exchange.} *

