1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh2h4] An interesting option to bring the bishop to [g2] in a dynamic manner.} Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. h4 {, and it is not easy for Black to coordinate the pieces. For instance, if} Nf6 {, then} 8. h5 gxh5 9. g5 {is really powerful, crushing Black. So, anyway, at some point, we need to develop our [b8]-knight to [d7] to push ...[c5].}) 6. h4 {The juicers are coming to haunt our kingside.} h6 (6... h6 {Just sticking to the groove to face} 7. h5 {with} g5 {.}) (6... h5 {is not effective here due to} 7. gxh5 Rxh5 {, and the difference is that White's bishop is on [f1] and not [g2]. White can continue with} 8. Nf3 {, [Ng5], [Be2], and, after the rook retreats, [h5].}) 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White's plan is very obvious: to castle long and continue the rampage on the kingside.} b5 8. O-O-O Ngf6 {[%csl Rg4]} 9. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3,Gg4]} Nb6 {Keeping an eye on the [c4]-square. One of the ideas is ...[b4] followed by ...[Nc4] when White's knight retreats to [e2], cutting off the connection of the [f1]-bishop with the [c4]-square.} 10. Nh3 {The knight cannot head to [e2] due to ...[Nc4].} (10. Bd3 {is another natural move, but now we have the nice plan of regrouping the other knight with} Nfd7 {, preparing ...[c5].}) 10... h5 $1 {Now that we have the [d7]-square for the [f6]-knight, we can challenge the pawn on [g4].} 11. gxh5 (11. g5 {only helps Black:} Nfd7 {and ...[c5] will happen in the near future.}) 11... Nxh5 12. Qf2 {[%csl Rg3] This move makes sense, as Black was planning to invade with ...[Ng3].} b4 {Black has to be quick in creating counterplay; otherwise, with our exposed king, we will certainly have some problems in the near future.} 13. Ne2 (13. Nb1 a5 14. Nd2 a4 {and the tables have turned in Black's favour as now our attack is faster on the queenside.}) 13... c5 {[%cal Gg7b2] This is the follow-up. Otherwise, the pawn push to [b4] would not make much sense.} 14. b3 {[%csl Rc4,Rc5] It is critical to stop ...[Nc4]. Now Black has to give an answer to the pressure around the [c5]-pawn.} Bxh3 $1 ({The direct} 14... c4 15. d5 Nd7 {(locks in the [c8]-bishop, and White also has [Nf4] ideas. With both their knights on [h3] and [e2], White can get rid of the blockade on [h5] the knight on [h5] and penetrate into the kingside. For all these reasons, we eliminate the [h3]-knight first.)}) 15. Bxh3 c4 16. f4 {This leads to an interesting and complex line.} cxb3 ({We can also start with} 16... a5 {followed by ...[cxb3] and ...[a4].}) 17. axb3 (17. cxb3 {is also met by} a5 {.}) 17... a5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Ga5a4]} 18. f5 gxf5 19. Qxf5 a4 {Let's see who is faster.} 20. Rhf1 {[%cal Gf1f7]} Bf6 (20... Bf6 {Barricading the f-file with the a nice idea in mind if White plays} 21. e5 {.}) 21. e5 axb3 22. exf6 b2+ $1 {This is the point.} 23. Kd2 (23. Kxb2 Nc4+ {and White is in big trouble.}) 23... Ra5 $3 {Only thanks to this idea Black is having a great advantange.} 24. Qf3 (24. Qxa5 Nc4+ {wins the queen.}) 24... d5 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Rd2][%cal Gb6c4] Followed by ...[Nc4]+. Though Black is a piece down, our pawn on [b2] is just one square away from promoting, and White's king is stuck in the center of the board. On the other side, White's attack is also sabotaged, so all these things work well in Black's favor.} *

