1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh2h4] An interesting option to bring the bishop to [g2] in a dynamic manner.} Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. h4 {, and it is not easy for Black to coordinate the pieces. For instance, if} Nf6 {, then} 8. h5 gxh5 9. g5 {is really powerful, crushing Black. So, anyway, at some point, we need to develop our [b8]-knight to [d7] to push ...[c5].}) 6. h4 {The juicers are coming to haunt our kingside.} h6 (6... h6 {Just sticking to the groove to face} 7. h5 {with} g5 {.}) (6... h5 {is not effective here due to} 7. gxh5 Rxh5 {, and the difference is that White's bishop is on [f1] and not [g2]. White can continue with} 8. Nf3 {, [Ng5], [Be2], and, after the rook retreats, [h5].}) 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White's plan is very obvious: to castle long and continue the rampage on the kingside.} b5 8. O-O-O Ngf6 {[%csl Rg4]} 9. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3,Gg4]} Nb6 {Keeping an eye on the [c4]-square. One of the ideas is ...[b4] followed by ...[Nc4] when White's knight retreats to [e2], cutting off the connection of the [f1]-bishop with the [c4]-square.} 10. Nh3 {The knight cannot head to [e2] due to ...[Nc4].} (10. Bd3 {is another natural move, but now we have the nice plan of regrouping the other knight with} Nfd7 {, preparing ...[c5].}) 10... h5 $1 {Now that we have the [d7]-square for the [f6]-knight, we can challenge the pawn on [g4].} 11. gxh5 (11. g5 {only helps Black:} Nfd7 {and ...[c5] will happen in the near future.}) 11... Nxh5 12. Qf2 {[%csl Rg3] This move makes sense, as Black was planning to invade with ...[Ng3].} b4 {Black has to be quick in creating counterplay; otherwise, with our exposed king, we will certainly have some problems in the near future.} 13. Ne2 (13. Nb1 a5 14. Nd2 a4 {and the tables have turned in Black's favour as now our attack is faster on the queenside.}) 13... c5 {[%cal Gg7b2] This is the follow-up. Otherwise, the pawn push to [b4] would not make much sense.} 14. b3 {[%csl Rc4,Rc5] It is critical to stop ...[Nc4]. Now Black has to give an answer to the pressure around the [c5]-pawn.} Bxh3 $1 ({The direct} 14... c4 15. d5 Nd7 {(locks in the [c8]-bishop, and White also has [Nf4] ideas. With both their knights on [h3] and [e2], White can get rid of the blockade on [h5] the knight on [h5] and penetrate into the kingside. For all these reasons, we eliminate the [h3]-knight first.)}) 15. Bxh3 c4 16. d5 {[%cal Rf2b6]} Nd7 ({I was trying hard to make the} 16... cxb3 {trick work but unfortunately it doesn't.} 17. Bxb6 bxa2 18. Kd2 Bh6+ 19. Kd3 {and White wins.}) 17. Nd4 cxb3 18. cxb3 Qc7+ 19. Kb1 a5 $132 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Ga5a4,Gd7c5,Gg7a1]} (19... a5 {Black can block} 20. Rc1 {with} Nc5 {, so nothing to worry about. Next, we will open the queenside with ...[a4], and the game is complex.}) *

