1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. a4 {[%csl Rb5] White does not allow Black's counterplay with ...[b5]. On the other hand, now White is unable to carry out a long castle, as they have already advanced [a4].} Nf6 {Time to develop the kingside now.} 6. h3 $5 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gg2g4] This makes sense, as it prevents the ...[Ng4] jump, which will in turn disturb the bishop on [e3]. One more idea of placing the pawn on [h3] is to indulge in the [g4] business.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] With the intent of ...[Bb7] next to pressurize the [e4]-pawn.} (6... O-O {is the alternative, but I don't like it due to} 7. g4 d5 8. e5 Ne4 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. b4 {, preventing ...[c5]. Following} f6 11. Bc4+ Kh8 12. Ne2 fxe5 13. d5 {, the bishop on [g7] is totaly limited.} Nd7 14. Ng3 Nf6 15. g5 Ne8 16. h4 {with a devastating attack on our king.}) 7. g4 Bb7 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rb7h1]} 8. Bg2 c5 {[%csl Rd4]} 9. Nge2 {Keeping the tension, but now the position turns into some kind of Sicilian.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 {This position resembles some sort of a favorable Dragon for Black as generally in the Dragon, the [c8]-bishop is not well placed.} Nbd7 11. g5 (11. O-O Nc5 {and the pressure on the [e4]-pawn gives Black a comfortable game.}) 11... Nh5 12. Bf3 {[%csl Rh5] Targeting the knight on [h5].} Rc8 $1 {We cannot protect the [h5]-knight, so instead, we create play around White's central [e4]-pawn, which will lose its strength when the light-squared bishop is exchanged on [h5]. So one might ask how the rook on [c8] helps in pressurizing the pawn on [e4]; the answer is simple: by sacrificing the exchange on [c3], we get to the [e4]-pawn.} 13. Bxh5 gxh5 14. Qxh5 {White gains the pawn but, in turn, loses the key light-squared bishop, and Black receives immense compensation.} O-O {[%cal Gc8c3,Gb7e4]} ({The direct} 14... Rxc3 {is also possible followed by ...[Bxe4].}) 15. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3] Not allowing ...[Rxc3] followed by ...[Bxe4], but the drawback is that the queen on [h5] is out of the game.} e6 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5] Restricting the knight on [d4]. The queen on [h5] is also out of the game, and next, Black can bring the [d7]-knight to [e5], followed by ...[Nc4].} *

