1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. a4 {[%csl Rb5] White does not allow Black's counterplay with ...[b5]. On the other hand, now White is unable to carry out a long castle, as they have already advanced [a4].} Nf6 {Time to develop the kingside now.} 6. h3 $5 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gg2g4] This makes sense, as it prevents the ...[Ng4] jump, which will in turn disturb the bishop on [e3]. One more idea of placing the pawn on [h3] is to indulge in the [g4] business.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] With the intent of ...[Bb7] next to pressurize the [e4]-pawn.} (6... O-O {is the alternative, but I don't like it due to} 7. g4 d5 8. e5 Ne4 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. b4 {, preventing ...[c5]. Following} f6 11. Bc4+ Kh8 12. Ne2 fxe5 13. d5 {, the bishop on [g7] is totaly limited.} Nd7 14. Ng3 Nf6 15. g5 Ne8 16. h4 {with a devastating attack on our king.}) 7. g4 Bb7 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rb7h1]} 8. Bg2 c5 {[%csl Rd4]} 9. d5 O-O 10. Nge2 Nbd7 {Black has accomplished the overall development but lacks space clearly and needs a breakthrough. So next, we will plan to carry out ...[b5] at any cost.} 11. O-O Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gb8b2] The direct ...[b5] is on the cards and one more plan is ...[Ne8]-[c7] and then ...[b5] also freeing the [g7]-bishop.} 12. Rb1 b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. b4 (14. Nxb5 {will be met by} Bxd5 {, and if} 15. Nxd6 Be6 $1) 14... Ba6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5]} 15. f4 Qc7 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gc5b4,Gf6g4] And it's a complex game. Black is actually threatening ...[cxb4] and ...[Nxg4] with the [c3]-knight under the radar of the queen on [c7].} (15... Qc7 {So play might continue with} 16. Qe1 {and then} Rfe8 {.}) *

