1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Nf3 {This is a really unpleasant move order to trick us, as against 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be3 , we prefer 5...O-O 6.Qd2 c5 , which is a very interesting approach that I have advocated in the previous chapters.} (5. Nf3 {With this move order, we cannot approach it in a similar way as we did above since we have committed to ...a6. The usual follow-up with} b5 {is the pretty common approach, but here it is slow, and White's attack is so powerful with [h4] and so on. Of course, we will analyze it a bit to understand why this is very strong for White to face ...[a6] and ...[b5] and why is White faster on the kingside.}) (5. Nf3 {So the question remains: how to face this annoying move order from White? After digging deep, I found that the} Nf6 {, ...[O-O], and ...[Nc6] plan to be the best.}) 5... Nf6 $1 ({➢ The best move in this position, avoiding} 5... b5 {altogether. The problem with 5...b5 is that after 6.h4 , Black is already in a tough spot. 6...Nf6 is the general response, but White has a strong resource here. (6...h5 7.Ng5 Nf6 8.Bd3! and Black suffers here. We have no proper counterplay. 8...O-O 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Ng4 11.e6 ± and Black's position is collapsing on the kingside. ) 7.h5! Nxh5 8.Ng5 , threatening [Rxh5]. 8...Nf6 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 and Black is in trouble, as once the knight drifts away from [f6], White can invade with [Nd5]. 11...Nh5 12.Nd5 Bxe5 13.g4 Nf6 14.Bg2 ± and Black has to take care of several threats from White on every move. Not a fun thing to do.}) ({➢} 5... Nd7 6. h4 Ngf6 7. Qe2 b5 (7... e5 8. O-O-O {±}) 8. e5 {+- .}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] The main critical plan. White is going to plant their bishop to [h6] next.} b5 {Since [h4] is no longer effective with our knight on [f6] already, we have to start the expansion on the queenside.} 7. Bd3 O-O (7... Bb7 {is met by} 8. e5 Ng4 {and} 9. e6 {, cruising into Black's camp.}) (7... Nbd7 {can be an alternative to maintain the bishop on [c8] so that the push with [e5]-[e6] is not that strong. Play continues after} 8. Bh6 Bxh6 9. Qxh6 e5 {and so on.}) 8. O-O-O (8. Bh6 Nc6 {transposes to the 7.Bh6 line.}) 8... b4 9. Ne2 Ng4 {[%csl Re3,Rf2] Wielding pressure on the [e3]-bishop.} 10. e5 ({The pawn grab} 10. Qxb4 {can be met by} c5 {, when after} 11. dxc5 Nxe3 12. fxe3 dxc5 13. Qxc5 Nd7 14. Qa3 Bb7 {, White is two pawns up but will have to fend off Black's long-term compensation given by the bishop pair and better structure. In fact, the [e7]-pawn can be sacrificed next by playing ...[Qc7], as initiative is more important than material. The fact that the engines give a very tiny plus to Black is already a good token.}) 10... a5 11. h3 Nxe3 12. Qxe3 {[%cal Gh3h4,Gh4h5] White's main threat is [h4]-[h5] and smash the kingside.} c5 {Opening on all fronts.} 13. dxc5 a4 $1 {Not caring about either pawn on [e5] or [c5]. Instead, coolly pushing the a-pawn all the way to create havoc around White's king.} (13... a4 14. Bc4 Qc7 {⇆ , and if 14.Be4 , we have 14...Ra6 . In case of 14.h4 , then our race is faster after 14...a3 15.b3 Nd7 with a lot of play.}) *

