s position is collapsing on the kingside. ) 7.h5! Nxh5 8.Ng5 , threatening [Rxh5]. 8...Nf6 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 and Black is in trouble, as once the knight drifts away from [f6], White can invade with [Nd5]. 11...Nh5 12.Nd5 Bxe5 13.g4 Nf6 14.Bg2 ± and Black has to take care of several threats from White on every move. Not a fun thing to do.}) ({➢} 5... Nd7 6. h4 Ngf6 7. Qe2 b5 (7... e5 8. O-O-O {±}) 8. e5 {+- .}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] The main critical plan. White is going to plant their bishop to [h6] next.} b5 {Since [h4] is no longer effective with our knight on [f6] already, we have to start the expansion on the queenside.} 7. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7]} O-O (7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 {followed by [e5] is annoying.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. Bd3 Nc6 {leads to the same story.}) 8... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5] The critical and the best direction Black has to go for.} 9. Nd5 {A rare option, but I could see a few correspondence games here.} Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Ng4 11. Qd2 e6 {[%csl Rd5] Kicking the knight before challenging the center with ...[e5].} 12. Ne3 e5 13. h3 Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e8] Next on the cards is ...[Re8] to put pressure on the [e4]-pawn.} 14. d5 Ne7 15. h4 (15. O-O-O Nh5 {is one idea so that when White expands with [g4], Black can occupy the [f4]-square, restricting the queen on [d2] from invading. Apart from 15...Nh5 , 15...c5 is also interesting to create some counterplay on the other side.}) 15... Kg7 16. O-O-O h6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc7c5] The attack on the kingside is contained. Next, Black can open on the queenside with ...[c6]. The point of the move ...[h6] is that whenever White rolls with [g4] and [h5], we can block with ...[g5]. Also, it takes away the square for the [f3]-knight to [g5].} 17. Rdg1 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Nh5 $132 (17... Nh5 {It is crucial to meet} 18. g4 {with} Nf4 {.}) *

