s position is collapsing on the kingside. ) 7.h5! Nxh5 8.Ng5 , threatening [Rxh5]. 8...Nf6 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 and Black is in trouble, as once the knight drifts away from [f6], White can invade with [Nd5]. 11...Nh5 12.Nd5 Bxe5 13.g4 Nf6 14.Bg2 ± and Black has to take care of several threats from White on every move. Not a fun thing to do.}) ({➢} 5... Nd7 6. h4 Ngf6 7. Qe2 b5 (7... e5 8. O-O-O {±}) 8. e5 {+- .}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] The main critical plan. White is going to plant their bishop to [h6] next.} b5 {Since [h4] is no longer effective with our knight on [f6] already, we have to start the expansion on the queenside.} 7. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7]} O-O (7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 {followed by [e5] is annoying.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. Bd3 Nc6 {leads to the same story.}) 8... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5] The critical and the best direction Black has to go for.} 9. e5 (9. Nd5 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Ng4 {followed by ...[e6] kicks the knight back.}) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Rh6]} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Arriving at a critical juncture. This position was discussed in a book of GM Parimarjan Negi in the Grandmaster Repertoire series.} 12. O-O-O b4 {[%csl Rc3]} 13. h3 bxc3 (13... Ngxe5 {is a mistake due to} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Qe3 {and the threats along the open d-file trouble Black.}) 14. Qxc3 Nxf2 {[%csl Rd1,Rh1][%cal Gf2h1,Gf2d1]} 15. e6+ f6 16. Qxc6 {[%csl Rc8,Rd8] Our queen and [c8]-bishop are shut in. So we have to find a way to release them.} Rb8 17. Bxg6 Rb6 $1 ({Including} 17... Nxd1 18. Rxd1 Rb6 {allows White to escape with a draw after} 19. Qa4 Rd6 20. Rxd6 Qxd6 21. Qg4 hxg6 22. Nh4 {and Black cannot avoid perpetual with [Qg6]-[h6]+.}) 18. Qa4 Rd6 19. Rxd6 Qxd6 20. Qh4 hxg6 21. Qxf2 Bxe6 $10 {Comp gives -0.16 for Black here, and practically, I feel we have more chances, thanks to the bishop combined with the free-flowing e-pawn.} *

