1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Nf3 {This is a really unpleasant move order to trick us, as against 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be3 , we prefer 5...O-O 6.Qd2 c5 , which is a very interesting approach that I have advocated in the previous chapters.} (5. Nf3 {With this move order, we cannot approach it in a similar way as we did above since we have committed to ...a6. The usual follow-up with} b5 {is the pretty common approach, but here it is slow, and White's attack is so powerful with [h4] and so on. Of course, we will analyze it a bit to understand why this is very strong for White to face ...[a6] and ...[b5] and why is White faster on the kingside.}) (5. Nf3 {So the question remains: how to face this annoying move order from White? After digging deep, I found that the} Nf6 {, ...[O-O], and ...[Nc6] plan to be the best.}) 5... Nf6 $1 ({➢ The best move in this position, avoiding} 5... b5 {altogether. The problem with 5...b5 is that after 6.h4 , Black is already in a tough spot. 6...Nf6 is the general response, but White has a strong resource here. (6...h5 7.Ng5 Nf6 8.Bd3! and Black suffers here. We have no proper counterplay. 8...O-O 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Ng4 11.e6 ± and Black's position is collapsing on the kingside. ) 7.h5! Nxh5 8.Ng5 , threatening [Rxh5]. 8...Nf6 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 and Black is in trouble, as once the knight drifts away from [f6], White can invade with [Nd5]. 11...Nh5 12.Nd5 Bxe5 13.g4 Nf6 14.Bg2 ± and Black has to take care of several threats from White on every move. Not a fun thing to do.}) ({➢} 5... Nd7 6. h4 Ngf6 7. Qe2 b5 (7... e5 8. O-O-O {±}) 8. e5 {+- .}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] The main critical plan. White is going to plant their bishop to [h6] next.} b5 {Since [h4] is no longer effective with our knight on [f6] already, we have to start the expansion on the queenside.} 7. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7]} O-O (7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 {followed by [e5] is annoying.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. Bd3 Nc6 {leads to the same story.}) 8... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5] The critical and the best direction Black has to go for.} 9. e5 (9. Nd5 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Ng4 {followed by ...[e6] kicks the knight back.}) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Rh6]} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Arriving at a critical juncture. This position was discussed in a book of GM Parimarjan Negi in the Grandmaster Repertoire series.} 12. O-O-O b4 {[%csl Rc3]} 13. Rhe1 $1 {[%csl Ge5]} Rb8 $1 ({We cannot capture the piece on c3. After} 13... bxc3 14. Qxc3 {, White has various threats. The piece on [c6] is hanging, and as well there are other added threats like [Be4] attacking [c6] and the [d8]-queen simultaneously.}) ({Now, after the text move} 13... Rb8 {, we are planning to capture the piece as we have the ...[Nb4] jump.}) 14. Na4 Qd5 {[%csl Re5,Ra2][%cal Gd5a2] By attacking the pawns on [e5] and [a2] simultaneously, Black creates dual threats on both the center and the queenside.} 15. b3 {Blocking out the queen.} Ngxe5 {We capture the key central pawn on [e5].} 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bf1 {[%cal Ge1e7,Gd2d5] By removing the defender on [d5], White eliminates Black's support for the [e5]-knight, which holds the game together. This, in turn, ensures that the knight no longer dominates the position.} Qxd2+ 18. Rxd2 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7] Supporting the pawn on [e7]. Right now, Black has an extra pawn.} 19. Rd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5c5] To my surprise, GM Negi has analyzed quite extensively and in greater depth way before. He has reached until here as well, covering various other moves for Black.} Nd8 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gd8e6] As [Rc5] was a big threat, we did not have any choice but to give up the pawn on [e7] and bring our knight to [e6], which is nicer than it being loose on [c6].} 20. Rde5 {[%csl Re7] This is the move prescribed by GM Negi in his book.} Ne6 {It looks natural to block out the rook.} 21. Bc4 {Planning [Bxe6] and [Nc5].} Kf6 22. Bxe6 Bxe6 23. Rc5 {[%csl Rc7]} Rfd8 $1 (23... Rfc8 {is met by} 24. Rc6 {and all of Black's pieces are stuck. The text move keeps the rook active.}) 24. Rc6 (24. Rxc7 Rbc8 {exchanges White's active rook.}) 24... Rd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e5]} 25. Rxa6 ({Negi has evaluated this position as slightly better for White, but is it so?} 25. Nc5 Rb6 26. Ne4+ Kg7 27. Rxc7 Rd7 {holds.}) 25... Rh5 {[%csl Rh2]} 26. h3 Re5 {Black's pieces are active and after the exchange on [e5], Black's king will also be a dominant force in the endgame. We have no particular weakness; as such, then why should we be slightly worse?} 27. Rxe5 Kxe5 28. Nc5 Bf5 29. Ra5 Kd6 $10 {Black keeps the position together in this complex endgame.} *

