1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Nf3 {This is a really unpleasant move order to trick us, as against 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Be3 , we prefer 5...O-O 6.Qd2 c5 , which is a very interesting approach that I have advocated in the previous chapters.} (5. Nf3 {With this move order, we cannot approach it in a similar way as we did above since we have committed to ...a6. The usual follow-up with} b5 {is the pretty common approach, but here it is slow, and White's attack is so powerful with [h4] and so on. Of course, we will analyze it a bit to understand why this is very strong for White to face ...[a6] and ...[b5] and why is White faster on the kingside.}) (5. Nf3 {So the question remains: how to face this annoying move order from White? After digging deep, I found that the} Nf6 {, ...[O-O], and ...[Nc6] plan to be the best.}) 5... Nf6 $1 ({➢ The best move in this position, avoiding} 5... b5 {altogether. The problem with 5...b5 is that after 6.h4 , Black is already in a tough spot. 6...Nf6 is the general response, but White has a strong resource here. (6...h5 7.Ng5 Nf6 8.Bd3! and Black suffers here. We have no proper counterplay. 8...O-O 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Ng4 11.e6 ± and Black's position is collapsing on the kingside. ) 7.h5! Nxh5 8.Ng5 , threatening [Rxh5]. 8...Nf6 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 and Black is in trouble, as once the knight drifts away from [f6], White can invade with [Nd5]. 11...Nh5 12.Nd5 Bxe5 13.g4 Nf6 14.Bg2 ± and Black has to take care of several threats from White on every move. Not a fun thing to do.}) ({➢} 5... Nd7 6. h4 Ngf6 7. Qe2 b5 (7... e5 8. O-O-O {±}) 8. e5 {+- .}) 6. Qd2 {[%cal Ge3h6] The main critical plan. White is going to plant their bishop to [h6] next.} b5 {Since [h4] is no longer effective with our knight on [f6] already, we have to start the expansion on the queenside.} 7. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7]} O-O (7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 {followed by [e5] is annoying.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. Bd3 Nc6 {leads to the same story.}) 8... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5] The critical and the best direction Black has to go for.} 9. e5 (9. Nd5 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Ng4 {followed by ...[e6] kicks the knight back.}) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Rh6]} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Arriving at a critical juncture. This position was discussed in a book of GM Parimarjan Negi in the Grandmaster Repertoire series.} 12. O-O-O b4 {[%csl Rc3]} 13. Rhe1 $1 {[%csl Ge5]} Rb8 $1 ({We cannot capture the piece on c3. After} 13... bxc3 14. Qxc3 {, White has various threats. The piece on [c6] is hanging, and as well there are other added threats like [Be4] attacking [c6] and the [d8]-queen simultaneously.}) ({Now, after the text move} 13... Rb8 {, we are planning to capture the piece as we have the ...[Nb4] jump.}) 14. Na4 Qd5 {[%csl Re5,Ra2][%cal Gd5a2] By attacking the pawns on [e5] and [a2] simultaneously, Black creates dual threats on both the center and the queenside.} 15. b3 {Blocking out the queen.} Ngxe5 {We capture the key central pawn on [e5].} 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bf1 {[%cal Ge1e7,Gd2d5] By removing the defender on [d5], White eliminates Black's support for the [e5]-knight, which holds the game together. This, in turn, ensures that the knight no longer dominates the position.} Qxd2+ 18. Rxd2 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7] Supporting the pawn on [e7]. Right now, Black has an extra pawn.} 19. Rd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5c5] To my surprise, GM Negi has analyzed quite extensively and in greater depth way before. He has reached until here as well, covering various other moves for Black.} Nd8 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gd8e6] As [Rc5] was a big threat, we did not have any choice but to give up the pawn on [e7] and bring our knight to [e6], which is nicer than it being loose on [c6].} 20. Rxe7 {The critical test not only regaining the pawn back but also conquering the seventh rank!} Ne6 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gg7f6] Next on the cards is ...[Kf6] to trap the rook on [e7].} 21. Nc5 (21. Nc5 {One idea is to meet} Kf6 {with} 22. Nd7+ {in order to save the [e7]-rook, and the other one is the obvious exchange of the knight on [e6], which guards the [c7]-pawn.}) 21... Kf6 22. Nd7+ Kxe7 23. Nxb8 {[%csl Ra6] The [a6]-pawn is vulnerable, and the knight on [b8] creates a huge ruckus in our camp. We have to deal with it cautiously.} Bb7 {[%csl Rd5]} (23... c5 {was played in only one existing game between GM Cheparinov and Asis in 2020 Sitges. White gets a free ride there after winning a pawn on [a6].}) 24. Rd7+ Kf6 {So far, all these moves have been forced.} 25. Nxa6 {White is a pawn up, but thanks to some concrete ideas, we are managing to hold the position together. That said, this is one line in the entire repertoire that I am not a big fan of. But sometimes, it is what it is.} Bc8 $1 {[%csl Rd7] The rook on the seventh rank is a powerful piece, exerting pressure on our pawns, so we have to kick it out.} 26. Rd5 {The best placement of the rook so that when we capture on [a6] and bring our rook to [a8], White can support the [a6]-bishop by [Ra5].} Bb7 27. Ra5 (27. Rd2 Bxa6 28. Bxa6 Ra8 {drops the [a2]-pawn.}) 27... Ra8 {[%csl Ra6] Thanks to the pin on the a-file, Black maintains compensation.} 28. Ra4 c5 {[%csl Ra4,Gb4,Gc5] The rook on [a4] is now in a weird place.} 29. a3 {The only way to free the rook.} bxa3 30. g3 (30. Rxa3 {would be a blunder due to} Nc7 {and the rook has no support on [a3] to rescue the [a6]-knight.}) 30... Ke5 {The king is also playing a major role now in providing more energy.} 31. Bc4 g5 $10 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gg5g4] It is not easy for White to make progress despite being a pawn up. Next, we can play ...[f5] with the idea of ...[g4].} *

