[White "11) Austrian Setup 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.f4"]
[Black "Austrian Setup 3.Nc3 d6 4.Be3 a6 5.f4 b5 6.a3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B06"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2159115898594281"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. f4 {The Austrian Attack with the inclusion of [Be3] is not that effective, as it wastes time and creates a target on [e3] ...[Nf5], ...[Ng4]. If you compare this to the main Austrian Attack, you will notice that White develops the [f1]-bishop to [d3] first and then castles immediately with the [c1]-bishop tucked in so that they can roll their pawn with [e5] and have a strong attack.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] In the footsteps of the ...[a6] move.} 6. a3 {This stops ...[b4] but is too slow. White should act quickly in the center to make use of their strong pawn mass. Hence, the text move on the other side of the board is harmless for Black.} Bb7 7. Nf3 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Preparing the key break ...[c5].} 8. Bd3 c5 {And already Black has taken over the game.} 9. e5 Nh6 {Next, Black is going to castle, and the inclusion of [a3] has reduced White's speed of striking in the center.} 10. e6 {Not too effective now and Black can simply ignore it.} Nf6 (10... fxe6 11. Ng5 {creates unnecessary drama.}) 11. exf7+ Nxf7 $15 {[%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Black has a great position with well-placed pieces. The two bishops on [g7] and [b7] are wide open and create a ruckus in White's camp.} *

