1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. f4 {The Austrian Attack with the inclusion of [Be3] is not that effective, as it wastes time and creates a target on [e3] ...[Nf5], ...[Ng4]. If you compare this to the main Austrian Attack, you will notice that White develops the [f1]-bishop to [d3] first and then castles immediately with the [c1]-bishop tucked in so that they can roll their pawn with [e5] and have a strong attack.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] In the footsteps of the ...[a6] move.} 6. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gf3a8] White is disoriented. I can understand White's idea is [Bf3], but the setup doesn't look threatening. This was actually the direction IM Christof Sielecki suggested in his Keep It Simple: 1.e4 series, but from our perspective, Black has nothing to fear.} Nd7 (6... Nd7 {is a sneaky move Sielecki didn't mention in his course. Black's idea is} 7. Bf3 e5 $1) 7. e5 {White's idea is a classic space grab, trying to restrict Black’s knight and follow up with [Bf3]. But guess what? Our knight is flexible – it finds another route via [h6]!} Nh6 {[%csl Rf5] The knight jump to [h6] has become a signature move in our repertoire. By heading to [f5], it becomes an active piece. For once, 'a knight on the rim is dim' doesn't apply; this knight is thriving on the edge!} 8. Bf3 Rb8 9. Nge2 O-O {Black has consolidated, and next, we will plan for ...[Nb6]-[c4] or ...[b4] and ...[c5].} 10. h4 {White makes a desperate attempt to muddy the waters with [h4], but we're faster! Our counterplay on the queenside with ...[b4] keeps White on the back foot.} b4 11. Ne4 Bb7 12. h5 c5 $132 {Black is doing well in this chaos. No need to fear White's h-pawn rampage since our knight on [h6] keeps the king safe while we press forward with our own counterplay.} *

