1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. f4 {The Austrian Attack with the inclusion of [Be3] is not that effective, as it wastes time and creates a target on [e3] ...[Nf5], ...[Ng4]. If you compare this to the main Austrian Attack, you will notice that White develops the [f1]-bishop to [d3] first and then castles immediately with the [c1]-bishop tucked in so that they can roll their pawn with [e5] and have a strong attack.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] In the footsteps of the ...[a6] move.} 6. Nf3 ({This resembles the Austrian Attack 4.f4 with one major difference: White has committed their bishop to e3. White can also start with} 6. Bd3 {, but it transposes to the text move after} Bb7 7. Nf3 {.}) 6... Bb7 7. Bd3 (7. e5 Nd7 8. Bd3 {simply transposes and has no independent value.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is the Black's setup. We are not able to play ...[Nf6] easily when White is aiming for [e5]. So first, we need to challenge the [d4]-pawn by ...[c5]. In order to do that, we need the knight on [d7] facilitating the ...[c5] breakthrough.} 8. O-O {This is the natural move, but it allows ...[c5].} c5 {[%cal Rg7a1] Yes, the much-needed breakthrough, and Black can free the position in a comfortable manner.} 9. e5 {White tries to maintain the tension and doesn't want to release it with [dxc5].} Nh6 10. Be4 {Black was planning for ...[Bxf3] and ...[cxd4] stuff, which weakens the support over the [e5]-pawn.} Bxe4 11. Nxe4 Nf5 {[%csl Rd4,Re3]} 12. Bf2 cxd4 13. exd6 O-O $1 {King's safety is important.} 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 {The obvious exchange since if we capture with the [f5]-knight, then we will have to lose the d-pawn.} 15. Bxd4 exd6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e8,Gd6d5] Yes, White does have control over the [a1]-[h8] diagonal, but there is nothing to worry about, as we will kick the knight on [e4] next with either ...[Re8] or ...[d5].} (15... exd6 {For example, after} 16. a4 {, we can count on} Re8 {with an equal position.}) *

