1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. f4 {The Austrian Attack with the inclusion of [Be3] is not that effective, as it wastes time and creates a target on [e3] ...[Nf5], ...[Ng4]. If you compare this to the main Austrian Attack, you will notice that White develops the [f1]-bishop to [d3] first and then castles immediately with the [c1]-bishop tucked in so that they can roll their pawn with [e5] and have a strong attack.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] In the footsteps of the ...[a6] move.} 6. Nf3 ({This resembles the Austrian Attack 4.f4 with one major difference: White has committed their bishop to e3. White can also start with} 6. Bd3 {, but it transposes to the text move after} Bb7 7. Nf3 {.}) 6... Bb7 7. Bd3 (7. e5 Nd7 8. Bd3 {simply transposes and has no independent value.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is the Black's setup. We are not able to play ...[Nf6] easily when White is aiming for [e5]. So first, we need to challenge the [d4]-pawn by ...[c5]. In order to do that, we need the knight on [d7] facilitating the ...[c5] breakthrough.} 8. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Preparing long castle.} c5 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1] Time to open up the game before White castles long, as then the d-file will be under the rook's control on [d1].} 9. e5 {[%csl Rg7] This is one of the crucial ways to react against the ...[c5] break so that the [g7]-bishop will be locked.} b4 (9... Bxf3 {is also possible but leads to a long line after} 10. Qxf3 cxd4 11. Bxd4 dxe5 12. fxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Bxe5 14. O-O-O Qb8 15. Nd5 Nf6 16. Rhf1 O-O 17. Nxe7+ Kg7 18. Nc6 Qc7 19. Rde1 Bf4+ 20. Qxf4 Qxc6 21. g4 h6 22. h4 Rad8 23. g5 hxg5 24. hxg5 Nh5 25. Qe5+ Kg8 26. Be4 Qd6 {and Black equalizes.}) ({I thought we had other simpler options rather than venturing into this long forced variation, and hence, I prefer} 9... b4 {.}) 10. Be4 (10. Ne4 {is met by} c4 {, while 10.Na4 by 10...Bxf3 and the evaluation of the earlier long variation is changed in Black's favor because White's knight is misplaced on [a4].}) 10... Qc8 {[%csl Gb7,Gc8]} 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 {[%csl Re4] And her highness controls the [e4]-square.} 12. Na4 cxd4 13. Bxd4 dxe5 14. Nxe5 (14. fxe5 e6 {kills all of White's play.}) 14... Nxe5 15. O-O-O {None of the alternatives promise White anything – [Nc5] can be met by ...[Qc6], while the various captures on [e5] allow Black to play either ...[Nf6] or ...[Nh6] followed by short castle.} Nh6 $10 {[%cal Ge8g8] Next, Black will castle and secure the king with a balanced game.} *

