1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. f4 {The Austrian Attack with the inclusion of [Be3] is not that effective, as it wastes time and creates a target on [e3] ...[Nf5], ...[Ng4]. If you compare this to the main Austrian Attack, you will notice that White develops the [f1]-bishop to [d3] first and then castles immediately with the [c1]-bishop tucked in so that they can roll their pawn with [e5] and have a strong attack.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] In the footsteps of the ...[a6] move.} 6. Nf3 ({This resembles the Austrian Attack 4.f4 with one major difference: White has committed their bishop to e3. White can also start with} 6. Bd3 {, but it transposes to the text move after} Bb7 7. Nf3 {.}) 6... Bb7 7. Bd3 (7. e5 Nd7 8. Bd3 {simply transposes and has no independent value.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is the Black's setup. We are not able to play ...[Nf6] easily when White is aiming for [e5]. So first, we need to challenge the [d4]-pawn by ...[c5]. In order to do that, we need the knight on [d7] facilitating the ...[c5] breakthrough.} 8. a4 {This is often seen when Black's pawn is on [b5].} b4 9. Ne2 c5 {[%cal Gg7b2]} 10. c3 {White may seem to have stabilized, but as they say, appearances can be deceiving! Black now gets the [g8]-knight into the game.} Ngf6 {[%csl Re4] And once again, thanks to the bishop placed on [e3], Black gets counterplay.} 11. e5 (11. Ng3 {is met by a typical plan of} h5 {and White is not able to hold the [e4]-pawn intact.}) 11... Ng4 {[%csl Re3] Now you see why the bishop is not well placed on [e3].} 12. Bc1 O-O 13. h3 {Here I suggest a dynamic response. Black has many moves apart from the text.} dxe5 {[%cal Ge5e4]} ({Nothing wrong with} 13... Bxf3 {and 13...Nh6 . The text move is alluring because we get immense play.}) 14. dxe5 Ngxe5 $3 {Bam!!} 15. fxe5 Nxe5 {[%csl Rd3,Rf3]} 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 {[%csl Re1] Black has sacrificed the piece for two pawns, and our activity is just killing with constant threats around the king, especially given the bishops on [e5] and [b7], who are just cruising into White's camp.} 17. O-O Qd5 {[%cal Gb7g2]} 18. Rf2 Rad8 {[%cal Gd8d1]} 19. Bf4 {The only counter to save the piece.} c4 20. Bc2 Qc5 {[%cal Gc5g1]} 21. Qf1 b3 $15 {And it is White who has to be cautious here with all their pieces going backwards.} (21... b3 {A sample line is} 22. Bxe5 Qxe5 23. Bd1 Rd2 24. Nd4 Qe3 {, when the engine suggests White should give up the bishop on [b3], or play} 25. Bf3 Bxf3 26. Nxf3 (26. Re1 Qxf2+ {with a better endgame for Black.}) 26... Rxb2 {, when Black's pawns outweigh the knight.}) *

