1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. f4 {The Austrian Attack with the inclusion of [Be3] is not that effective, as it wastes time and creates a target on [e3] ...[Nf5], ...[Ng4]. If you compare this to the main Austrian Attack, you will notice that White develops the [f1]-bishop to [d3] first and then castles immediately with the [c1]-bishop tucked in so that they can roll their pawn with [e5] and have a strong attack.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gg7a1] In the footsteps of the ...[a6] move.} 6. Nf3 ({This resembles the Austrian Attack 4.f4 with one major difference: White has committed their bishop to e3. White can also start with} 6. Bd3 {, but it transposes to the text move after} Bb7 7. Nf3 {.}) 6... Bb7 7. Bd3 (7. e5 Nd7 8. Bd3 {simply transposes and has no independent value.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is the Black's setup. We are not able to play ...[Nf6] easily when White is aiming for [e5]. So first, we need to challenge the [d4]-pawn by ...[c5]. In order to do that, we need the knight on [d7] facilitating the ...[c5] breakthrough.} 8. e5 {[%csl Rg7] Before Black opens up with ...[c5], White plans to attack on the kingside and barricade the [g7]-bishop at the same time.} Nh6 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ge8g8,Gh6f5,Gc7c5]} (8... c5 {is recommended by Vjeko in his Uncompromising Modern Defense course. I like the text move of developing the knight first and then carrying the important break ...[c5], keeping the options flexible. Doing necessary things first, like developing the knight.}) 9. O-O c5 {Black is already planning to capture on [f3] and on [d4], weakening the [e5]-pawn, so White needs to intervene.} 10. Be4 Bxe4 11. Nxe4 cxd4 12. Bxd4 Nf5 $10 {[%csl Rd4,Gf5][%cal Ge8g8]} (12... Nf5 {Black frees the position. A sample line, at the end of which the engine insists Black is to be preferred, is} 13. exd6 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 O-O 15. dxe7 Qxe7 16. Qd3 Rfe8 17. Rae1 Nc5 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. c3 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 b4 {. Black can also opt for 16...Rac8 or 16...Nc5 , and in all cases, it turns out that the bishop on [g7] is a strong piece.}) *

