e same time.} Nh6 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ge8g8,Gh6f5,Gc7c5]} (8... c5 {is recommended by Vjeko in his Uncompromising Modern Defense course. I like the text move of developing the knight first and then carrying the important break ...[c5], keeping the options flexible. Doing necessary things first, like developing the knight.}) 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1] The main move, planning to castle long.} c5 $1 {Time to strike before White castles long.} 10. dxc5 (10. O-O-O b4 {and the white knight has no proper square since} 11. Ne4 c4 {exists, and 11.Na4 Bc6 also keeps the knight under threat.}) 10... dxe5 (10... Nxc5 11. Bxc5 dxc5 12. O-O-O {is the problem.}) 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. fxe5 O-O 13. O-O-O Qc7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc7e5]} (13... Bxe5 {is not possible due to} 14. Bxh6 {.}) 14. Kb1 Rad8 $1 {[%cal Gc7e5]} ({Crucial, as if we capture the e5-pawn now, there are some consequences. For example} 14... Qxe5 15. Bxh6 Qxe2 16. Bxe2 Bxh6 {and White can chip in with} 17. Nd5 {, and we have to face an unpleasant endgame. The text move improves the position of our pieces and, at the same time, keeps an eye on the [e5]-pawn. Next, of course, we will regain the pawn back on [e5].}) 15. a3 (15. e6 $2 {is well met by} f5 $1 {with a clear advantage for Black given the ...[Ng4] and ...[f4] ideas. White's structure is weak, and that yields more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 15... Qxe5 16. Bxh6 Qxe2 17. Bxe2 Bxh6 18. Bf3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Bd2 {[%csl Rc3]} 20. Ne4 Bf4 $10 {[%cal Gf7f5] Followed by ...[f5] and White's knight has no proper square to jump forward.} *

