1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] We will have to check this move every time, as it creates an ambitious threat of [h5].} h5 $1 {This is important. Otherwise, White will push the h-pawn all the way, creating deadly threats.} ({Unfortunately, the natural} 5... Nf6 $2 {is a big mistake, as it allows the deadly} 6. h5 $1 {, a well-known exchange sacrifice that happened in many games, including Prag-Carlsen 2022, and White was superior in the arising complications.} Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 e6 9. e5 d5 10. O-O-O {± followed by [f4] and [Nf3] with a crushing advantage.}) 6. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3][%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] With the plan of [Qd2], [O-O-O] and [Nh3].} b5 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} Nf6 8. O-O-O {The logical follow-up.} b4 $1 9. Nce2 a5 10. Nf4 Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] Aiming for ...[e5] at the right moment.} 11. Qe1 {[%cal Gd1d8] White prevents ...[e5] for the time being by drifting the queen and giving free range for the rook on [d1], which is pinning the [d8]-queen.} Nd7 $1 {Quite unusual, but the idea is clear: blocking the [d1]-rook and preparing ...[e5] at all cost.} 12. Bb5 Na7 {[%csl Rb5]} 13. Be2 Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] Coming back to carry out ...[e5].} 14. Ngh3 e5 {And finally, we get the desired breakthrough.} 15. dxe5 Ncxe5 16. Kb1 O-O 17. g4 hxg4 {Thanks to the attack on the [h3]-knight, White cannot ignore it and continue with an attack on the h-file with the [h5] push.} 18. fxg4 Bb7 {[%cal Gb7e4]} 19. Nf2 b3 $1 {A nice idea, creating play on the queenside with tempo.} 20. cxb3 a4 21. b4 a3 $132 {[%csl Ra2,Rb1,Rb2] Exposing the white king and Black is preferable here.} *

