1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] We will have to check this move every time, as it creates an ambitious threat of [h5].} h5 $1 {This is important. Otherwise, White will push the h-pawn all the way, creating deadly threats.} ({Unfortunately, the natural} 5... Nf6 $2 {is a big mistake, as it allows the deadly} 6. h5 $1 {, a well-known exchange sacrifice that happened in many games, including Prag-Carlsen 2022, and White was superior in the arising complications.} Nxh5 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Qxh5 e6 9. e5 d5 10. O-O-O {± followed by [f4] and [Nf3] with a crushing advantage.}) 6. Nh3 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh3g5] White wants to puncture the knight to [g5], creating threats around Black's king. White will enjoy a nice outpost on [g5] since Black cannot kick it with ...[h6], while ...[f6] would be a positional concession.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 7. f3 {[%csl Rg4]} ({Stopping ...Ng4 makes sense, as the immediate} 7. Ng5 {will be met by} Ng4 8. Bf4 Nc6 {.}) 7... b5 {Time to create counterplay. We can also capture the knight on [h3] and follow it with ...[Nbd7].} ({But in this particular position, White gets a nice attack after} 7... Bxh3 8. Rxh3 Nbd7 9. Qe2 {, an important place for the queen not blocking the rook on [d1] after White castles long. Play will continue} b5 10. O-O-O {with a powerful thrust of [e5] coming next thanks to the queen on [e2]. So when White places the queen on [d2], then we can capture on [h3]. So, for now, we keep the idea in mind.}) 8. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} Bxh3 {And now yes, we take it.} 9. Rxh3 Nbd7 {[%csl Re5]} 10. O-O-O b4 (10... c6 {is played in most of the games, which is also possible, with the plan of ...[Rb8], ...[a5], ...[Nb6], and so on, but I feel it is a bit slow compared to the text, which feels like in the spirit of Modern Defense, to create play as soon as possible.}) ({The direct} 10... c5 {is worse due to} 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Bf4 {with the [e5] plan and Black cannot avoid it by any means.}) 11. Ne2 c5 {Now we have our desired breakthrough.} 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Bf4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} (13. e5 Nxe5 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. Bxc5 a5 {, and no worries for Black in this endgame.}) 13... e6 $1 (13... e6 {With the intent to meet} 14. e5 {with} Nd5 {.}) 14. Qd6 (14. Bd6 Qb6 {, with the trick of ...[Nd5], allows Black to free the game.}) 14... Qb6 $10 {After the exchange of queens, Black can challenge the [d6]-bishop by ...[Bf8], and we are able to push White's pieces back.} *

