ortant place for the queen not blocking the rook on [d1] after White castles long. Play will continue} b5 10. O-O-O {with a powerful thrust of [e5] coming next thanks to the queen on [e2]. So when White places the queen on [d2], then we can capture on [h3]. So, for now, we keep the idea in mind.}) 8. Ng5 O-O 9. Qd2 c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7a1] The typical pawn sacrifice to open up the Dragon bishop on [g7].} 10. dxc5 (10. d5 Nbd7 {doesn't help White.}) 10... dxc5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxc5 {[%cal Gc5e7] Black has lost a pawn, but in turn, Black has a tremendous activity, which provides decent compensation.} Nc6 {Here, White has a couple of plans of how to place their pieces.} 13. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1]} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Rb6]} ({The direct} 13... Nd7 {is met by} 14. Be3 Nd4 15. O-O-O {. The text move is useful in covering the [b6]-square. For example, after 14.Be3 Nde5 , White can insert their knight to [d5] by 15.Nd5 and invade on [b6] as well.}) 14. Rd1 Rxd1+ 15. Nxd1 Nd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 16. Be3 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2,Gd4e2]} 17. Bd3 (17. Kd2 Nxe2 18. Kxe2 b4 {restricts White's pieces, and the bishop pair gives us a balanced game.}) 17... Nc5 $10 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4] The dominating knights provide Black good compensation.} *

