ortant place for the queen not blocking the rook on [d1] after White castles long. Play will continue} b5 10. O-O-O {with a powerful thrust of [e5] coming next thanks to the queen on [e2]. So when White places the queen on [d2], then we can capture on [h3]. So, for now, we keep the idea in mind.}) 8. Ng5 O-O 9. Qd2 c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7a1] The typical pawn sacrifice to open up the Dragon bishop on [g7].} 10. dxc5 (10. d5 Nbd7 {doesn't help White.}) 10... dxc5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxc5 {[%cal Gc5e7] Black has lost a pawn, but in turn, Black has a tremendous activity, which provides decent compensation.} Nc6 {Here, White has a couple of plans of how to place their pieces.} 13. Bb6 {The main move, worsening the position of Black's rook before developing their light-squared bishop.} Rd7 14. Bd3 {[%csl Rd7]} Rb7 15. Be3 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d6,Gd6c4,Gg7b2]} (15... Nd7 {is slow here, and White can react with} 16. f4 {, shutting the knight. This is another knight sortie to come to [c4] via [d6].}) 16. f4 Nb4 $1 (16... Nd6 {is imprecise due to} 17. e5 Nc4 18. Bc5 {.}) 17. e5 Nxd3+ 18. cxd3 Bg4 {[%cal Ge8c7] The lights squares are in Black's control; next, we can bring the [e8]-knight into the game via [c7].} *

