1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. h4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 7. Bh6 ({This is the first reaction we have to take care of.} 7. f3 h5 {would transpose.}) 7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 Nbd7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc7c5]} (8... b4 9. Nd5 {exists.}) 9. h5 (9. f3 c5 {and Black gets the needed counterplay.}) ({And if} 9. O-O-O {now, we can play} b4 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Nf6 {, and Black is just in time to consolidate thanks to the rotation of the other knight to [f6].}) 9... b4 10. Nd5 Nxh5 11. O-O-O Bb7 $132 {[%cal Ge7e6] Nothing is threatening from White's side.} *

