1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5] The second plan, apart from the main [O-O-O] and [h4] ideas, is to stir up the [b5]-pawn.} b4 {As we cannot maintain it anymore on [b5], we are forced to push ...[b4]. So now the question is where the knight is going to move to.} 7. Nce2 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} (7... Nf6 8. f3 Nbd7 {is also equally good.}) 8. Qxb4 Rb8 {[%csl Rb4]} 9. Qa3 (9. Qc3 c5 {puts a lot of pressure along the [h8]-[a1] diagonal.}) 9... c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7b2,Gb8b2]} 10. f3 Ngf6 11. O-O-O (11. Nh3 Qb6 12. O-O-O O-O {and White's queen is clearly misplaced on [a3], which gives Black good compensation for the pawn loss.}) 11... Qa5 $15 {[%csl Ra4] Black is much better here with all of our pieces in an ideal world.} *

