1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5] The second plan, apart from the main [O-O-O] and [h4] ideas, is to stir up the [b5]-pawn.} b4 {As we cannot maintain it anymore on [b5], we are forced to push ...[b4]. So now the question is where the knight is going to move to.} 7. Nd5 {[%csl Rb4] A possible option, but White should be ready to be kicked once again when Black plays ...[c6].} a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4] Supporting the pawn on [b4].} 8. c3 c6 {Exploiting the drawback of White's knight on [d5].} 9. Nf4 Nf6 {[%csl Re4] With tempo and Black gains a lead in development.} 10. f3 (10. Bd3 Ng4 {loses the bishop pair.}) 10... O-O 11. cxb4 axb4 12. Qxb4 Nbd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gc6c5] Followed by ...[Rb8], ...[c5], and so on, opening up the diagonal of the Dragon bishop on [g7], and Black is, in fact, slightly better here due to our lead in development.} *

