1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5] The second plan, apart from the main [O-O-O] and [h4] ideas, is to stir up the [b5]-pawn.} b4 {As we cannot maintain it anymore on [b5], we are forced to push ...[b4]. So now the question is where the knight is going to move to.} 7. Nd1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gd2b4] The advantage of having the queen on [d2] – the knight can retreat to [d1] instead of [e2], where it would obstruct the [f1]-bishop.} a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4]} 8. f3 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3]} (8. f3 {With the idea of facing} Nf6 {with} 9. Bh6 {.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} ({As} 8... Nf6 9. Bh6 {is very powerful, we will have to develop the other knight, aiming for ...[c5].}) 9. c3 bxc3 10. Nxc3 c6 $1 {[%csl Rc3] Restricting the [d5] push, and next, Black will develop the knight to [f6].} 11. d5 (11. Bd3 Ngf6 12. Nge2 Ba6 {equalizes.}) 11... cxd5 12. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Ba6 14. Bb5 Ngf6 $10 {Black is doing good here with ...[Bxb5] and ...[Ne5] coming next.} *

