1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5] The second plan, apart from the main [O-O-O] and [h4] ideas, is to stir up the [b5]-pawn.} b4 {As we cannot maintain it anymore on [b5], we are forced to push ...[b4]. So now the question is where the knight is going to move to.} 7. Nd1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gd2b4] The advantage of having the queen on [d2] – the knight can retreat to [d1] instead of [e2], where it would obstruct the [f1]-bishop.} a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4]} 8. f3 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3]} (8. f3 {With the idea of facing} Nf6 {with} 9. Bh6 {.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} ({As} 8... Nf6 9. Bh6 {is very powerful, we will have to develop the other knight, aiming for ...[c5].}) 9. Bb5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gb5e8] Not allowing ...[c5] and White now plans to seal with [d5] next.} Bb7 10. Ne2 c6 11. Bd3 Qc7 (11... Ngf6 {is again met by} 12. Bh6 {and since White has not castled short, they will follow it up with the h-pawn roll. So the text move is a useful move, waiting for White to castle so that the [h4]-pawn rolls are not effective.}) 12. c3 bxc3 13. Ndxc3 (13. bxc3 Ba6 {and we exchange our bad bishop on [b7].}) 13... Ngf6 {We are running out of useful moves, so we will have to develop the [f6]-knight, allowing the [Bh6] invasion. The only thing we have to care about is whether we will be equipped when White penetrates with [Bh6].} 14. Bh6 O-O 15. h4 Bxh6 16. Qxh6 Ba6 {Exchanging the other bishop as well so that White does not have some [e5] ideas in the future.} 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. h5 {It looks scary with h-file getting opened up, but Black withholds the game.} e5 19. g4 Rb8 {[%cal Gd7f8] Counterplay on the b-file and at the same facilitating the [d7]-knight to [f8] to safeguard the king.} 20. hxg6 (20. g5 Nxh5 21. Rxh5 gxh5 22. Ng3 Kh8 {and Black is in time to meet} 23. Nf5 {with} Rg8 {.}) 20... fxg6 21. g5 Nh5 22. Rxh5 gxh5 23. g6 Nf8 $10 {[%cal Gf8g6,Gf8h7,Gc7h7] Black protects the king.} *

