1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. O-O-O Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb5b4]} ({Threatening ...b4.} 6... Bb7 {looks natural as well but is imprecise here, as Black lacks this option of exchanging the [c8]-bishop for the deadly [h3]-knight.} 7. h4 h5 8. f3 {and the bishop on [b7] is limited.} Nd7 9. Nh3 {and I don't like this for Black, as White can simply seal the knight on [g5] with a nice attack, and the bishop on [b7] does not do much as it is confined by the [f3]-[e4] pawn chain.} c5 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Bd4 Nf6 12. e5 {± and Black is totally worse here with the king in the center.}) 7. Bh6 {White is not well equipped for this idea, as their [e4]-pawn is not yet well strengthened, and this point is reflected in the arising variation.} Bxh6 8. Qxh6 b4 {[%csl Re4] And now you can see why [f3] is required before venturing into [Bh6] business.} 9. Nd5 Nxe4 10. Re1 c6 11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. f3 f5 $10 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5] Black holds on to not exposing the e-file.} *

