1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. O-O-O Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb5b4]} ({Threatening ...b4.} 6... Bb7 {looks natural as well but is imprecise here, as Black lacks this option of exchanging the [c8]-bishop for the deadly [h3]-knight.} 7. h4 h5 8. f3 {and the bishop on [b7] is limited.} Nd7 9. Nh3 {and I don't like this for Black, as White can simply seal the knight on [g5] with a nice attack, and the bishop on [b7] does not do much as it is confined by the [f3]-[e4] pawn chain.} c5 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Bd4 Nf6 12. e5 {± and Black is totally worse here with the king in the center.}) 7. a3 {A novelty from White. Surprisingly, there are no games in my database. I can understand that it slows down White's kingside attack with [f3], [g4], [h4], and so on, but it is still a logical option, as it prevents Black's expansion on the queenside with ...[b4].} Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} ({With the light-squared bishop still on f1 instead of d3 as we previously seen,} 7... Ng4 {is only an empty shot and well met by} 8. Bf4 {since the pawn on [d4] is defended now.}) 8. f3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] We have formulated our setup, so next we will strike with ...[c5].} 9. Bh6 {Here, Black has to be careful since if we castle short, then White has a powerful attack with [h4].} Bxh6 10. Qxh6 e6 {[%cal Gd8e7]} ({Next, the queen on d8 will land on e7 followed by the ...c5 breakthrough. Another interesting computer-like option for Black is} 10... Qc8 {followed by ...[c5].}) 11. Nge2 Qe7 12. h4 c5 13. Kb1 O-O-O $10 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8c7,Gd7b8] Black has consolidated the game. Some of our plans are ...[Kb8], ...[Nb8] or ...[Ne8]-[c7], and so on.} *

