1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] A logical developing move preparing [Qd2] and long castle, and whenever Black moves the [g8]-knight, White can insert [Bh6], exchanging the important bishop on [g7], weakening Black's king.} ({According to the lichess database, this is played much more than the other main move,} 4. f4 {.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's main idea to create counterplay is to push ...[b5] and play ...[Bb7]. There are two ways to do this. Either by ...[c6] and ...[b5] or ...[a6] and ...[b5]. In the Pirc Defense, Black generally opts for the ...[c6] and ...[b5] plan. But in the Modern, we prefer the setup with ...[a6] and ...[b5] in order not to block the [c8]-bishop.} 5. Qd2 {White's plan here is free flowing, like long castle, [f3], [h4], [Nh3], and think next.} b5 6. O-O-O Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb5b4]} ({Threatening ...b4.} 6... Bb7 {looks natural as well but is imprecise here, as Black lacks this option of exchanging the [c8]-bishop for the deadly [h3]-knight.} 7. h4 h5 8. f3 {and the bishop on [b7] is limited.} Nd7 9. Nh3 {and I don't like this for Black, as White can simply seal the knight on [g5] with a nice attack, and the bishop on [b7] does not do much as it is confined by the [f3]-[e4] pawn chain.} c5 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Bd4 Nf6 12. e5 {± and Black is totally worse here with the king in the center.}) 7. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3][%cal Ge3h6,Gh2h4] The main move and next [Bh6] is on the list.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] Black wants to pitch in ...[Nb6].} 8. h4 {[%cal Gg1h3,Gh4h5,Gg2g4,Gg4g5]} Nb6 9. Bh6 {A game between Shankland and Nakamura has taken place in a blitz game in 2022. We have to watch out for [Bh6] always, as it is a natural and logical idea to change the key bishop and create holes in the dark squares.} Bxh6 ({Hikaru played the strange} 9... Bf8 {and he was totally worse in the game, but he tricked Shank in the end. Typical Hikaru things. :}) 10. Qxh6 Bb7 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd8e7] Black's plan is ...[e6], ...[Qe7] and long castle to stabilize the king.} 11. Nh3 e6 {[%cal Gd8e7] Black intends to pursue long castling after ...[Qe7]. Once we do that, we are well stabilized.} 12. e5 dxe5 13. dxe5 Nfd7 14. Qg7 (14. h5 Qe7 15. hxg6 fxg6 {and Black is totally fine as long castle cannot be stopped.}) 14... Ke7 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gd8f8]} ({Only move, as} 14... Rf8 {fails to} 15. Ng5 {and [Nxh7]. Next on the cards is ...[Qf8].}) 15. Qh6 b4 16. Ne2 Qf8 17. Qd2 Kd8 $13 {[%cal Gd8c8] Haha, it's a circus. The king is going to escape via [c8], and then Black will expand with ...[a5].} *

