1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. e5 $6 {This is premature and gives ample counterplay for Black.} Nfd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Already ...[c5] is incoming, and it is tough for White to hold the center together without proper development.} 6. Nf3 c5 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] Crushing the center.} 7. e6 {A typical pawn sacrifice in this opening to weaken the position of Black's king.} fxe6 8. Ng5 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gg5e6]} Nf6 {[%cal Gc8e6] Protecting the key pawn on [e6].} 9. dxc5 Nc6 (9... dxc5 {is an obvious mistake due to} 10. Qxd8+ {and the [Nf7]+ fork.}) 10. Be2 O-O $10 {Black consolidates.} *

