1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. a3 {The thought of why [a3] will be lingering in your minds right now. It has a concrete purpose. For that, let's understand what are Black's ideas. The main agenda of Black is to challenge the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5]. Now that the [e5]-square is heavily controlled by the [f4] and [d4]-pawns, we have to concentrate our forces towards the ...[c5] break. For Black to carry out ...[c5], Black has to prepare how to face [dxc5]. Generally, for [dxc5], Black has this nice intermediate queen sortie to [a5], ...[Qa5] threatening ...[Nxe4] and planning to capture the [c5]-pawn back with the queen, maintaining the intactness of the pawn structure and the center. Now, coming back to why [a3], the point is that whenever Black follows up with ...[Qa5] after ...[c5] [dxc5], White can push the b-pawn to [b4], totally barricading the queen.} O-O {Completing development before shooting towards the center.} 6. Bd3 {This is inaccurate here.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Since the bishop on [d3] is obstructing the queen, the [d4]-pawn becomes pressurized. One more point is that Black is preparing the ...[e5] thrust to challenge White's central pawn mass.} 7. Nf3 (7. d5 Nd4 8. Nge2 {is met by simply taking on [e2] followed by ...[c6], undermining the center, and Black is totally fine.}) 7... Bg4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1]} 8. Be3 e5 {[%csl Rd4] Black has achieved a dream scenario where White is unable to stabilize their center. In fact, computers prefer Black here.} 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qd2 exf4 11. Bxf4 Nh5 $10 (11... Nh5 {Black is more than comfortable here.} 12. Be3 Ne5 {or 12.Bg5 Bf6 , both these options give Black a good game, as White's center is dissolved.}) *

