1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. a3 {The thought of why [a3] will be lingering in your minds right now. It has a concrete purpose. For that, let's understand what are Black's ideas. The main agenda of Black is to challenge the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5]. Now that the [e5]-square is heavily controlled by the [f4] and [d4]-pawns, we have to concentrate our forces towards the ...[c5] break. For Black to carry out ...[c5], Black has to prepare how to face [dxc5]. Generally, for [dxc5], Black has this nice intermediate queen sortie to [a5], ...[Qa5] threatening ...[Nxe4] and planning to capture the [c5]-pawn back with the queen, maintaining the intactness of the pawn structure and the center. Now, coming back to why [a3], the point is that whenever Black follows up with ...[Qa5] after ...[c5] [dxc5], White can push the b-pawn to [b4], totally barricading the queen.} O-O {Completing development before shooting towards the center.} 6. Nf3 c5 {Anyway, we don't shy away from the ...[c5] break. The game turns concrete now.} 7. dxc5 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e1,Ra5c5,Rf6e4]} (7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. e5 {gives a pleasant endgame for White. Hence, we need to create counterplay by the text move.}) 8. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4] Supporting the [e4]-pawn, but now Black can recapture the [c5]-pawn with the queen without conceding the center as in the case of capturing back with the [d6]-pawn.} Qxc5 {[%cal Gc5g1] White is unable to castle now, and their only option is to bring the [c1]-bishop to [e3] to get rid of the queen on [c5].} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1e3] Facilitating [Be3] next.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2] Anticipating [Be3] and acting in preventive mode as now the [b2]-pawn hangs. White has to waste one more move before bringing the bishop to [e3].} 10. Rb1 {[%csl Gb1,Gb2]} Nbd7 11. Be3 Qc7 12. O-O {Finally, White has castled.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] The only piece that is not developed is the [c8]-bishop, so it is time.} 13. a4 {White prevents ...[b5], but Black can move the pawn to [b6] and then develop the last piece.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b6]} (13... b6 {is also possible, but why unnecessarily allow White to play the [f5] breakthrough? Hence, some more preventive measures on the kingside. The problem is that after} 14. f5 {, we will be forced to recapture on [g6] with the h-pawn, which is not ideal:} Bb7 15. fxg6 hxg6 (15... fxg6 $2 {now is immediately countered by} 16. Bc4+ {followed by [Nd5] or [Ng5] with big pressure.}) 16. Qf2 {, when White's straightforward plan of a kingside attack with [Qh4] and [Ng5] is rather unpleasant.}) 14. f5 Nc5 15. fxg6 fxg6 $10 {Again, it is important to recapture with the f-pawn in order to maintain harmony and connection among our pieces.} *

