1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. a3 {The thought of why [a3] will be lingering in your minds right now. It has a concrete purpose. For that, let's understand what are Black's ideas. The main agenda of Black is to challenge the center with ...[e5] or ...[c5]. Now that the [e5]-square is heavily controlled by the [f4] and [d4]-pawns, we have to concentrate our forces towards the ...[c5] break. For Black to carry out ...[c5], Black has to prepare how to face [dxc5]. Generally, for [dxc5], Black has this nice intermediate queen sortie to [a5], ...[Qa5] threatening ...[Nxe4] and planning to capture the [c5]-pawn back with the queen, maintaining the intactness of the pawn structure and the center. Now, coming back to why [a3], the point is that whenever Black follows up with ...[Qa5] after ...[c5] [dxc5], White can push the b-pawn to [b4], totally barricading the queen.} O-O {Completing development before shooting towards the center.} 6. Nf3 c5 {Anyway, we don't shy away from the ...[c5] break. The game turns concrete now.} 7. dxc5 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e1,Ra5c5,Rf6e4]} (7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. e5 {gives a pleasant endgame for White. Hence, we need to create counterplay by the text move.}) 8. b4 {The main point behind the pawn on [a3], but the drawback is that the [h8]-[a1] diagonal is under fire now.} Qd8 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1]} ({Back to square one. :} 8... Qc7 {is another option, but the queen is not well placed there due to [Nb5] jumps in some lines. For example,} 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nb5 {disturbs the queen.}) 9. Rb1 ({Moving out of the h8-a1 pin.} 9. e5 dxe5 10. fxe5 Ng4 {is worse for White.}) ({Another option for White is} 9. Bd2 {, but it is met by} a5 {, challenging the [b4]-pawn.} 10. Rb1 axb4 11. axb4 dxc5 12. bxc5 Nfd7 {and we regain the pawn.}) 9... Nh5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gg7c3]} ({A logical novelty as the knight is pretty active on h5.} 9... Nfd7 {is played in some games, but I don't like the fact that it obstructs the [c8]-bishop.}) 10. Nd5 (10. Na4 Bd7 {and White has problems with their knight.}) 10... dxc5 11. bxc5 Nd7 {[%csl Rc5]} 12. e5 ({Blunting the bishop on g7, as Black was threatening ...e6 and ...Bc3+. For example, if} 12. Be3 {, then} e6 {followed by ...[Bc3]+ is disrupting White's harmony.}) 12... Nxc5 13. Be3 b6 $10 {[%cal Gc8b7] Followed by ...[Bb7] and I like Black's position. We can always expel the [d5]-knight with ...[e6].} *

