1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 {The bishop is generally better placed on [d3] than on [e2], as it strengthens the [e4]-pawn. Hence, this option is not so critical.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. dxc5 (7. d5 e6 {, and we have a good version of Benoni-type of positions as the white pawn is still on [c2] and not on [c4], fortifying the [d5]-pawn.}) 7... Qa5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga5e1] Now one can see the drawback of the bishop on [e2]. The [e4]-pawn is hanging, and thanks to this tactic, Black recaptures the pawn on [c5] with the queen.} 8. O-O Qxc5+ 9. Kh1 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7,Gb8d7] Black's setup is ...[b5], ...[Bb7] and ...[Nbd7].} 10. a4 {[%csl Rb5]} b6 $10 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8d7] If not ...[b5], then ...[b6] is the way to go, preparing ...[Bb7].} *

