1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Be3 {A rare option played at Grandmaster level, but it looks logical to prevent the ...[c5] breakthrough, with the plan of [Qd2] followed by [O-O-O]. Let's see how to respond.} Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5]} ({One of the best responses against the Be3 setup. Another interesting option is} 6... Ng4 {followed by ...[c5].}) 7. Qd2 (7. e5 {is quite dubious due to} Ng4 {followed by ...[c5].}) 7... c5 8. O-O-O Qa5 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ra5d2]} 9. Kb1 (9. Bd3 b5 {is just crushing, as White cannot capture the [b5]-pawn due to the weak [a2]-pawn.}) 9... b5 $1 {Time for counterplay before White consolidates with [Bd3].} 10. Nxb5 (10. Bxb5 Nxe4 {is the problem.}) 10... Qxd2 11. Nxd2 Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} 12. d5 a6 13. Nc3 Ng4 14. Bg1 f5 {[%csl Rc3,Rd5,Re4][%cal Gg7c3,Gb7h1] Black gets more than enough counterplay for the pawn loss. White's center is just dismantled.} *

