1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. e5 {Yes, this is needed, but not now without securing the white king, and hence it becomes premature.} dxe5 7. fxe5 Nd5 8. Bc4 (8. Ne4 Bf5 9. Ng3 Bg4 {and White has wasted too many moves with the knight.}) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5] White has doubled pawns on the c-file, but the pawn chain [e5]-[d4]-[c3] is formidable. So, the next move creates an imbalance in White's camp.} c5 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gg4d1,Gc5d4]} 10. O-O Bg4 {All eyes on the [d4]-pawn.} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {[%cal Gf3b7]} Nc6 {Necessary, as the [b7]-pawn was hanging.} 13. Bxf7+ Kh8 {[%cal Gf8f1]} 14. e6 cxd4 15. Rb1 dxc3 16. Rxb7 Qc8 $132 {[%cal Gc6e5,Gc6d4] Next, Black will play ...[Ne5] or ...[Nd4] with a comfortable game. The bishop on [f7] is stuck, and our king is safe on [h8] guarded by the [g7]-bishop. All these factors give a slight preference to Black.} *

