1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 {The best square for the [f1]-bishop, strengthening the [e4]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] The recent trend of facing the Four Pawns Austrian Attack. Black prepares ...[e5] next to challenge White's center.} 7. h3 {[%csl Rg4] Stopping ...[Bg4] is a sensible alternative to the main line.} e5 $1 {As White is slower with this approach, we can strike in the center efficiently.} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. O-O Nh5 $1 {[%csl Rf4] The knight is forcing White to release the tension around the [f4]-pawn.} 10. f5 (10. fxe5 Nxe5 11. g4 Nf6 12. Nxe5 Qd4+ {and Black is doing well.}) 10... Ng3 {[%csl Rf1,Rf5] Double attack.} 11. fxg6 Nxf1 12. gxh7+ Kh8 13. Qxf1 Nd4 $1 {13.Bg5 Qe8 14.Nh4 was a very annoying threat, so we prevented that from happening.} 14. Nxd4 Qxd4+ 15. Kh1 Be6 $10 {White definitely has some compensation for the exchange but not more. Black's position is also solid, and the game is balanced.} *

