1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 {The best square for the [f1]-bishop, strengthening the [e4]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] The recent trend of facing the Four Pawns Austrian Attack. Black prepares ...[e5] next to challenge White's center.} 7. Be2 $5 {One might wonder why White just played [Bd3] and now the bishop is going back to [e2]. There is a subtle point to it. After 6.Be2 , we had the option to break with ...[c5], which is absent here. And the bishop is better placed on [e2] than on [d3], as it makes the ...[Bg4] pin less effective.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Ge7e5]} ({Now} 7... e5 {is not that effective due to} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. fxe5 Ng4 11. Nb5 {, and so on. With the bishop on [d3], White couldn't exchange queens and target the [c7]-pawn. Now, it's a different story. Hence, we have to pressurize the [f3]-knight by placing our bishop on [g4]. The idea is ...[Bxf3] and ...[e5].}) 8. e5 dxe5 9. fxe5 (9. dxe5 Qxd1+ {followed by ...[Nd7] and ...[f6] also neutralizes White's play.}) 9... Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f6] Next, we will immediately break with ...[f6].} (9... Nd7 {instead allows} 10. Ne4 {and if} f6 11. c3 fxe5 12. d5 Ncb8 13. Nfg5 {, when Black is under pressure. After 9...Ne8 , White should better keep an eye on the [d4]-pawn since ...[Bxf3] is a big threat.}) 10. Be3 f6 $1 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 e5 {We have to be fast and take advantage of White's uncastled king. If given time to consolidate, White would start taking over.} 14. Bxc6 (14. dxe5 {is parried by} Nxe5 15. Bxb7 Nc4 16. Qxd8 (16. Bxa8 $2 Qxa8 {gives Black a winning advantage since both [g2] and [Be3] are under attack.}) 16... Raxd8 17. Bxa7 Rfe8+ 18. Kf2 {, and here the engine wants} c6 {, but 18...Rd2+ followed by ...[Nxb2] is totally fine for Black given White's clumsy pieces.}) 14... bxc6 15. O-O (15. dxe5 Nd5 {followed by ...[Qh4] is risky for White.}) 15... e4 $10 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gf8e8] Next on the cards is ...[Rb8], ...[Re8], and so on. The game is equal.} *

