1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 {The best square for the [f1]-bishop, strengthening the [e4]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] The recent trend of facing the Four Pawns Austrian Attack. Black prepares ...[e5] next to challenge White's center.} 7. Be2 $5 {One might wonder why White just played [Bd3] and now the bishop is going back to [e2]. There is a subtle point to it. After 6.Be2 , we had the option to break with ...[c5], which is absent here. And the bishop is better placed on [e2] than on [d3], as it makes the ...[Bg4] pin less effective.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Ge7e5]} ({Now} 7... e5 {is not that effective due to} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. fxe5 Ng4 11. Nb5 {, and so on. With the bishop on [d3], White couldn't exchange queens and target the [c7]-pawn. Now, it's a different story. Hence, we have to pressurize the [f3]-knight by placing our bishop on [g4]. The idea is ...[Bxf3] and ...[e5].}) 8. d5 {Before Black strikes with ...[e5], White gains space and pushes the [c6]-knight.} Nb8 {[%cal Gc7c6]} 9. O-O c6 {Black undermines the pawn on [d5] while also vacating the c-file for the rook, improving piece activity and creating counterplay.} 10. Be3 {This is a normal developing move to prevent any …Qb6+ ideas in the near future.} cxd5 11. exd5 Na6 $1 ({A precise move to get the knight to c5 via a6 rather than d7 since after} 11... Nbd7 {, White can hit the bishop on [g4] by} 12. h3 {, and we will not have the [d7]-square for it.}) 12. h3 Bd7 13. Qd2 Nc5 14. Rfe1 Rc8 $10 {[%csl Gc5] Black has got good control over the c-file with a strong knight on [c5].} *

