2] than on [d3], as it makes the ...[Bg4] pin less effective.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Ge7e5]} ({Now} 7... e5 {is not that effective due to} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. fxe5 Ng4 11. Nb5 {, and so on. With the bishop on [d3], White couldn't exchange queens and target the [c7]-pawn. Now, it's a different story. Hence, we have to pressurize the [f3]-knight by placing our bishop on [g4]. The idea is ...[Bxf3] and ...[e5].}) 8. d5 {Before Black strikes with ...[e5], White gains space and pushes the [c6]-knight.} Nb8 {[%cal Gc7c6]} 9. h3 Bxf3 {We have to give up the bishop, as retracting it would lead to [e5].} 10. Bxf3 c6 {[%csl Rd5] This is necessary to conquer the c-file after ...[Nbd7] and ...[Rc8].} 11. Be3 cxd5 12. exd5 Nbd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Bd4 {[%cal Gd4g7] The best move in the position. Let's see a sample line of how Black should react, as it is impossible to analyze all the numerous possibilities. We just need to know how to place our pieces.} ({After} 14. Bxa7 {, Black has even better than} b6 15. Nb5 {, which is not so simple. Instead, 14...Rxc3! 15.bxc3 b6 is very strong. White loses the bishop to ...[Qc7] next, when the engine claims a winning advantage for Black.}) 14... Qa5 (14... Ne8 {is also possible, exchanging the dominating bishop on [d4].}) 15. Re1 Rfe8 {[%csl Ge7,Ge8][%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] Black's ideas are ...[Nb6]-[c4] or ...[b5]-[b4].} 16. Rb1 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 17. a3 {White had to prevent ...[b4].} a6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5]} 18. Na2 {[%cal Ga2b4,Gb4c6] White plans to occupy the [c6]-square by this knight maneuver. So, we have to act quickly to dismantle the [d5]-pawn.} Qc7 19. Nb4 Nc5 $10 {[%cal Ge7e5] Followed by ...[e5]/[e6] and we exchange the [d5]-pawn with a fine game.} *

