1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 {The best square for the [f1]-bishop, strengthening the [e4]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] The recent trend of facing the Four Pawns Austrian Attack. Black prepares ...[e5] next to challenge White's center.} 7. e5 dxe5 8. fxe5 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4]} ({Here,} 8... Nd5 {is not good due to} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. c3 f6 {and} 11. Qe2 {threatening [Bc4] as well as [c4] and [d5] if Black opposes with} Be6 {. The queen is clearly misplaced on [d5], and hence, we have to change the knight's route to a different square.}) 9. Be3 Bg4 10. Be2 {Unpinning.} f6 {It's important to break the pawn chain of [d4]-[e5] with this freeing move.} 11. d5 {Yours truly faced this against GM Aryan Chopra in the MPL Indian Chess Tour of the chess24 series way back in 2022.} Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 fxe5 14. O-O-O Nf6 $1 ({Instead of} 14... Nf6 {, I played 14...Nf4 followed by ...[Nxg2], which was weird and I lost the game badly for having no sense of danger.}) 15. Qc4 Kh8 $10 {Black's position is good. Though we have an extra pawn, it is of no use because it is not well connected.} *

