1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} Nf6 ({In this particular case, I would like to develop the knight first, as I felt quick development might be crucial. Definitely,} 4... a6 {is the choice if we have to walk in the footsteps of the Modern Defense setup. But the drawback is that it gives White the momentum built up by their strong pawn chain of [e4], [d4] & [f4]. We have to be precise in some resulting variations, as we are hanging by a thread there.}) ({Having said that, I have also suggested it as an alternative with analysis in greater depth in a separate chapter for people who would like to stick up to the Modern Defense vibes. Practically, it is still playable and complex in nature.} 4... Nf6 {is comparatively solid. One can make a choice depending on the opponent.}) 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3] The main line. It has similar vibes to the King's Indian Defense but with a major difference, as the white pawn would be on [c4] instead of [f4].} ({White can also start with} 5. Bd3 {, which will later transpose to the main line after} O-O 6. Nf3 Nc6 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 {The best square for the [f1]-bishop, strengthening the [e4]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] The recent trend of facing the Four Pawns Austrian Attack. Black prepares ...[e5] next to challenge White's center.} 7. O-O e5 {In the spirit of King's Indian, striking in the center.} 8. d5 Nd4 ({The knight is more active here compared to} 8... Ne7 {, when I felt Black is very passive after} 9. Kh1 exf4 10. Bxf4 {.}) 9. f5 $1 {[%csl Rg7] Playing against the [g7]-bishop by killing its activity is the acid test for Black's pieces.} c6 {[%csl Rd5] The central pawns have to be undermined to ease the game, as not only the Dragon bishop on [g7] is restricted but also the [c8]-bishop is blocked by the white pawns on [d5] and [f5].} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] No more ...[cxd5] threats, as White can capture back with the knight thanks to the pin along the [h4]-[d8] diagonal.} h6 {Asking a question to the bishop.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd2 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ga2a4]} Nb5 $1 {Before White plays [a4] and corners the knight, we get out.} 13. dxc6 {This is a crazy line.} Nxc3 14. cxb7 Qb6+ {Intermezzo.} 15. Kh1 Nxd1 16. bxa8=Q Nf2+ 17. Rxf2 (17. Kg1 {falls into the smothered mate after} Nh3+ 18. Kh1 Qg1+ 19. Rxg1 Nf2# {and I am pretty sure every 5-year-old child will know the pattern of a smothered mate.}) 17... Qxf2 18. Nc4 Qc5 {Thanks to the bishop pair, Black has enough compensation for the pawn.} *

