[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Defense"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Austrian Attack 4.f4 a6 – Alternative"]
[Black "Austrian Attack 4.f4 a6 – Alternative: 6.Bd3 | Informational 6...Nd7"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B06"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[GameId "2159115900089411"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is the main direction recommended by Vjeko Nemec in his Chessable course The Uncompromising Modern Defense. Black develops the knight first with the intention of ...[c5], but somehow after analyzing it quite deeply, I see problems everywhere, and moreover, the arising variations are extremely dangerous for Black with White's central pawn mass [d4], [e4], [f4] threatening to pierce Black's camp.} 7. a4 $1 ({Disrupting the pawn on b5.} 7. e5 {is interesting as well to punish Black's slow development.}) 7... b4 ({This is Vjeko's direction in his course.} 7... b4 {is one of the main ways to deal against the [a4] breakthrough, but it does release the tension, and White is in time to fortify the center after} 8. Ne2 c5 9. c3 {and Black has zero counterplay here. Moreover, it is not easy to bring the [g8]-knight into the game. For instance, if} Ngf6 {,} 10. e5 {is always annoying.}) (7... c5 {is another way to react against the 7.a4 breakthrough, to counter the attack in the center, but it does not work here due to} 8. axb5 cxd4 9. Nd5 {. Let's continue the line showcasing why this counter idea does not work.} Ngf6 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. e5 $1 {Concrete action leading to a forced line after} dxe5 12. fxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Qf3 Ra7 15. bxa6 {± and the passed [a6]-pawn is just two steps away from promoting.}) 8. Ne2 c5 9. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4] A stable center is always a treasure to have.} Bb7 (9... a5 {gives the option of} 10. Bb5 {.}) 10. O-O (10. a5 {is also doable and Black will suffer there as well.}) 10... cxd4 ({Again, Black cannot play} 10... Ngf6 {due to} 11. e5 {.}) 11. cxd4 a5 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gb7a6] When I see such moves on the queenside without even developing the kingside pieces, I feel something is off, and I will just mention a sample line showcasing how dangerous Black's position is.} 12. Ng3 Qb6 13. Kh1 {[%cal Rb6g1] Away from the [b6]-[g1] pin.} h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} 14. Ne2 Ba6 15. f5 $1 {Time to pave through the kingside. This thrust was not mentioned in Vjeko's course, and White is taking over here with a powerful attack.} gxf5 16. Ng3 $1 {[%csl Re8]} fxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxf1 18. Bxa8 Bc4 19. Bg5 $16 {[%csl Re8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Ga1c1] Followed by Rc1 gives a strong initiative. Black is stuck with the kingside pieces underdeveloped. This is one of the main reasons I did not like the direction of 6...Nd7 .} *

