counterplay idea, without which we would be crushed.} 9. Ng5 {This is critical, as White goes all in to expose our king.} Nh6 (9... cxd4 {is not effective here.} 10. e6 f5 {, to stop from getting mated, we sacrifice a piece.} 11. exd7+ Qxd7 12. Ne2 h6 13. Nf3 e5 {and Black might claim there is enough compensation with the juicers dominating in the center, if not for the maneuver with} 14. Nh4 {, which is really powerful, not allowing Black to stabilize.}) 10. f5 {All in. No stepping back.} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6g1]} ({One needs a cool attitude not to be scared of the pawn roll on the kingside and just act as if nothing happened. One such move is} 10... Qb6 {.}) 11. Be4 (11. f6 exf6 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Qe2+ Kd7 {, and we escape.}) 11... Bxe4 12. f6 $1 {Haha. Modern chess is so concrete.} Bb7 13. fxg7 Rg8 14. e6 cxd4 15. exd7+ Kxd7 16. Nce4 Nf5 {[%csl Gd4,Gd6,Ge7,Gf7,Gg6] The dust has settled. We have sacrificed a piece for some pawns. Practically, I like Black's position, as we can simply roll out our juicers and it is White who has to respond to it in a precise manner.} 17. Qd3 f6 18. Nf3 Rac8 {[%cal Gb6c6,Gc8c2,Gc6e4]} (18... Rac8 {Threatening ...Qc6 if White plays} 19. Bd2 {. That is the idea of 18...Rac8.}) 19. Ng3 Nxg7 20. Rf2 e5 {[%csl Gd4,Gd6,Ge5,Gf6] Black has great compensation with our intact pawns.} *

