1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Both bishops are fianchettoed now towards the d4 and e4-pawn respectively. This will be my suggestion if you would like to play the 4.f4 a6 system.} 7. O-O Nd7 8. a4 {This is one of the major problems. In the end, we kind of neutralize by holding on to a thread with many concrete moves. This direction is also one of the reasons I am not so happy about the 4...a6 system, as every time, we need to play some accurate moves. Having said that, White also needs some precision to create problems. You can check the lines and decide for yourself if you are happy with it or if you prefer the solid 4...Nf6 system.} c5 $1 {We often see that Black reacts in this manner to White's breakthrough with [a4] rather than pushing our pawn to [b4].} (8... b4 {only helps White since after} 9. Ne2 c5 10. c3 {, White builds up a great center. There are only three games in my database here, so it is a relatively fresh concept. A young Hans Neimann from 2019 also approves us, as he is one of the Black players who played ...[c5] here.}) 9. axb5 cxd4 10. Ne2 ({All the three White players chose} 10. Ne2 {here. 10.Na4 is the main move discussed here; the other knight move, 10.Nd5 , is met by 10...e6 .}) 10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 (11... Qxa8 12. Nexd4 Bxe4 13. Nxb5 {, threatening [Nc7]+, and the queen on [a8] is under some threats. So it's better to take with the bishop on [a8].}) 12. Nexd4 Ngf6 {[%csl Re4]} 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Nxb5 Nc5 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd3,Re4]} 15. Nc3 (15. e5 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Ng4 {and Black is taking over with the bishop pair.}) 15... Qb6 {[%cal Gb6g1]} 16. Kh1 Qb4 {[%csl Re4]} 17. Re1 Rc8 $132 {Black is preferable. Though White has an extra pawn, their pieces are stuck.} *

