r problems. In the end, we kind of neutralize by holding on to a thread with many concrete moves. This direction is also one of the reasons I am not so happy about the 4...a6 system, as every time, we need to play some accurate moves. Having said that, White also needs some precision to create problems. You can check the lines and decide for yourself if you are happy with it or if you prefer the solid 4...Nf6 system.} c5 $1 {We often see that Black reacts in this manner to White's breakthrough with [a4] rather than pushing our pawn to [b4].} (8... b4 {only helps White since after} 9. Ne2 c5 10. c3 {, White builds up a great center. There are only three games in my database here, so it is a relatively fresh concept. A young Hans Neimann from 2019 also approves us, as he is one of the Black players who played ...[c5] here.}) 9. axb5 cxd4 10. Na4 {The top choice of the engine.} axb5 11. Bxb5 Bxe4 {Again, the position is totally messy and only clings on to concrete resources.} 12. Bxd7+ (12. Nxd4 Ngf6 {and Black consolidates with castle coming next.}) 12... Kxd7 {Forced, as if we capture with the queen, then White has the knight fork on [b6].} 13. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5f7,Gg5e4]} (13. Nxd4 Nf6 14. Be3 Qb8 {followed by ...[Rc8], ...[Ke8], and Black consolidates slowly.}) 13... Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc7c6] With the plan of ...[Qc7]-[c6].} ({For a long time, the computer was suggesting} 13... Bc6 {over 13...Bb7 , but after probing it in greater depth, the computers increased the evaluation to White's favor.}) ({So} 13... Bc6 14. Nxf7 Qa5 {, targeting the [a4]-knight.} 15. Bd2 Qa7 16. Qg4+ Kc7 17. Qe6 d3+ 18. Be3 {, and so on.}) 14. Nxf7 {[%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8]} Qc7 {[%csl Ra4,Rg2][%cal Gc7c6]} 15. Rf2 $1 {[%cal Gf2g2] Guarding [g2], which I don't think is easy to find if White players don't have this course. :P Generally, one automatically takes on [h8].} Qc6 {[%cal Ga8a4]} 16. c3 d3 (16... dxc3 {is a mistake, as White has} 17. Ne5+ {.}) 17. Be3 Ke8 {[%csl Rf7] Forcing White to take on [h8].} 18. Nxh8 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Not in a hurry to take on [f8]. Time matters here to create counterplay, so we bring in more energy.} 19. Nxg6 hxg6 20. b3 {[%csl Ga4,Gb3][%cal Gd1d3]} (20. Qxd3 Rxa4 21. Qxg6+ Kf8 {, and Black defends everything.}) 20... Qd5 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Gd5][%cal Gd5d3] Supporting the key [d3]-pawn.} 21. Rd2 {[%csl Gg2,Rd3][%cal Ga1a2,Gd2d3] White's plan next is [Raa2], defending the [g2]-pawn so that they can capture on [d3] with the other rook.} Qe4 $1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge4e3]} 22. Qf3 {The only way to neutralize the dangerous battery of the queen and bishop on the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} Qxf3 23. gxf3 Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e3,Gd5c3,Gg7a1] Activating all the forces.} 24. Rxd3 (24. Re1 Nxc3 25. Rxd3 Nxa4 {16.bxa4 Rxa4 and it is soon heading towards a draw.}) 24... Nb4 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 25. Rd2 Bxc3 $10 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ga8a1] Thanks to the pin, we regain the material.} *

