r problems. In the end, we kind of neutralize by holding on to a thread with many concrete moves. This direction is also one of the reasons I am not so happy about the 4...a6 system, as every time, we need to play some accurate moves. Having said that, White also needs some precision to create problems. You can check the lines and decide for yourself if you are happy with it or if you prefer the solid 4...Nf6 system.} c5 $1 {We often see that Black reacts in this manner to White's breakthrough with [a4] rather than pushing our pawn to [b4].} (8... b4 {only helps White since after} 9. Ne2 c5 10. c3 {, White builds up a great center. There are only three games in my database here, so it is a relatively fresh concept. A young Hans Neimann from 2019 also approves us, as he is one of the Black players who played ...[c5] here.}) 9. axb5 cxd4 10. Na4 {The top choice of the engine.} axb5 11. Bxb5 Bxe4 {Again, the position is totally messy and only clings on to concrete resources.} 12. Bxd7+ (12. Nxd4 Ngf6 {and Black consolidates with castle coming next.}) 12... Kxd7 {Forced, as if we capture with the queen, then White has the knight fork on [b6].} 13. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5f7,Gg5e4]} (13. Nxd4 Nf6 14. Be3 Qb8 {followed by ...[Rc8], ...[Ke8], and Black consolidates slowly.}) 13... Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc7c6] With the plan of ...[Qc7]-[c6].} ({For a long time, the computer was suggesting} 13... Bc6 {over 13...Bb7 , but after probing it in greater depth, the computers increased the evaluation to White's favor.}) ({So} 13... Bc6 14. Nxf7 Qa5 {, targeting the [a4]-knight.} 15. Bd2 Qa7 16. Qg4+ Kc7 17. Qe6 d3+ 18. Be3 {, and so on.}) 14. Nxf7 {[%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8]} Qc7 {[%csl Ra4,Rg2][%cal Gc7c6]} 15. Rf2 $1 {[%cal Gf2g2] Guarding [g2], which I don't think is easy to find if White players don't have this course. :P Generally, one automatically takes on [h8].} Qc6 {[%cal Ga8a4]} 16. c3 d3 (16... dxc3 {is a mistake, as White has} 17. Ne5+ {.}) 17. Nxh8 ({If White delays one more move by} 17. Be3 {, then we can force things with} Ke8 18. Nxh8 Bxh8 {followed by ...[Qe4].}) 17... Bxh8 18. Ra2 $1 {[%cal Gb2b3] A deep idea is behind this mysterious rook move. White wants to connect their pieces and as well strengthen the knight on [a4] by [b3].} ({The direct} 18. b3 {is met by} Bxc3 {, attacking the rook on [a1], hence the rook move to [a2].}) 18... Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 19. b3 {[%csl Ga4,Gb3,Rd3]} Ne4 20. Qxd3 {White is forced to give back the exchange but gains a pawn in return.} Nxf2 21. Rxf2 Ke8 {[%csl Gb7,Gh8] Securing the king. The bishop pair compensates for the pawn loss.} 22. Bb2 (22. c4 d5 {fizzles out.}) 22... Qe4 {Thanks to our king place on [e8], this is possible as we are not afraid of [Nb6]+.} 23. Qxe4 Bxe4 {[%csl Ra4]} 24. c4 {It makes sense to connect the pieces.} Bxb2 25. Rxb2 Bc6 {[%csl Ra4]} 26. Nc3 (26. Ra2 Rb8 {targets the [b3]-pawn.} 27. Ra3 Ra8 {and White is unable to release their pieces.}) 26... Ra1+ 27. Kf2 Rc1 {[%csl Rc3]} 28. Ne2 Rh1 {[%csl Rh2]} 29. Nd4 Bb7 30. h3 Rd1 31. Ke3 h5 {Thanks to our active rook, we are doing fine in this endgame.} *

