1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Both bishops are fianchettoed now towards the d4 and e4-pawn respectively. This will be my suggestion if you would like to play the 4.f4 a6 system.} 7. Qe2 {[%cal Ge4e5]} (7. a4 {is also possible, but this option of 7.Qe2 is even more threatening, as White is now in a mood to roll out with [e5] next.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] What else? We only have one plan of carrying out the most important ...[c5] break before White starts rolling on the kingside.} 8. e5 (8. a4 {now is met by the typical} c5 {.}) 8... c5 {The only counterplay idea. If it works, it's all well and good; if not, then we are crushed.} 9. exd6 {White wins a pawn but loses the momentum to attack.} Ngf6 $1 ({Accurate. If} 9... cxd4 {, which looks natural, then White has} 10. Ne4 {. There is nothing wrong with our position, but why allow the knight into the game?}) 10. O-O (10. dxe7 Qxe7 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. O-O Rhd8 {and Black has full compensation for the pawn thanks to the razor-sharp bishops and the pressure on the [d4]-pawn. Black can next secure the king on [f8] if threatened. 12...cxd4 transposing to the text is equally possible.}) 10... cxd4 11. dxe7 Qxe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. Nxd4 Rhc8 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4] Next on the agenda is to roll the pawns by ...[b4], ...[a5], etc. Black can also jump with the knight to [c5], targeting the [d3]-bishop.} 14. f5 Kf8 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black has full compensation. We first secured our king, and then ...[b4] is coming to disturb the position of White's pieces.} *

