sible, but this option of 7.Qe2 is even more threatening, as White is now in a mood to roll out with [e5] next.}) 7... Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] What else? We only have one plan of carrying out the most important ...[c5] break before White starts rolling on the kingside.} 8. e5 (8. a4 {now is met by the typical} c5 {.}) 8... c5 {The only counterplay idea. If it works, it's all well and good; if not, then we are crushed.} 9. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Rf7][%cal Ge5e6]} ({All in, threatening e6.} 9. Be3 b4 {turns the table in the Black's favor.}) 9... cxd4 10. e6 {Play gets very interesting and complex.} f5 {Only move, as [exf7]+ followed by [Ne6]+ was a big threat.} 11. exd7+ Qxd7 {The start of a crazy and imbalanced position.} 12. Nd1 {White has got an extra piece after the complications, but thanks to our central pawn mass, we do have some counterplay. Stockfish overestimates this position for White, as once you start digging deep, the evaluations drop. That is why it is always nicer to have a human perspective.} ({After} 12. Nxb5 axb5 13. Ne6 {, we have} Kf7 {, and if 13.Bxb5 Bc6 safeguards. 14.Bc4 Bf6 followed by the ...[Nh6] setup is important to make note of. Black has safeguarded the [f7]-square thanks to the knight on [h6] and as well Black can exchange the annoying knight on [g5] anytime. If you play the Modern, you have to get used to these weird setups as most of the time, play is concrete and not based on the general setup of pieces.}) 12... e5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5] Let's go!! The juicers on [e5] and [f5] rule the game.} 13. fxe5 dxe5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf5]} 14. a4 {[%csl Rb5]} (14. O-O {allows us to stabilize with 15...Ne7 , and then ...[h6] followed by ...[e4] is a big threat since our king is safeguarded.}) 14... h6 15. Nf3 e4 {Although we don't have an immediate threat, the pawns create a mess all over the board, not allowing White to relax.} 16. axb5 Ne7 {Unpinning on the e-file and now White has to surrender one piece.} 17. bxa6 O-O (17... exd3 {would be a blunder due to} 18. axb7 Rxa1 19. b8=Q+ {.}) 18. Bc4+ Kh7 {I can understand that we have already reached a bit far, and it might not happen over the board. The reason for analyzing further is that we are still a piece down, and we ought to know the natural responses from White and how to react to them as the game is concrete.} 19. Nd2 {[%csl Rc1,Rd1,Rd2] White escapes from the piece loss, but their pieces are cramped and not in full flow.} Bd5 20. O-O Rfc8 {[%cal Gc8c2,Ge4e3] Threatening ...[e3].} 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 {I would like to stop the analysis here, claiming it as good compensation, but the position is so concrete still, so we will have to continue a bit further.} 22. c3 ({This looks logical, as the c2-pawn was attacked. The other option is to give the piece back, grabbing two pawns by} 22. Nxe4 {.}) 22... dxc3 23. Nc4 (23. bxc3 Nxc3 24. Nxc3 Rxc3 {, and Black will gain the [a6]-pawn too.}) 23... c2 {Only move.} 24. Nde3 (24. Qxc2 Qb5 25. Nde3 Bd4 {and White is suffering due to pins everywhere.}) 24... f4 {There is no stopping. We have to roll.} 25. Nxd5 (25. Nxc2 Qc6 {is the point.}) 25... Qxd5 26. Nd2 Bd4+ 27. Kh1 Be3 {Locking White's pieces again and the [e4]-pawn is also safe now. If we push ...[e3] instead of this bishop sortie, then we give White a nice blockade with a big advantage.} 28. Ra3 {[%cal Ga3e3]} Rc7 ({The other rook is arriving on d8. If} 28... Rd8 {, then} 29. Rc3 {kills the major pawn on [c2].}) 29. Re1 Rd8 {[%csl Rd2]} 30. Rxe3 {White is forced to give up something in order to protect the [d2]-knight.} fxe3 31. Qxe3 Qd3 {Finally, here we can stop our analysis claiming that Black has a balanced game. The [a6]-pawn is hanging now, and our [c2]-pawn is on the brink of promotion. Of course, it is blockaded, but this factor does restrict the white pieces to an extent, maintaining the balance.} *

