with. Apart from} 7. O-O Nd7 8. a4 {, this is one more area where we need to be really cautious.}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... b4 {is an automatic response in all the games played in this position, but it allows White to stabilize the center with a comfortable advantage after} 8. Ne2 c5 9. c3 {. The text move is in the spirit of the position, as Black has to act quickly.}) 8. dxc5 {Other moves do not make sense since the [d4]-pawn is hanging.} b4 9. Nd5 Bxd5 (9... dxc5 {is a mistake due to} 10. Ne3 Nf6 11. e5 {and White has full control.}) 10. exd5 dxc5 {So we sort of reach this position where no games are played. The analysis from here is totally from a fresh perspective.} 11. O-O Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} (11... Qxd5 {would be a big blunder due to} 12. Bb5+ {.}) 12. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5] Holding on to the [d5]-pawn.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] Black's only play is around the [d5]-pawn, so we are intending ...[Nb6] next.} 13. Qe2 {[%csl Ra6]} (13. a5 {stops ...[Nb6], but we have another plan of} Ne4 {followed by ...[Nd6], asking questions to the [c4]-bishop.}) 13... O-O 14. Bxa6 Qc7 $1 (14... Nxd5 {is not possible due to} 15. Bb7 {.}) 15. a5 Nxd5 16. Bc4 e6 $10 {And we stabilize.} *

