1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Both bishops are fianchettoed now towards the d4 and e4-pawn respectively. This will be my suggestion if you would like to play the 4.f4 a6 system.} 7. a4 $1 ({The most critical one to deal with. Apart from} 7. O-O Nd7 8. a4 {, this is one more area where we need to be really cautious.}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... b4 {is an automatic response in all the games played in this position, but it allows White to stabilize the center with a comfortable advantage after} 8. Ne2 c5 9. c3 {. The text move is in the spirit of the position, as Black has to act quickly.}) 8. dxc5 {Other moves do not make sense since the [d4]-pawn is hanging.} b4 9. Nd5 Bxd5 (9... dxc5 {is a mistake due to} 10. Ne3 Nf6 11. e5 {and White has full control.}) 10. exd5 dxc5 {So we sort of reach this position where no games are played. The analysis from here is totally from a fresh perspective.} 11. O-O Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} (11... Qxd5 {would be a big blunder due to} 12. Bb5+ {.}) 12. Bc4 {[%csl Gd5] Holding on to the [d5]-pawn.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] Black's only play is around the [d5]-pawn, so we are intending ...[Nb6] next.} 13. Qe2 {[%csl Ra6]} (13. a5 {stops ...[Nb6], but we have another plan of} Ne4 {followed by ...[Nd6], asking questions to the [c4]-bishop.}) 13... O-O 14. f5 Nb6 15. Bxa6 Qd6 $1 ({Precise, as if we capture with} 15... Nbxd5 {, then} 16. Ne5 {is now powerful. For example} Qd6 {now will be met by} 17. Bd3 {and White has a free ride with their dominating knight on [e5], an outside passed a-pawn, and a bishop pair on top of that.}) 16. fxg6 (16. Ne5 {is bad here due to} Rxa6 17. Qxa6 Qxe5 18. Qxb6 Ng4 {and White is suffering.}) 16... hxg6 17. a5 Nbxd5 18. Bb7 Ra7 19. a6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb7] Sealing the rook on [a7].} Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gd6h2]} 20. g3 e6 $13 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6] The game remains unclear... It's impossible to analyze till the end, as there are always many options for both sides. One of the ideas for Black is ...[Qb6] and ...[Rxb7], sacrificing the exchange since, anyway, the rook on [a7] is dead. Thanks to our dominating knight on [d5], we maintain good compensation.} *

