1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. f4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] Termed as the Austrian Attack – one of the critical and sensible directions as White occupies more space before developing the [g1]-knight to [f3]. The pawn mass brings White great control over the center. So we ought to hurry up with undermining it with ...[e5] or ...[c5] as soon as possible.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Preparing ...[b5] to develop the [c8]-bishop to [b7]. Once the bishop arrives on [b7], Black threatens ...[b4] targeting the central [e4]-pawn. The drawback of this pawn push is obvious: Black lacks proper development. We always need two more moves to complete castling with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], but the longer we delay ...[Nf6], the tougher it will be for us to develop it later due to the [e5] push, which becomes much more powerful when White brings their army of pieces.} 5. Nf3 b5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb5b4] The flank attack begins.} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf3,Gd3,Gc3][%cal Ge1g1] White has completed their natural developing moves bringing their pieces to perfect squares. Once White castles, they will be rolling their pawns with [e5]/[f5] marching towards Black's king. Here, Black has two ways: either to develop the knight on [b8] first to [d7], preparing ...[c5], or the bishop to [b7]. One more important point to note is that Black can only counterattack on the flank here, and the king's safety becomes an issue as we are no longer able to develop our [g8]-knight to [f6] due to the [e5] push. Having the king in the center for too long is definitely dangerous – the price to pay for the flank attack with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] Both bishops are fianchettoed now towards the d4 and e4-pawn respectively. This will be my suggestion if you would like to play the 4.f4 a6 system.} 7. a4 $1 ({The most critical one to deal with. Apart from} 7. O-O Nd7 8. a4 {, this is one more area where we need to be really cautious.}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... b4 {is an automatic response in all the games played in this position, but it allows White to stabilize the center with a comfortable advantage after} 8. Ne2 c5 9. c3 {. The text move is in the spirit of the position, as Black has to act quickly.}) 8. dxc5 {Other moves do not make sense since the [d4]-pawn is hanging.} b4 9. Nd5 Bxd5 (9... dxc5 {is a mistake due to} 10. Ne3 Nf6 11. e5 {and White has full control.}) 10. exd5 dxc5 {So we sort of reach this position where no games are played. The analysis from here is totally from a fresh perspective.} 11. Qe2 ({Another critical direction apart from the natural} 11. O-O {. White is keeping the option of long castle.}) 11... Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} 12. f5 (12. f5 {Not an easy decision to make over the board for White, as they will have to consider} Qxd5 {and be aware of a strong move} 13. g4 {, threatening [g5] & [Be4]. If one doesn't know the pawn push to [g4], I don't know how easy it is to find over the board.}) (12. Bc4 O-O 13. f5 (13. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the O-O line.}) 13... Nbd7 14. O-O {again transposes to 11.O-O .}) 12... O-O (12... Qxd5 13. g4 gxf5 14. gxf5 {followed by [Rg1] and White has a powerful attack.}) 13. Bg5 {White is quickly developing their pieces to pressurize before castling.} Qd6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf6d5] The queen is nicely placed on [d6], and next, Black will develop the [b8]-knight to [d7].} (13... Nbd7 14. O-O Nb6 15. Ne5 {and Black is having a tough time in coping with White's dominant pieces.}) (13... Nxd5 14. Rd1 {is the problem.}) 14. O-O Nxd5 {As the queen is on [d6] and not on [d8], we can capture the pawn. Of course, we have to aid it with concrete variations.} 15. Rad1 Bxb2 $1 {Biting the bullet.} 16. Qe4 {[%cal Re4a8]} Ra7 $3 {Only move, drifting away from the [e4]-[a8] diagonal.} 17. fxg6 hxg6 18. Qh4 (18. Bc4 e6 {is fine for Black.}) 18... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 19. c4 {Deflecting the bishop on [b2] as now we are forced to capture with the pawn.} bxc3 20. Bc2 {[%cal Gd1d6]} f5 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6] Restricting White's pieces and Black is planning to shift the rook to the kingside next by ...[e6].} 21. Qh6 e6 22. Qxg6+ Rg7 23. Qh6 Rh7 $10 {With a funny repetition.} *

