with. Apart from} 7. O-O Nd7 8. a4 {, this is one more area where we need to be really cautious.}) 7... c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} (7... b4 {is an automatic response in all the games played in this position, but it allows White to stabilize the center with a comfortable advantage after} 8. Ne2 c5 9. c3 {. The text move is in the spirit of the position, as Black has to act quickly.}) 8. dxc5 {Other moves do not make sense since the [d4]-pawn is hanging.} b4 9. Nd5 Bxd5 (9... dxc5 {is a mistake due to} 10. Ne3 Nf6 11. e5 {and White has full control.}) 10. exd5 dxc5 {So we sort of reach this position where no games are played. The analysis from here is totally from a fresh perspective.} 11. Qe2 ({Another critical direction apart from the natural} 11. O-O {. White is keeping the option of long castle.}) 11... Nf6 {[%csl Rd5]} 12. f5 (12. f5 {Not an easy decision to make over the board for White, as they will have to consider} Qxd5 {and be aware of a strong move} 13. g4 {, threatening [g5] & [Be4]. If one doesn't know the pawn push to [g4], I don't know how easy it is to find over the board.}) (12. Bc4 O-O 13. f5 (13. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the O-O line.}) 13... Nbd7 14. O-O {again transposes to 11.O-O .}) 12... O-O (12... Qxd5 13. g4 gxf5 14. gxf5 {followed by [Rg1] and White has a powerful attack.}) 13. Bg5 {White is quickly developing their pieces to pressurize before castling.} Qd6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf6d5] The queen is nicely placed on [d6], and next, Black will develop the [b8]-knight to [d7].} (13... Nbd7 14. O-O Nb6 15. Ne5 {and Black is having a tough time in coping with White's dominant pieces.}) (13... Nxd5 14. Rd1 {is the problem.}) 14. O-O Nxd5 {As the queen is on [d6] and not on [d8], we can capture the pawn. Of course, we have to aid it with concrete variations.} 15. Rad1 Bxb2 $1 {Biting the bullet.} 16. fxg6 ({The direct} 16. c4 {would be a mistake due to the} Bd4+ 17. Nxd4 Nc3 {trick.}) 16... hxg6 17. c4 bxc3 ({Now} 17... Bd4+ {is another story compared to the line without the inclusion of [fxg6] and ...[hxg6].} 18. Nxd4 Nc3 19. Qf3 Nxd1 20. Nf5 {, and it looks dangerous for Black with all the white pieces pouncing. The computer defends it eventually, but I would refrain from this crazy line.}) 18. Bxg6 {The craziness starts.} fxg6 19. Qe4 {[%csl Rd5,Rg6][%cal Rd1d6]} Rf5 20. g4 c2 21. gxf5 (21. Qxc2 Rxf3 22. Rxf3 Bg7 {is better for Black.}) 21... cxd1=Q 22. Rxd1 gxf5 23. Qxf5 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6d4] We have to connect our pieces to aid the king, who is burning under fire.} 24. Rxd5 Nd4 $1 25. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 26. Kg2 Rf8 $10 {The dust has finally settled with an equal endgame.} *

