 at the position over the board without any computer, then it looks complex to the human eye. Once you switch on the engine, you get demotivated as comp gives 0.48-0.60. That's where practical play comes into the role. No one will be assisted by computers while playing the game, and one cannot play precise moves all the time. This is such a position where only precision increases White's advantage, and it is not easy even for a very strong player to find them all. I agree that the white pieces look good objectively, but when it comes to practical play, the position is double-edged. Also, scientifically, once we keep analyzing the evaluation drops, but it's not our job to analyze everything till death with high-end comp. Our job is to play chess in practical terms, and in that sense, all three results are possible.} 16. Bh4 g5 17. Bg3 Qxd5 {White has given up some pawns, and concrete play is required from their side.} 18. Bc4 Qxf5 {One more pawn in the bag.} 19. O-O {[%cal Gf1f5]} Qg4 20. b3 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4][%cal Ge2e7] Supporting the bishop on [c4] and now White can capture the [e7]-pawn.} e6 21. Rd6 Qh5 {[%cal Gg5g4]} 22. Rxa6 Rxa6 23. Bxa6 Nd5 $13 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5c3,Gg5g4] The position is unclear. The knight on [d5] is dominant, which creates huge play.} *

