 at the position over the board without any computer, then it looks complex to the human eye. Once you switch on the engine, you get demotivated as comp gives 0.48-0.60. That's where practical play comes into the role. No one will be assisted by computers while playing the game, and one cannot play precise moves all the time. This is such a position where only precision increases White's advantage, and it is not easy even for a very strong player to find them all. I agree that the white pieces look good objectively, but when it comes to practical play, the position is double-edged. Also, scientifically, once we keep analyzing the evaluation drops, but it's not our job to analyze everything till death with high-end comp. Our job is to play chess in practical terms, and in that sense, all three results are possible.} 16. Bc1 g5 {[%csl Rc1,Rd3,Rf5,Gg5,Gh6] Blunting both bishops.} 17. O-O Qxd5 {Once again biting the bullet.} 18. Bxa6 Qxf5 19. Qb5 {[%cal Ga6b7,Gb5a5] The idea is [Bb7].} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d6,Ge8c7] Only move, and now the incoming line is more or less forced.} 20. Nxg5 Qg6 {[%cal Gg6a6]} 21. Bb7 Nd6 22. Rxd6 Qxd6 23. Bxa8 Rxa8 24. Nxf7 Bd4+ 25. Kh1 Qa6 {[%cal Ga6f1]} 26. Nxh6+ Kh8 27. Qxa6 Rxa6 {[%cal Ga6a5] Black's active pieces compensate for the pawn loss.} *

