1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bf4 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gf4h6] This setup gives off some London System vibes – by placing the bishop on [f4], White firmly controls the [e5]-square, making it difficult for Black to achieve the crucial ...[e5] breakthrough. However, this setup comes with a trade-off: another dynamic break becomes even more effective, ...[c5]! With the bishop on [e3], executing ...[c5] wouldn't be as easy, but now that it's on [f4], Black should look to exploit this nuance and strike in the center at the right moment!} Nc6 {We have already analyzed this exact position through a different move order.} *

