1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bf4 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gf4h6] This setup gives off some London System vibes – by placing the bishop on [f4], White firmly controls the [e5]-square, making it difficult for Black to achieve the crucial ...[e5] breakthrough. However, this setup comes with a trade-off: another dynamic break becomes even more effective, ...[c5]! With the bishop on [e3], executing ...[c5] wouldn't be as easy, but now that it's on [f4], Black should look to exploit this nuance and strike in the center at the right moment!} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd8a5] Another way to tackle this position.} 6. Qd2 c5 $1 7. d5 {[%cal Gg7a1] White releases the tension, and this, in turn, activates our [g7]-bishop.} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} (7... a6 8. a4 Qa5 {followed by ...[Qb4] is also an interesting plan.}) 8. Rb1 (8. Qc1 {also leads to} e6 {.}) 8... e6 {[%csl Rd5]} 9. Be2 (9. h3 exd5 10. exd5 Bf5 {and Black is doing well with ...[Nbd7] next.}) (9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Qxd6 {hands Black the initiative. For example, after} Nc6 11. Be2 Nh5 12. O-O Rad8 13. Qc7 Nxf4 14. Qxf4 Nb4 {, Black is getting back the pawn with interest.}) 9... exd5 10. exd5 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4e2] This is one of the typical ideas in these kinds of positions to exchange the bishop for the [f3]-knight in order to seal our [b8]-knight on [e5] and restrict White's pieces. We lack space, and hence, these kinds of exchanges support us in neutralizing our opponents' forces.} 11. O-O Nbd7 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Ne5 {[%csl Rf3] The knight has arrived.} 14. Be2 a6 {[%csl Rb5] In the future, we will expand with ...[b5].} 15. a4 {It makes sense to get rid of ...[b5] forever.} Rfe8 $10 {[%cal Gb6a5,Ge8e7,Ga8e8] Black's position is solid. We can double the rooks on the e-file, place our queen on [a5], and so on. White has no proper improvement. The game is equal.} *

