1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bf4 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gf4h6] This setup gives off some London System vibes – by placing the bishop on [f4], White firmly controls the [e5]-square, making it difficult for Black to achieve the crucial ...[e5] breakthrough. However, this setup comes with a trade-off: another dynamic break becomes even more effective, ...[c5]! With the bishop on [e3], executing ...[c5] wouldn't be as easy, but now that it's on [f4], Black should look to exploit this nuance and strike in the center at the right moment!} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd8a5] Another way to tackle this position.} 6. Qd2 c5 $1 7. dxc5 dxc5 {The exchange of queens is inevitable.} 8. O-O-O Qxd2+ 9. Nxd2 {[%cal Gf2f3]} (9. Rxd2 Nc6 10. Bb5 Nd4 {with a good game.}) 9... Ng4 {[%csl Rf2] White was planning to strengthen with [f3], so we ought to act quickly to avoid an unpleasant endgame.} 10. Bg3 Bd4 {[%csl Rf2]} 11. Nd5 (11. f3 Ne3 {is the problem.}) 11... Bxf2 12. Nxe7+ Kg7 13. Bd6 {[%cal Gd6f8]} Be6 14. Nd5 Rd8 {[%csl Rd6]} 15. Nc7 {Our rook on [a8] is trapped; meanwhile, White's rook on [d1] is also trapped.} Ne3 {[%csl Rd1]} (15... Rxd6 {would run into} 16. Ne8+ {.}) 16. Be5+ Kg8 17. Nxa8 Nc6 {[%csl Ra8,Rd1,Re5] So many hanging pieces in White's camp.} 18. Bf4 Nxd1 19. Kxd1 Rxa8 20. c3 Bh4 $10 {The dust has settled with an equal endgame.} *

