1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bg5 $5 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gg5h6] This is rarely played in top-level games, but it looks very interesting. White's plan is [Qd2] and [Bh6], and at the same time, with the bishop on [g5], White is pressuring the knight on [f6]. Also, this bishop move provokes ...[h6], which will then become a target.} O-O 6. Qd2 {[%cal Gg5h6]} d5 $1 (6... c5 {unfortunately does not work here due to the presence of the white bishop on [g5].} 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. e5 {and the [e7]-pawn hangs.}) 7. exd5 (7. Bd3 {leads to} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nc6 9. c3 Bf5 {and Black effortlessly equalizes.}) 7... Nxd5 8. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 {As we have already castled short, we have to take steps to stop White's push to [h5] instantly.} 9. Bc4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 c5 $1 {The center has to be crushed.} 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 $132 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3] Black is doing well with ...[Bxf3] coming.} *

