1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. h3 O-O 6. Bd3 {A possible option. White strengthens the pawn on [e4] by placing the bishop on [d3].} (6. Be3 d5 {would transpose.}) 6... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] Enabling ...[e5].} 7. O-O e5 8. d5 ({If White maintains the tension by} 8. Be3 {, then} exd4 9. Nxd4 d5 {equalizes.}) 8... Ne7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc7c6] Black is able to cruise through the [d5]-pawn instantly by ...[c6].} 9. Be3 c6 (9... Ne8 {is another plan, aiming for...[f5].}) 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Qd2 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd6d5] Followed by ...[Bb7], ...[d5], etc., and Black is doing well.} *

