1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. h3 O-O 6. Bd3 {A possible option. White strengthens the pawn on [e4] by placing the bishop on [d3].} (6. Be3 d5 {would transpose.}) 6... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] Enabling ...[e5].} 7. O-O e5 8. dxe5 ({White releases the tension. Black should be fine in this symmetrical structure. If White maintains the tension by} 8. Be3 {, then} exd4 9. Nxd4 d5 {equalizes.}) 8... dxe5 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gc8e6,Gf8d8] One of Black's plans is ...[Qe7], ...[Rd8], ...[Be6]. Maybe also insert ...[h6] in between to stop [Bg5] and [Nd5] ideas from White.} 9. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8]} h6 $1 {[%csl Rg5]} (9... Qe7 {now is slightly inaccurate due to the} 10. Bg5 {pin.} Be6 11. Bxe6 Qxe6 12. Nd5 {, and there is some pressure.}) 10. a4 (10. Qe2 {with the intention of [Rd1] is met by} Nd4 {.}) 10... b6 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8b7]} (10... Qe7 {is also possible, but then we have to deal with} 11. Nd5 {jumps.}) ({First} 10... b6 {with the intent of finachettoing the bishop to [b7] and then ...[Qe7] makes sense, as we are then well-equipped for [Nd5] jumps.}) 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Rd1 (12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Qc8 {looks fine, as we can then unpin our knight.}) 12... Qe7 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Na5 $10 {Black has untangled the cramped pieces.} *

