1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. h3 O-O 6. Bd3 {A possible option. White strengthens the pawn on [e4] by placing the bishop on [d3].} (6. Be3 d5 {would transpose.}) 6... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] Enabling ...[e5].} 7. d5 Nb4 {[%csl Rd3]} 8. Be2 Na6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga6c5] Very subtle as now if White captures on [a6], then Black can undermine the [d5]-pawn not only by ...[e6] but also ...[c6].} 9. Bxa6 (9. Be3 Nc5 10. e5 Nfd7 {is fine for Black.}) 9... bxa6 10. O-O Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gb7h1] Next, Black will poke the [d5]-pawn with ...[c6] & ...[e6].} 11. Be3 c6 12. Qd3 cxd5 13. exd5 e6 14. dxe6 fxe6 $132 {[%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1] The two bishops are wide open.} *

