1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... Nf6 5. h3 O-O 6. Bd3 {A possible option. White strengthens the pawn on [e4] by placing the bishop on [d3].} (6. Be3 d5 {would transpose.}) 6... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] Enabling ...[e5].} 7. Bg5 e5 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. dxe5 (8. d5 Nd4 {or 8...Ne7 followed by ...[c6] is good for Black.}) 8... dxe5 9. Bc4 Qxd1+ $1 ({Precise. After} 9... h6 {first, then} 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd5 {loses the [c7]-pawn.}) 10. Rxd1 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd5 Bd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd8] Though Black has defended the [c7]-pawn, there is now some pressure due to the annoying knight on [d5].} 13. O-O {White is going to double the rooks on the d-file.} Kg7 14. Rd2 f5 {Aiming for active play to change the nature of the position.} 15. Nc3 Bf6 16. Re1 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5] Protecting the [e4]-pawn, so that White can hop on to the [d5]-square with the [c3]-knight.} Rb8 $10 (16... Rb8 {Prophylaxis against the Nd5 jump – now} 17. Nd5 {is met by} fxe4 {and} 18. Nxc7 {no longer attacks the rook on [a8]. White must continue with 18.Rxe4 , but then 18...Bf5 follows.}) *

