1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 5. a4 {[%csl Rb5] White stops ...[b5].} (5. Be2 Nf6 6. O-O O-O {transposes to the Tricky Systems chapter, and 5.Be3 Nf6 transposes to the 4.Be3 line.}) 5... Nf6 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] This is a useful move, aiming to prevent ...[Ng4] when White plays [Be3], while also sometimes stopping ...[Bg4] and the resulting pin.} (6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {would transpose.}) 6... O-O 7. Be3 {[%csl Ge3,Rg4] The bishop feels safe now without having to worry about ...[Ng4] jumps.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 8. Be2 e5 $1 {The whole idea of ...[Nc6].} 9. d5 Ne7 {We reach a structure reminiscent of the King's Indian, with slight differences in pawn placements. However, the core essence remains unchanged – Black must orchestrate play on the kingside with ...[f5], while White looks to launch a queenside offensive.} 10. Nd2 {[%cal Gd1h5] White keeps an eye on ...[Nh5] ideas.} Bd7 ({The direct} 10... Ne8 {is met by} 11. a5 f5 12. f3 Nf6 13. g4 {and White gets a better position. With the text move, Black keeps both the option of ...[Ne8] followed by ...[f5], or ...[c6] based on White's setup.}) 11. O-O Ne8 {Now that White has castled kingside, we can plan for ...[f5] without having to be concerned about [f3] and [g4] ideas challenging our attack.} 12. a5 f5 13. f3 Nf6 14. Na4 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5g3]} 15. c4 Nc8 $13 {The knight firmly supports the [d6]-pawn against White's [c5] push while also clearing the way for the queen on [d8]. Black has several ideas, such as ...[Bf6] followed by ...[Bg5] or ...[Bh4], repositioning the bishop to more active squares. Additionally, the knight can jump to [f4] or even [g3], creating tactical opportunities and increasing Black's dynamic potential.} *

