1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] A logical developing move, gaining control over the [d5]-square. Next, White will decide where to place the other pieces.} d6 4. Nf3 {Again, Black has two options – either developing the knight first or playing ...[a6]. While there are some minor differences, most lines eventually transpose to earlier chapters.} ({That's why I've chosen to cover} 4. Nf3 {in the final chapter. In many variations, I've also provided an additional alternative beyond simply transposing, highlighting the flexible nature of the Modern Defense and its various setup possibilities.}) 4... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 5. a4 {[%csl Rb5] White stops ...[b5].} (5. Be2 Nf6 6. O-O O-O {transposes to the Tricky Systems chapter, and 5.Be3 Nf6 transposes to the 4.Be3 line.}) 5... Nf6 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4] This is a useful move, aiming to prevent ...[Ng4] when White plays [Be3], while also sometimes stopping ...[Bg4] and the resulting pin.} (6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {would transpose.}) 6... O-O 7. Be3 {[%csl Ge3,Rg4] The bishop feels safe now without having to worry about ...[Ng4] jumps.} b6 $5 {[%csl Ga4,Ga6,Re4][%cal Gc8b7] This plan is only possible when the moves ...[a6] and [a4] are included.} 8. e5 {This is the true test of the position, as White unleashes firepower.} Nfd7 {[%csl Re5]} 9. e6 $5 {Black is forced to capture, which weakens the [g6]-square, making it a target for [h4]-[h5]. Additionally, the bishop on [c8] remains locked in. Now, let's explore how to navigate this situation.} fxe6 10. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] With the h-pawn charging forward, the position appears dangerous, but the essence of the Modern Defense lies in skillfully countering such aggression.} Nf6 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gf6h5] A logical move to stop [h5].} 11. h5 {Regardless, White is pushing forward.} Nxh5 {A complex position arises with no known games, but since it is highly concrete and requires precise play, we must delve deeper.} 12. Ng5 {[%cal Gh1h7]} ({White brings in all their pieces to launch a mating attack on our king, but it's not that simple – we have defensive resources.} 12. Bd3 Qe8 {leads to the same story.}) 12... h6 {At this point, White has multiple ways to launch an offensive.} 13. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3g6]} Qe8 {[%cal Ge8g6] A crucial defensive move, reinforcing [g6].} 14. Nh7 $1 {White is mobilizing every piece to penetrate the kingside defenses.} Rf5 $1 {Sacrificing the exchange to barricade the bishop on [d3], limiting its influence.} 15. g4 Kxh7 16. gxh5 g5 $132 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7] White's attack comes to a halt.} *

