k on our king, but it's not that simple – we have defensive resources.} 12. Bd3 Qe8 {leads to the same story.}) 12... h6 {At this point, White has multiple ways to launch an offensive.} 13. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Gd3g6] A true trial for Black. The position appears highly dangerous, yet this is the essence of the Modern Defense – wild, double-edged play.} Qe8 {[%cal Ge8g6] True to its role, the queen comes to the rescue, shielding her majesty. :} 14. Nxe6 {The chaos unfolds from this point.} Bxe6 15. Qe4 {[%cal Ge4e6,Ge4a8]} Nc6 16. Qxe6+ Qf7 17. Bc4 (17. Qxf7+ Kxf7 18. Bc4+ e6 {and Black's king is active, which can't be a bad thing in an endgame. Following} 19. d5 Bxc3+ 20. bxc3 Ne5 21. dxe6+ Ke7 22. Bd5 c6 23. Bb3 Nf4 {, the knights successfully fight the bishop pair.}) 17... Qxe6 18. Bxe6+ Kh7 19. Bd5 {[%cal Gd5a8] The line continues to unfold as the battle intensifies.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 20. Bxa8 Nxc2+ 21. Kd2 Nxa1 {[%csl Ra8]} 22. Bd5 c5 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Re3][%cal Gc5d4] The entire sequence is justified by this incredible move. Without it, we would lose the knight on [a1]. Once again, the only move.} 23. dxc5 dxc5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gd8d2]} 24. Ba2 (24. Rxa1 Rd8 {is the point.}) 24... Rd8+ 25. Kc1 b5 $10 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gb4b3] Followed by ...[b4]-[b3] and finally the [a1]-knight escapes.} *

