{Find the best move for Black to create counterplay.} 9... b5 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb5b4] Now is the time for counterplay before White consolidates with [Bd3]. Once White plays [Bd3], their position becomes more solid, and it becomes harder for Black to create immediate threats. Therefore, Black should seize the moment to challenge White's center or expand on the queenside while White is still in the development phase.} 10. Nxb5 (10. Bxb5 Nxe4 {is the problem.}) 10... Qxd2 11. Nxd2 Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} 12. d5 a6 13. Nc3 Ng4 14. Bg1 f5 {[%csl Rc3,Rd5,Re4][%cal Gg7c3,Gb7h1] Black gains more than sufficient counterplay for the pawn loss. White's center is completely dismantled, and the resulting imbalance provides Black with significant dynamic chances. Despite the temporary material deficit, Black's active pieces create overwhelming pressure. White's central structure collapses, leaving Black in full control of the key squares and open lines.} *

