{Black to play!} 10... b6 $1 {[%csl Ra5] Black is planning to meet the [a5] push with ...[b5] and that is why the ...[b6] plan is important. White has a couple of options here. Of course, it is impossible to analyze all of them, so let's check a logical continuation.} 11. a5 b5 12. Na2 {[%cal Gc2c4] An interesting plan in order to open up the queenside.} c5 ({Better than} 12... c6 {as now if White plays} 13. b4 {, we can close with c4 .}) 13. dxc6 Nxc6 14. Bb6 Qe7 15. c4 bxc4 16. Nxc4 Nd4 $1 {Black needs to act quickly to gain counterplay. Otherwise, our position will deteriorate.} 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Nb6 Ra7 $1 (18... Rb8 {loses contact over the [a6]-pawn after} 19. Nb4 {.}) 19. Nb4 Bb7 $132 {[%csl Re4] Black is holding on. The [e4]-pawn is hanging.} *

