{Black to play!} 15... Ra4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a3,Gg7a1] The bishop on [a3] is cornered.} 16. O-O-O (16. O-O {is worse for White after} Rxa3 17. bxa3 Bxa1 18. Rxa1 Rc8 {and White's pawns are lonely and vulnerable, along with the pressure on the c-file. Though on paper White has an extra pawn, their rook is tied down to protect the [a2]-pawn, and the doubled a-pawns and the c-file give Black a slightly better position.}) 16... Rc8 17. f4 (17. Kb1 {is met by a nice shot} Rxa3 18. bxa3 Na4 {, and Black is on top since ...[Nc3] is unavoidable.}) 17... Bd4 {[%csl Re3]} (17... Bxa2 {is also possible.} 18. Bxe7 Bc4 {with counterplay.}) 18. Rhe1 a6 $1 {[%csl Rb5] White was planning [Bb5], so it is important to prevent it. Next on the agenda is ...[Bxa2].} 19. f5 Rxa3 $1 20. bxa3 Bxa2 {[%cal Gb6a4] Followed by ...[Na4] and Black has great compensation for the exchange loss. White's king is also exposed, so at some point, they need to give up the exchange, which balances the game.} *

