{One of the best ways to understand an opening deeply is by studying well-played games where key ideas and plans are demonstrated in action. In this chapter, we will explore a selection of model games that highlight the essential strategic and tactical themes of the Modern Defense. These games will help you grasp typical middlegame plans and piece placements that arise frequently in practical play. As you go through these games, try to understand the reasoning behind each move rather than just memorizing them. Pay special attention to recurring patterns, as they will help you navigate similar positions with confidence. P.S. Ignore the move orders, as we often reach these setups through different sequences. The structure is more important!} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Defense"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anton Smirnov – Magnus Carlsen, Chennai 2022"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B08"]
[PlyCount "80"]
[GameId "2159115901568200"]

1. e4 Nc6 {Magnus doing Magnus things. :} (1... g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. h3 O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6 {, we can reach the game by this move order through our repotire. (7...b5 is the best move. )}) 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 5. h3 Bg7 6. Be3 O-O 7. Qd2 a6 {We get to a Modern Defense kind of position through 1...Nc6 . It's interesting to see how Magnus chose a complex line, which practically unsettled the opponent. If you switch on the computer, it will scream as better for White, but it's not entirely the case. Once we dig deeper, the evaluation drops, and also, during the game, it is impossible to choose the best moves among various options.} 8. Bd3 (8. Bh6 b5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. a3 {, stopping...[b4] is sensible.} e5 {challenges the center, which is one of the main ideas behind placing the knight on [c6].} 11. O-O-O exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bb7 14. f3 {(14.g4 c5 15.Qe3 h6 and next ...[b4] is on the cards. )} Qe7 {, now that the [e4]-pawn is well strengthened, we cannot kick away the [d4]-queen by ...[c5], as we drop the [d6]-pawn.} 15. g4 Qe5 16. Qd2 Rad8 {and Black is doing fine with ...[d5], ...[c5], and ...[b4] ideas floating in the air.}) (8. d5 {is the critical continuation.} Na7 $5 {This is the favorite square of Magnus. We will see one more game against Solak where he places his knight on [a7], which is one of the advantages of having the pawn on [a6]. Black is preparing ...[Nb5] to challenge the [c3]-knight, which is protecting the key central [e4]-pawn. (8...Nb8 9.Bh6 (9.O-O-O b5 10.Bh6 c5 (10...b4 11.Bxg7 Kxg7 12.Ne2 and we cannot capture on [e4] due to [Qxb4]. ) 11.Bxg7 Kxg7 12.g4 Nbd7 13.Qe3 Nb6 ∞ . Computers overestimate this position as 0.40, but I don't trust it as the position is not at all clear. And this is where Magnus thrives. Black has many ideas like ...[e5] or ...[e6]. ) 9...b5 10.h4 , White is bringing all his forces to pierce the kingside. 10...b4 11.Ne2 Nxe4 12.Qe3 Nf6 13.Bxg7 Kxg7 14.h5 Nxd5 15.Qd2 e6 and now a crazy line is coming. : 16.hxg6 hxg6 17.Qh6+ Kf6 , the king is indeed the strongest piece. : 18.Qh4+ Kg7 19.Qh7+ Kf6 20.O-O-O Ke7 21.Rxd5 exd5 22.Nf4 Bf5 and the games goes on... )} 9. Bd3 {(9.a4 stops...[Nb5]. 9...c6 , undermining the [d5]-pawn. 10.h4 cxd5 11.exd5 h5 ∞ and Black stops the h-pawn's march totally. Next, ...[e6] to get rid of the [d5]-pawn and simultaneously activating the bishop on [c8] is on the list. )} c6 ({The direct} 9... Nb5 {is met by} 10. Ne2 {and [c4].}) 10. a4 b5 $1 {to muddy the waters.} 11. Bh6 {(11.axb5 Nxb5 12.Nxb5 (12.Ne2 Bb7 13.c4 Nc7 , Black's main idea is now to dissolve the central [d5]-pawn, which is limiting the scope of his pieces. 14.O-O cxd5 15.exd5 e6 16.Qb4 Qb8! 17.Qxd6 exd5 18.c5 Ne6 ∞ and Black has coordinated his pieces. ) 12...cxb5 13.O-O e6 and Black frees his position as White is not able to contain the [d5]-pawn right there. )} b4 12. Ne2 cxd5 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. exd5 Qa5 {⇆ and the position is double-edged. Not an easy game, especially for White, as he is losing his central pawn on [d5]. He needs to play concretely to compensate it by [h4]-[h5], and it is not clear if it works effectively.}) 8... e5 $1 {And now Black has effortlessly neutralised White's control over the center.} 9. dxe5 (9. d5 Ne7 10. O-O (10. a4 Bd7 {so that after [c6] and [dxc6], Black has the option of [Bxc6] pressurizing the [e4]-pawn.}) 10... Nh5 {, now ...[f5] is coming with full force:} 11. g4 f5 $3 12. exf5 gxf5 13. gxh5 f4 {⩱ .}) 9... Nxe5 {In some instances, Black takes with the knight on [e5] so that he will not end up with a bad knight on [c6]. But here, the difference is that White can castle long and roll his pawns with [f3], [g4], and [h4].} ({So perhaps} 9... dxe5 {was a better capture:} 10. O-O-O b5 {.}) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. O-O-O (11. f3 Be6 12. g4 b5 13. h4 {is a better move order than in the game.} h5 14. O-O-O {is the best plan for White, though it remains complex.}) 11... b5 12. g4 c6 13. f3 Be6 14. h4 Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Gb5b4]} 15. a3 Rfb8 (15... b4 16. Nb1 c5 17. h5) (15... h5 16. Bc5 Rab8 $3 {is an amazing idea suggested by comp, to ignore the [f8]-rook, as taking it would only help Black to create a strong attack due to the absence of White's dark-squared bishop:} 17. Bxf8 Bxf8 {∓ .}) 16. Bc5 {[%csl Rb4] White wants to prevent ...[b4], but now Black can sabotage White's roll on the kingside.} (16. h5 {, White has to ignore the queenside and continue his roll on the kingside.} b4 17. Nb1 c5 18. hxg6 c4 {, perhaps Smirnov was not sure about this position and indeed it does look a bit scary on the queenside:} 19. gxh7+ Kh8 20. axb4 Rxb4 21. Be2 {.}) 16... h5 $1 17. Bd6 Rb7 18. Kb1 Rd8 {[%csl Rd6]} 19. Bb4 Qc7 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc6c5]} 20. Ne2 {[%cal Gb4a5,Ga5d8]} Rd7 21. Bc5 hxg4 22. Ng3 gxf3 {Practically, the best move.} 23. h5 Qd8 {Shifting the queen to the kingside.} 24. hxg6 fxg6 25. Qg5 (25. Qe3 a5 26. Qxf3 Bg4) 25... Kf7 (25... Bf7 26. Qe3) 26. Nf5 $4 (26. Qe3 {is the best resistance.} a5 27. Rdf1 Bg4 28. Rfg1 {and the game continues..}) 26... Nxe4 27. Nh6+ Bxh6 28. Qxh6 Bf5 29. Ka2 Qg8 ({Again, practically the best, but} 29... Kf6 $3 30. Qh4+ Ke6 {-+ .}) 30. Bxe4 Bxe4 31. Rde1 Kf6+ 32. b3 Rh7 33. Qe3 Rxh1 34. Rxh1 Qd5 35. Kb2 Rd7 36. Rh8 Bf5 37. Rf8+ Rf7 38. Re8 Qe4 39. Qd2 Kg7 40. Bf2 Qe2 {A very nice game by Magnus, who played almost perfect chess, posing a lot of practical questions to the opponent.} 0-1

