1. e4 d6 2. d4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nf3 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 Nc6 8. d5 Na7 ({Magnus makes use of the pawn on a6 and plans to place the knight without giving any positional concession to the opponent. For instance, our move} 8... Ne5 {doubles the pawn on the e-file.}) (8... Ne5 {is the direction we delve into in the theoretical section.}) 9. h3 $6 (9. a4 $1 {Shutting the knight down is the problem; otherwise, this idea of ...[Na7] would be good. Additionally, it also prevents one of the main ideas of ...[b5].} e6 10. Be3 exd5 11. exd5 {⩲ and White is slightly better here due to Black's misplaced knight on [a7].}) 9... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1,Gb5b4,Gc7c6,Ge7e6]} 10. Bf1 Bb7 11. a4 b4 12. Na2 a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4]} 13. c4 $6 {[%cal Gg7a1]} ({This is a bad positional decision as now the g7-bishop has a free range –} 13. c3 c5 {.}) 13... e6 14. Bg5 h6 15. Be3 Re8 {[%cal Ge8e4]} (15... Nxe4 $2 16. Bxa7 Rxa7 17. Rxe4 Bxb2 18. Rb1) 16. Bd3 exd5 17. exd5 c6 {Once Black gets rid of the [d5]-pawn, all his pieces will spring into action.} 18. dxc6 Nxc6 19. Nc1 Nd7 {[%cal Gg7a1] White's position has completely collapsed.} 20. Qc2 Qf6 21. Rb1 Nce5 22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Be2 d5 24. cxd5 Bxd5 25. Nb3 Rac8 26. Nc5 Bf8 27. Rbc1 Bxc5 28. Bxc5 Qg5 29. g3 Nd7 30. h4 Qd8 31. Bb5 Rxe1+ 32. Rxe1 Rxc5 33. Qd2 h5 34. Qd4 Qf6 35. Qe3 Bc6 36. Qe8+ Nf8 37. Qc8 Rc2 38. Bxc6 Qxf2+ 39. Kh1 Qxe1# {Just one bad decision of allowing ...[b5] in the opening and White never got back into the game.} 0-1

