{I chose this game primarily because it was played between two stalwarts of the game.} 1. e4 d6 (1... g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. f4 Nf6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 c5 {is our prescribed move order in the theoritical section.}) 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 c5 7. dxc5 Qa5 {[%cal Ra5e1,Gf6e4]} 8. O-O Qxc5+ 9. Kh1 Nc6 (9... a6 {is the direction that I recommend:} 10. a4 b6 {.}) 10. Nd2 $6 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd2b3]} (10. Qe1 {is the best move with the idea of [Bd3] and [Be3], coordinating the pieces and also hitting the queen on [c5].}) (10. Bd3 {is human but is met by a strong pawn thrust:} b5 11. Nxb5 Nxe4 12. Nc7 Nf2+ 13. Rxf2 Rb8 $3 (13... Qxf2 14. Nxa8 {+-}) 14. Re2 Nb4 {, trapping the knight on [c7].} 15. Rxe7 Bf6 16. Be3 Qa5 17. Ne6 Bxe6 18. Rxa7 Qd5 {∞ and all the black pieces are attacking something in White's camp.}) 10... a5 $1 {Anticipating [Nb3] from White so that after moving the queen from [c5], Black can harass the [b3]-knight by ...[a4].} 11. a4 Nb4 {Using the havoc created around the [b4]-square.} 12. Nb3 Qb6 13. g4 $4 {A blunder from Fischer. A rare happening that Fischer missed a simple tactical idea...} (13. Nd2 {is one of the possible moves for White.} Qc7 {and the game continues.}) 13... Bxg4 $1 14. Bxg4 Nxg4 15. Qxg4 Nxc2 {[%csl Ra1,Rb3][%cal Gb6b3,Gc2a1]} 16. Nb5 Nxa1 17. Nxa1 Qc6 $19 {[%cal Gc6h1] Black is simply winning due to White's misplaced pieces and vulnerable pawns.} 18. f5 Qc4 {[%cal Gc4f1,Gb4a4,Gc4a4]} 19. Qf3 Qxa4 20. Nc7 Qxa1 21. Nd5 Rae8 22. Bg5 Qxb2 23. Bxe7 Be5 24. Rf2 Qc1+ 25. Rf1 Qh6 26. h3 gxf5 27. Bxf8 Rxf8 28. Ne7+ Kh8 29. Nxf5 Qe6 30. Rg1 a4 31. Rg4 Qb3 32. Qf1 a3 33. Rg3 Qxg3 {It is rare to see Fischer losing like this – one of the reasons why I was intrigued by this game.} 0-1

