{The Hippopotamus Defense is a flexible and resilient setup that can be used against almost any opening. It prioritizes flexible pawn structure like a fotress (e6, [d6], [g6], [b6], [a6], [h6], and so on) , solid piece development (bishops to [g7] and [b7], knights to [e7] and [d7]) and follows a hypermodern approach where Black does not immediately contest the center but instead waits for White to overextend before striking back. The reason I analyzed some model games dedicated to the Hippo structure is that it can also arise from our Modern Defense. While the theory section does not contain many recommendations to adopt the Hippo setup, there are certain directions where one can experiment with it. Objectively, it may not be entirely sound, but practically, it is a viable and playable system, as demonstrated in these games. I wanted to present these games out of curiosity, to explore a new structure that can arise from the Modern and highlight its practical value, even if engines assess it as significantly better for White. Before diving into the games, it is worth looking at the origins of the Hippopotamus Defense. The system gained popularity after Boris Spassky employed it twice in his 1966 World Championship match against Tigran Petrosian, which we will examine as well. However, credit for introducing the setup goes to Slovak IM Maximilian Ujtelky, who first brought it to the board in 1964, according to various sources. Over the years, several strong players have experimented with the Hippopotamus, including Tony Miles, Gata Kamsky, Luke McShane, and Hikaru Nakamura, among others. Despite being considered strategically dubious by engines, it remains a fascinating and practical choice in human play, often leading to rich and unbalanced positions. Now, let's check some games!} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Modern Defense"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tigran Petrosian – Boris Spassky, Moscow (12) 1966"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "A42"]
[PlyCount "77"]
[GameId "2159115901654221"]

1. Nf3 g6 2. c4 Bg7 3. d4 d6 4. Nc3 Nd7 5. e4 e6 {Seeing the Hippopotamus Defense in a World Championship match is truly a rare and bold choice. It speaks volumes about Spassky's creativity and fighting spirit. Given that he has just passed away, revisiting his daring games feels like a fitting tribute to his legacy.} 6. Be2 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gg8e7] This is the Hippo setup – the bishop to [b7] and the knight to [e7].} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Be3 Ne7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Accomplishing the setup and next, Black will castle.} 9. Qc2 {It also makes a lot of sense to put the rooks on [d1] and [e1] before striking, but it does give Black some time to consolidate. So perhaps it was better to advance the d-pawn right now.} (9. d5 $1 {has to be played gaining space, changing the character of the game, before Black consolidates further. Somehow, in many of the games in this structure, White hesitates to strike immediately and shuffles the pieces instead, losing quite some momentum. Strike while the iron is hot is a good theory to be applied here. But on the other hand, I understand it is a responsible decision, and perhaps White was not ready, given an abundance of choices for improving his pieces to nice squares.} e5 10. b4 {and White marches ahead on the queenside. At the right time, White will chip in with the [c5] breakthrough.} a5 {, Black tries to contain the queenside by this challenge.} 11. bxa5 Rxa5 12. a4 {and White is the one who is steering the wheel.} O-O 13. Nd2 Nc5 14. Nb3 Ra8 15. a5 Bc8 16. Qc2 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 bxa5 18. c5 dxc5 19. Na4 {± .}) 9... h6 10. Rad1 {Though it looks logical, in hindsight, when White expands with [b4] after the [d5] and ...[e5] inclusion, the rook will be useful on [a1] in containing Black's idea of ...[a5].} O-O 11. d5 e5 12. Qc1 (12. Qd2 Kh7 13. g4 {is the computer's choice, restricting Black's ...[f5], but the game remains complex.} Rh8 {is a mysterious rook move in stabilizing the [h6]-pawn. The Hipppo structure is all about shuffles and maneuvers.} 14. Kh1 Bc8 {, repositioning the bishop as the [d5]-pawn simply cuts it down on [b7];} 15. g5 Qf8 {∞ .}) 12... Kh7 {[%csl Gh6,Gh7]} 13. g3 {Again, 13.g4 is required to stop ...[f5] from Black. This is a typical move thanks to the fact that the black bishop is on [b7] and not on [c8]. One can also learn how to play with White against these structures by studying these games.} (13. g3 Rh8 {and so on.}) 13... f5 $1 {Now Black has got free flowing play.} 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Bd3 Bc8 $1 {The bishop is dead on [b7], so it has to be rerouted.} 16. Kg2 Nf6 17. Ne4 {And here, Black overpushes with his next move.} Nh5 $6 {[%csl Rh5]} ({This is not necessary at all as it is leading nowhere. Instead,} 17... Qd7 18. Nxf6+ Rxf6 19. Ng1 Qf7 {, or 17...Bd7 18.Nxf6+ Qxf6 19.Be4 Rac8= .}) 18. Bd2 Bd7 19. Kh1 Ne7 $6 (19... Nf6 {accepting the mistake and retreating is the way to go.}) 20. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gh4g6,Gc1h6]} Bh3 21. Rg1 {Now Black's position is simply decaying.} Bd7 22. Be3 (22. f4 $1 {Opening up is the best way to punish Black's play, as all of White's pieces are well positioned to poke the black king.} exf4 23. g4 Nf6 24. Nf2 {+- and with [g5] coming, White is crushing Black.}) 22... Qe8 23. Rde1 {Somehow, Petrosian still keeps shuffling his pieces instead of going for the kill.} Qf7 24. Qc2 Kh8 25. Nd2 Nf5 26. Nxf5 ({Slowly, the advantage is disappearing. Better would have been} 26. Ndf3 {± .}) 26... gxf5 $2 (26... Bxf5 {is required.}) 27. g4 $1 e4 (27... fxg4 28. Bg6 {+-}) 28. gxh5 f4 29. Rxg7 $1 {White is again winning.} Qxg7 30. Rg1 Qe5 31. Nf3 $1 exd3 (31... exf3 32. Bd2 {+-}) 32. Nxe5 $4 ({Perhaps Petrosian missed the sequence arising after} 32. Qxd3 {. Hard to explain the blunder.} Bf5 33. Nxe5 Bxd3 34. Bd4 dxe5 35. Bxe5+ Kh7 36. Rg7+ Kh8 37. Rxc7+ Kg8 38. Rg7+ Kh8 39. Rxa7+ Kg8 40. Rg7+ Kh8 41. Rg3+ Kh7 42. Rxd3 Rxa2 43. Kg2 {+- .}) 32... dxc2 33. Bd4 dxe5 34. Bxe5+ Kh7 35. Rg7+ {Due to the [c2]-pawn, White is unable to make use of the discovered threats.} Kh8 36. Rf7+ Kg8 37. Rg7+ Kh8 38. Rg6+ Kh7 39. Rg7+ {One of the first top-level games in the Hippopotamus structure. Classics!} 1/2-1/2

