{After the 12th game, Spassky again comes back to the Hippo structure. Like I mentioned before, even to see the Hippo structure once in a World Championship is a rare sight, but here Spassky repeats once again, having full faith in the system.} 1. d4 g6 2. e4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. Be2 e6 5. c3 {Petrosian places the pawn on [c3] in this game instead of [c4].} Nd7 6. O-O Ne7 7. Nbd2 b6 8. a4 a6 {[%cal Gc8b7] This is necessary, and next, the bishop is going to land on [b7], completing the Hippo setup.} (8... Bb7 9. a5) 9. Re1 Bb7 {[%cal Gb7h1,Gg7a1]} 10. Bd3 O-O 11. Nc4 Qe8 {Spassky is going the creative way with his next moves.} (11... Nf6 {, keeping an eye on the [e4]-pawn is one of Black's best possibilities:} 12. e5 dxe5 13. Ncxe5 c5 {.}) 12. Bd2 f6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb6,Gd6,Ge6,Gf6,Gg6] Haha, yeah, the Hippopotamus Defense often leads to funny-looking positions. All of Black's pawns sit on the third rank a6, [b6], [d6], [e6], [f6], [g6], except for the c- and h-pawns. Despite engines claiming a significant advantage for White, they often struggle to find a clear breakthrough, which proves how complex and resilient the setup actually is. This is one of those cases where human understanding differs from engine evaluation. The position might look passive, but it's full of hidden counterplay.} 13. Qe2 Kh8 {Looks like it is very hard to break Black.} 14. Kh1 Qf7 15. Ng1 {[%cal Gf2f4] Unable to find a proper plan, Petrosian retracts his knight to push [f4], but Black challenges the center before [f4] arrives.} e5 16. dxe5 fxe5 {Already here, Black's position is preferable with nicely placed pieces and a stable pawn structure.} 17. f3 Nc5 {[%csl Rd3]} 18. Ne3 Qe8 {[%cal Gc5a4]} (18... d5 {, the best time to break open.} 19. exd5 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 {and Black has a comfortable game.}) 19. Bc2 a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gc5]} 20. Nh3 Bc8 21. Nf2 Be6 22. Qd1 Qf7 {[%csl Rb3]} 23. Ra3 {Keeping an eye on the [b3]-square.} Bd7 24. Nd3 Nxd3 25. Bxd3 Bh6 26. Bc4 Qg7 27. Re2 Ng8 (27... Bf4 {is the best chance to create play on the kingside with ...[g5], ...[Rf6], and so on.}) 28. Bxg8 Rxg8 29. Nd5 Bxd2 30. Rxd2 Be6 {[%cal Gg7c7] Although Black is better, he is unable to break through, and the game ends in a draw after a couple of moves.} 31. b4 Qf7 32. Qe2 Ra7 33. Ra1 Rf8 34. b5 Raa8 35. Qe3 Rab8 36. Rf1 Qg7 37. Qd3 Rf7 38. Kg1 Rbf8 39. Ne3 g5 40. Rdf2 h5 41. c4 Qg6 42. Nd5 Rg8 43. Qe3 Kh7 44. Qd2 Rgg7 45. Qe3 Kg8 46. Rd2 Kh7 47. Rdf2 Rf8 48. Qd2 Rgf7 49. Qe3 1/2-1/2

