{Tony Miles was known for his creative and offbeat opening choices, and his famous e4 a6 game against Karpov (European Team Championship,1980) is a perfect example of his daring style. Given his tendency to experiment with hypermodern setups, it's no surprise that he was also a frequent practitioner of the Hippopotamus Defense.} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 3. a3 g6 {As I mentioned before, we get the Hippo structure from so many openings, and this is one of them.} 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 Ne7 6. Nf3 Bb7 7. Bd3 d6 8. O-O Nd7 {[%csl Gb6,Gb7,Gd6,Gd7,Ge6,Ge7,Gg6,Gg7] Completing the setup.} 9. Re1 h6 {[%cal Gg6g5] Black keeps the option of ...[g5] by this move order.} 10. h3 {I'm not sure about this pawn push, as it gives a target for Black to roll with ...[g5]-[g4] and use [h3] as a hook.} a6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb6,Gd6,Ge6,Gg6,Gh6] Once again, almost all the pawns sit on the 3rd rank. :} 11. Be3 g5 {Vaccating the [g6]-square for the [e7]-knight. Apart from ...[g4] ideas in the future, it does free some space for the pieces.} 12. Rc1 c5 {Containing the queenside.} 13. d5 Ng6 {[%csl Re5] Now Black heads towards the [e5]-square.} 14. Bc2 {White drifts away from ...[Ne5] ideas, but he misses an important point.} (14. b4 {is the best way to create some play on the queenside and not end up passive like in the game.} Nde5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 {and the game continues.}) 14... Qe7 (14... Bxc3 $1 {is a typical positional idea to damage White's pawn structure and close the game with ...[e5]. Unfortunately, Black misses this chance.} 15. bxc3 {, White is not able to interpose with [dxe6] due to the attack on the [e1]-rook;} e5 {⩱ .}) 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Rcd1 {[%cal Gd1d7]} Nde5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Bd3 $6 (18. Ne2 {is necessary, preparing [f4] and not allowing Black to conquer the dark squares.} Qf6 19. Rf1 Nf4 (19... Bxb2 20. f4 {+-}) 20. g3 $1 Nxe2+ (20... Nxh3+ $4 21. Kg2 g4 22. f3 {+-}) 21. Qxe2 exd5 22. cxd5 Qg7 {with a complex game.}) 18... Qf6 {[%cal Gf6b2,Gg6f4] Now, White is not able to shift his [c3]-knight due to the hanging pawn on [b2].} 19. Na4 {[%csl Rb6]} Rab8 20. Nxb6 Bc8 {[%csl Rb6] Black has completely taken over.} 21. Na4 (21. Nxc8 Rxb2 $1) 21... Bd7 22. Nc3 Rb3 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Gf8b8]} 23. Rb1 Rfb8 24. Nd1 exd5 25. cxd5 Nf4 (25... g4 26. hxg4 Qh4 27. g3 Bxg3 28. fxg3 Qxg3+ 29. Kf1 Rxd3 $1 30. Qxd3 Bb5 {-+}) 26. Bxf4 gxf4 27. Bc2 Rxh3 $3 {The final touch!!} 28. gxh3 Kh8 (28... f3 {-+}) 29. f3 Rg8+ 30. Kh1 Qh4 {A beautiful game by Miles.} 0-1

