1. d4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. Bf4 d6 4. e4 {We get to the Modern from different move orders.} c5 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Qd2 c5 {is the recommendation in the course. 6...Bg4 is also another interesting plan, exerting pressure on the [f3]-knight.}) 5. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4] Without the white knight placed on [c3], White has this extra option of sticking the pawn on [d4] with [c3].} (5. dxc5 Bxb2) 5... cxd4 (5... Nf6 $1 {is necessary to keep the tension and not allow White to develop the knight to [c3].} 6. dxc5 {(6.Nbd2 cxd4 and now that the knight is on [d2], we can exchange on [d4]. 7.cxd4 O-O 8.Be2 ( 8.Bd3? e5! A typical tactic and now Black is much better. ) 8...b6 9.O-O Bb7 10.Qb1 Nbd7= with a solid game. )} O-O $1 {Development in the key!} (6... Nxe4 $4 7. Qa4+ {+-}) 7. cxd6 (7. Nbd2 dxc5 8. h3 Nc6) 7... Nxe4 8. dxe7 Qxe7 {. By this operation, White remains with an extra pawn, but he is way behind in development, and Black uses this fact to create counterplay!} 9. Be2 Rd8 10. Qc1 {(10.Qc2 Nf6 and the queen is certainly misplaced on [c2]. )} Nf6 11. Qe3 Be6 12. Bg5 (12. O-O Nd5 13. Qc1 Nxf4 14. Qxf4 Bxa2) 12... h6 $1 13. Bxf6 {(13.Bxh6 Ng4 ∓)} Qxf6 14. O-O Nc6 15. Nbd2 Re8 16. Ne4 Qd8 17. Rfd1 Qc7 18. Nd6 Re7 {∞ and the bishop pair combined with active pieces provide Black good compensation.}) 6. cxd4 {[%cal Gb1c3] Now, White gets to bring his knight on [c3].} Bg4 7. Nbd2 {A passive square for the knight.} (7. Bb5+ {is the best move aiming for accomplishing development with tempo.} Nc6 8. Nc3 (8. O-O Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Bxd4 10. Na3 Bxb2 11. Rad1 {and Black's position is dangerous.}) 8... a6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Bxd4 12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 {⩲ .}) 7... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. d5 $6 (8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 Qb6 10. Be3 {and White is able to hold the pawns.}) 8... Nd4 9. Bd3 Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 $2 ({Weakening the position of the king in turn and now Black takes over. Better was} 10. Nxf3 Bxb2 11. Rb1 Bc3+ 12. Ke2 {.}) 10... Bd7 (10... Bh3 {⩱}) 11. Qb3 Nf6 12. Be3 O-O {[%csl Re1]} 13. O-O-O e6 14. Kb1 exd5 15. exd5 a5 $17 {White is busted on the queenside.} 16. Ne4 a4 ({This is a slower approach.} 16... Nxe4 17. fxe4 b5 {-+ kills right there.}) 17. Qb6 Qxb6 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Bxb6 a3 20. b3 Rfc8 21. Rc1 Bh3 {[%cal Gh3g2,Gg2d5]} 22. Rhd1 $2 (22. Rhg1 {is the last chance to stay in the game.}) 22... Be5 23. Be3 Bg2 {The rest is not that important.} 24. f4 Bb2 25. Rxc8+ Rxc8 26. Bc2 Bf3 27. Rd3 Be4 28. Rd2 f5 29. Re2 Bxd5 30. Bc1 Bxc1 31. Kxc1 Be4 32. Kd1 Bf3 0-1

