1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. f4 Nf6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. d5 Ne7 ({This knight move is passive compared to} 8... Nd4 {, but it's definitely possible. 8...Nd4 is the move we analyzed in the theoretical section.}) 9. fxe5 {Releasing the tension is not the best way to continue.} (9. Kh1 {, moving away from the [a7]-[g1] diagonal makes a lot of sense. For example, in some lines Black will break with ...[c6] and have the option of ...[Qb6]+;} exf4 10. Bxf4 {⩲ .}) 9... dxe5 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8]} (10. Nxe5 c6 $1 {is the point.} 11. Bg5 (11. dxc6 $4 Qd4+ {+ -+}) 11... cxd5 12. Bxf6 Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Bxf6 {.}) 10... h6 $1 11. Bh4 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4] Keeping some practical chances to keep the game going. Practical chess > correct chess.} (11... c6 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. Nd5 Qd6) 12. Bc4 Qd6 {[%cal Gd6b6,Gb6g1,Gb6b2]} (12... Nf4 {and ...[Bg4] is another idea.}) 13. Kh1 a6 {[%csl Rb5]} 14. a4 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1]} 15. a5 Nf4 {I like Black's position here, as he has free flowing moves, though the computer disagrees with me.} 16. Ne2 $6 ({Better is} 16. Qe1 g5 {.}) 16... g5 17. Be1 Neg6 (17... c6 $1 {Now it's the right time to strike, as White's pieces are not connected properly:} 18. dxc6 Qxc6 19. Bd3 f5 {∓ .}) 18. Ra4 {[%cal Ge1b4]} Qd7 19. Ra3 f5 20. exf5 $6 (20. Ng3 {is more stubborn.} Nxg2 $1 21. Kxg2 fxe4 22. Nxe4 Bxf3+ 23. Raxf3 Qg4+ 24. Kh1 Qxe4 25. Qd3 {and White holds.}) 20... Bxf5 21. Ng3 e4 22. Ng1 Bg4 23. Qd2 Nh4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4,Gg4,Gh4]} ({With his menancing pieces, Black takes over the game.} 23... Rae8 {, protecting the pawn on [e4], is also possible.}) 24. Rf2 (24. Nxe4 Nhxg2 25. Nc5 Qd6 26. Nxb7 Qg6 {looks scary for White, though the computer keeps on defending.}) 24... Rae8 25. Re3 Bf5 26. N1e2 Bg6 27. Nc3 Kh8 28. Ncxe4 Qa4 $5 (28... Qe7 29. Bd3 Bd4 {-+ is winning on the spot.}) 29. b3 Qa1 30. c3 Qxa5 31. h3 Qb6 32. b4 a5 33. Nc5 Rxe3 34. Qxe3 Re8 35. Qc1 Qd6 36. Ne2 Nxd5 37. Nxb7 Qe5 38. Nc5 Ne3 39. Bb5 Re7 40. Bd2 Nexg2 41. Rxg2 Qd5 42. Qg1 Qxd2 43. bxa5 Qd5 44. c4 Qxg2+ 45. Qxg2 Nxg2 46. Ng3 Nf4 47. a6 Re1+ 48. Kh2 Bd4 {[%cal Gd4g1]} 0-1

