{This game was played in the Qatar Masters against the upcoming strong IM Harshit Raja, who is right now a well-known commentator and the 69th GM of India. Let's dive into the game.} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. Nc3 a6 5. a4 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7e6,Gg8e7,Gb8d7]} ({Aiming for the Hippo structure.} 5... Nf6 {is the direction suggested in the theoretical part.}) 6. Bc4 e6 {[%csl Rc4]} 7. Bg5 (7. h4 h6 8. d5 Bxc3+ $1 {Damaging the pawn structure.} 9. bxc3 e5 {leads to a complex game.}) {8...e5?! blocks the [g7]-bishop and is not in time to carry out the ...[f5] break in a desired way: 9.h5 g5 10.Nd2 f5 11.exf5 Bxf5 . It would be ideal to take back with the g-pawn, but it is absent here, which is a major drawback. 12.Nde4 ± and White has firm control.} 7... Ne7 8. Qd2 (8. d5 $1 {is the best move here, immediately taking some responsible action before Black stabilizes:} e5 9. Nd2 h6 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 Nd7 12. h3 {⩲ . This is a nice, typical idea, with the follow-up of [g4], where White effectively sabotages Black's play on the kingside. Additionally, White retains the flexibility to castle queenside with [Qe2], ensuring a strong and dynamic position.}) 8... h6 9. Be3 (9. Bh4 Nd7 10. O-O g5 11. Bg3 Ng6 {⇆ and the bishop on [g3] is quite dull.}) 9... Nd7 (9... d5 $5 {is possible.} 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O (11. e5 c5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Bxc5 Nd7 14. Bd6 Nc8 {and the [e5]-pawn drops.}) 11... dxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13. Nxe4 Nbc6 {followed by ...[Nf5], and Black is doing fine.}) 10. O-O Bb7 11. h3 Nf6 {[%csl Re4]} (11... Kf8 {is another plan to secure the king on [h7] since we cannot castle kingside due to less support over the [h6]-pawn.}) 12. Bd3 $6 {White does not want to commit any responsible move. He shuffles here and there, losing the momentum.} (12. d5 $1 {Once again, this ambitious move is required to shut down the [b7]-bishop.} e5 13. Nh2 (13. Ne1 g5) 13... g5 (13... Nh5 14. Be2) 14. Bd3 Ng6 15. a5 b5 16. Ne2 {± followed by [c4], and White cruises through the queenside.}) 12... d5 (12... c5 $1 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rfe1 Qc7 15. Bf4 e5 {∞}) 13. e5 Ne4 14. Qe2 (14. Qe1 $1 {is a better placement so that after ...[c5], we cannot trap the [d3]-bishop by ...[c4] as in the case of the queen placed on [e2];} c5 15. a5 {⩲ .}) 14... c5 15. dxc5 (15. a5 Nxc3 16. bxc3 c4 {-+ is the drawback of the queen on [e2].}) 15... Nxc5 16. a5 Nc6 (16... Nxd3 17. cxd3 bxa5 18. Bc5) 17. b4 $2 ({White loses the thread.} 17. Rfd1 $1 {gives White some plus.} Nxa5 {(17...Nxd3 18.Rxd3 Nxa5 19.Ne4 is the point of placing the rook on the d-file: 19...O-O 20.Nf6+ Bxf6 21.exf6 +- . )} 18. Bxg6 $3 Nc4 {± and White is still much better, but the game continues. And if 18...fxg6 19.Rxa5 bxa5 20.Bxc5 ± .}) 17... Nxd3 18. Qxd3 $2 (18. cxd3 bxa5 19. bxa5 d4 20. Ne4 Nxe5 {⩱}) 18... Nxb4 19. Qd2 bxa5 20. Bc5 Rc8 $19 21. Na4 d4 $1 22. Ra3 d3 23. Bxb4 axb4 24. Rxd3 Qa5 25. Nb2 O-O $19 26. Re1 Rc3 27. Nd4 Qd5 28. Nf3 Rxd3 29. Nxd3 a5 30. Ra1 Rc8 31. Rb1 Qa2 0-1

