{Before this game, I had never played the Modern/Pirc against higher-rated opponents. It was always a weapon I experimented with against lower-rated players, where I felt more comfortable testing new ideas. However, for the first time, I decided to challenge myself and see how it holds up against a stronger opponent. I knew that if the setup is sound, it should be effective at all levels, but I had never put it to the test in such a high-stakes game. To my delight, the game played out well, and I managed to navigate the complexities successfully.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} O-O 6. Nf3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] This resembles our usual setups.} 7. Bd3 {White has played natural moves so far, placing the pieces in ideal positions. The only drawback is that he allowed ...[b5] now, which totally changes the dynamics of the game.} ({For} 7. a4 Nc6 {, check the theoretical part for more details.}) 7... b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 8. e5 (8. Qd2 {is a natural option, and here we can respond with} Bb7 9. Bh6 {(9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Nh5)} b4 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Bxd5 12. h4 {. White tries to speed up his attack on the kingside, but we are in time to stabilize after} Nc6 13. h5 Bxf3 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Qh6+ Kf6 17. Qf4+ Kg7 {and a repetition!}) 8... dxe5 9. dxe5 Nd5 {Black has a comfortable game.} 10. Bd2 Bb7 11. Ne4 Nd7 {[%csl Re5]} (11... Nb6 {keeps some chances to play for more:} 12. O-O N8d7 13. e6 f5 $1) 12. e6 f5 13. exd7 fxe4 14. Bxe4 Bxb2 15. O-O $1 (15. Rb1 Nc3 {-+}) 15... Bxa1 $6 {It was hasty to capture the exchange and, in return, gifted White some play. Although there's nothing wrong with it, and I am not worse in any way.} (15... Qxd7 16. Rb1 Bg7 {with a preferable position for Black.}) 16. Qxa1 Qxd7 17. Bh6 Rf6 18. Rd1 Rd8 19. Ne5 Qe6 20. Re1 Qd6 (20... Qb6 21. Ng4) 21. Ng4 Bc6 ({Better was} 21... Kf7 {.}) 22. Rd1 Qe6 23. Re1 Qd6 24. Rd1 Qe6 25. Re1 Qd6 {And we repeated. An effortless draw, I must say!} 1/2-1/2

